  var epithelialTissueQuestions = [
    {question:"Epithelia are classified by cell shape and number of layers. Which classification correctly describes a 'stratified squamous non-keratinized epithelium' and gives an example location?",options:{A:"Multiple layers of cells; all layers contain cylindrical cells; found in the ureter",B:"Multiple layers of cells; surface cells are flat (squamous) and retain their nuclei (non-keratinized — no stratum corneum); found in the esophagus, oral mucosa, vagina, and cornea — areas subject to friction with need for continuous surface renewal",C:"Single layer of flat cells with prominent nuclei; found in the alveoli and blood vessels",D:"Multiple layers; surface cells are anucleate; basal cells are cuboidal; found in the thick skin of the palms"},correct:"B",explanation:"Stratified squamous non-keratinized (SSNK) epithelium: Multiple cell layers with flat nucleated surface cells. Found where there is mechanical abrasion but continuous moisture: esophagus, oral cavity (buccal mucosa, gingiva, hard palate, tongue), pharynx, vagina, ectocervix, cornea (transparent, requires moisture). The cells from basal (cuboidal/columnar stem cells) through intermediate (polygonal, desmosomes) to superficial (flat, nucleated) layers are all viable. Contrast: Stratified squamous keratinized (SSK) — surface cells anucleate, filled with keratin (stratum corneum) — skin epidermis. Simple squamous — one layer of flat nucleated cells (endothelium, mesothelium, alveoli). Pseudostratified columnar — all cells touch basal lamina but not all reach the surface (nuclei at different heights — 'pseudostratified') — respiratory tract, epididymis.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Epithelial classification"},
    {question:"Tight junctions (zonula occludens) form the most apical component of the junctional complex in simple columnar epithelia. Which molecular components form tight junctions and what are their two critical functions?",options:{A:"Formed by E-cadherin and vinculin; functions: maintain cell polarity and provide tensile strength against mechanical stress",B:"Formed by claudins (23+ isoforms; form the backbone of the TJ strand), occludin (modulates permeability), junctional adhesion molecules (JAMs), and scaffolding proteins (ZO-1, ZO-2, ZO-3 that link TJ to actin cytoskeleton); two functions: (1) Barrier/gate function — regulate paracellular ion and solute permeability (claudin composition determines selectivity — e.g., claudin-2 forms cation-selective water channels, claudin-3/4 restrict permeability); (2) Fence function — maintain membrane protein polarity by preventing lateral diffusion between apical and basolateral domains",C:"Formed only by occludin; claudins provide additional reinforcement in the gut only; TJs function exclusively as barriers to bacterial entry",D:"Tight junctions are identical in all epithelia; claudin composition does not vary"},correct:"B",explanation:"Tight junctions (TJs, zonula occludens): Located at the very apex of the lateral membrane, forming a continuous belt around the cell. Molecular components: Claudins (24 human isoforms): 4-TM proteins, each ~23 kDa, with two extracellular loops that form homophilic and heterophilic interactions with claudins on adjacent cells, creating the TJ 'strands' (visible as continuous strands on freeze-fracture EM). Claudin isoform expression determines paracellular permeability: claudin-2 forms cation-selective channels (leaky TJ — kidney proximal tubule, intestinal crypt); claudin-3, -4, -5, -11, -18 restrict permeability (tight barriers — BBB has claudin-5 and -3). Occludin: single 4-TM protein, modulates TJ regulation. JAM-A, -B, -C: Ig superfamily, single-pass TM, involved in leukocyte transmigration and polarity. ZO-1/2/3 (MAGUK proteins): cytoplasmic scaffolds linking claudins to actin. TJ functions: (1) Gate — paracellular barrier (prevents unrestricted passage of ions and molecules via intercellular space); (2) Fence — prevents mixing of apical (glycocalyx, transporters, enzymes) with basolateral membrane proteins (Na+/K+-ATPase, growth factor receptors). Clinical: Helicobacter pylori CagA disrupts ZO-1/occludin → TJ dysfunction → gastric mucosal permeability. Cholera toxin disrupts TJs (Vibrio cholerae zonula occludens toxin — ZOT).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Tight junctions"},
    {question:"Adherens junctions (zonula adherens) are located just basolateral to tight junctions. What are their molecular components and main function?",options:{A:"Formed by integrins and fibronectin; their main function is cell-matrix adhesion rather than cell-cell adhesion",B:"Formed by E-cadherin (the transmembrane adhesion protein, a calcium-dependent cell-cell adhesion molecule), which connects via its cytoplasmic tail to beta-catenin (and p120 catenin) → alpha-catenin bridges to the actin cytoskeleton (via vinculin, EPLIN, afadin); main function: mechanical cell-cell cohesion ('belt desmosome' distributing tension) and cell signaling (E-cadherin/beta-catenin signaling pathway); E-cadherin is a tumor suppressor (loss promotes epithelial-mesenchymal transition)",C:"Formed by desmoglein and desmocollin; identical to desmosomes but located more apically",D:"Formed by connexins in a belt around the cell; allow diffusion of small molecules between cells in addition to providing mechanical adhesion"},correct:"B",explanation:"Adherens junctions (AJs, zonula adherens): E-cadherin (epithelial cadherin): Type I classical cadherin, single-pass TM glycoprotein with 5 extracellular cadherin domains (EC1-5) that form Ca2+-dependent homodimeric (cis-dimer) and trans-dimeric interactions with E-cadherin on the opposite cell surface. Cytoplasmic tail binds: p120-catenin (regulates E-cadherin stability, prevents endocytosis) and beta-catenin (which in turn binds alpha-catenin). Alpha-catenin: 'molecular clutch' between E-cadherin complex and actin cytoskeleton (binds F-actin via vinculin under tension). AJ function: belt-like mechanical coupling transmitting contractile forces (actomyosin contraction) between cells → apical constriction during morphogenesis. Signaling: E-cadherin sequesters beta-catenin from the cytoplasm (limiting availability for Wnt nuclear signaling). E-cadherin loss (CDH1 mutations, promoter methylation, EMT) releases beta-catenin → Wnt signaling activation + loss of cell cohesion. CDH1 germline mutations → hereditary diffuse gastric cancer and lobular breast cancer (prophylactic gastrectomy recommended). EMT: E-cadherin → N-cadherin switch ('cadherin switching') is a hallmark of mesenchymal transition.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Adherens junctions"},
    {question:"Desmosomes (maculae adherentes) provide mechanical strength against shearing forces. What are their distinctive molecular components and ultrastructural appearance?",options:{A:"Formed by E-cadherin and alpha-catenin; ultrastructurally appear as dense plaques with intermediate filament bundles attached",B:"Formed by desmoglein 1-4 and desmocollin 1-3 (desmosomal cadherins, calcium-dependent, transmembrane, heterotypic trans-dimers); cytoplasmic plaque: desmoplakin (bridges to intermediate filaments) + plakoglobin (gamma-catenin) + plakophilins 1-3 (regulate size); attached to keratin IFs in epithelial cells (or desmin in cardiac muscle); ultrastructure: symmetric dense plaques with midline in the intercellular space, IF loops attached at each plaque ('rivet' appearance)",C:"Formed by connexins; allow passage of small molecules between cells; ultrastructurally appear as gap junction channels visible in freeze-fracture EM",D:"Formed by integrins (alpha6beta4) connecting the cell to the basement membrane; contain laminin-332 as the extracellular ligand"},correct:"B",explanation:"Desmosomes: Transmembrane core: Desmoglein (Dsg 1, 2, 3, 4) and Desmocollin (Dsc 1, 2, 3) — desmosomal cadherins (calcium-dependent). In the intercellular space, Dsg and Dsc form asymmetric trans-dimers (Dsg from one cell with Dsc from the adjacent cell). Extracellular midline dense plaque (midpoint of the 25-35 nm intercellular space). Cytoplasmic plaque (inner dense plaque = outer dense plaque + inner plaque): Plakoglobin (gamma-catenin) and plakophilins (1, 2, 3 — promote lateral clustering and IF attachment) bind to the Dsg/Dsc cytoplasmic tails. Desmoplakin (outer plaque component): large plakin-family protein that bridges between the plakoglobin/plakophilin complex and the intermediate filament network (keratin in epithelial cells, desmin in cardiac muscle). Ultrastructure: 'zipper' appearance with electron-dense plaques on each cell and IF loops. Clinical importance: Pemphigus vulgaris (anti-Dsg3/1 IgG4 → acantholysis); Pemphigus foliaceus (anti-Dsg1 → only superficial acantholysis, no mucosal involvement because Dsg3 compensates in oral mucosa but not in skin epidermis where Dsg1 predominates). Arrhythmogenic cardiomyopathy (ARVC): desmoplakin, plakophilin-2, desmoglein-2, junctional plakoglobin mutations → cardiac desmosome dysfunction → fibrofatty replacement of myocardium → ventricular arrhythmia, sudden death.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Desmosomes"},
    {question:"Hemidesmosomes attach epithelial cells to the basement membrane. What is their composition, and what disease results from their dysfunction?",options:{A:"Hemidesmosomes are identical to desmosomes but oriented toward the basement membrane; they contain E-cadherin as the transmembrane component",B:"Hemidesmosomes contain: integrin alpha6beta4 (transmembrane component, binds laminin-332 in the lamina lucida), collagen XVII (BP180, transmembrane collagen, single-pass), BPAG1e (BP230/dystonin — plakin family, links to keratin IF network), and plectin (links to keratin and vimentin IFs); the extracellular laminin-332 (formerly laminin-5) anchors to the lamina densa via anchoring fibrils (type VII collagen); autoantibodies to BP180 or BP230 → bullous pemphigoid (subepidermal blistering)",C:"Hemidesmosomes contain tight junction proteins (claudins) oriented vertically toward the basement membrane instead of laterally between cells",D:"Hemidesmosomes are found only in smooth muscle cells where they anchor smooth muscle to the ECM via alpha-smooth muscle actin"},correct:"B",explanation:"Hemidesmosomes: Basement membrane zone (BMZ) component linking basal keratinocytes to the lamina lucida of the basement membrane. Components: (1) Integrin alpha6beta4: transmembrane, binds laminin-332 (formerly laminin-5) in the extracellular space; the beta4 subunit has an unusually long cytoplasmic tail (~1000 aa) that interacts with plectin and BPAG1. (2) Collagen XVII (BP180/BPAG2): type II transmembrane collagen; ectodomain projects into the lamina lucida and binds laminin-332 and collagen IV. (3) BP230 (BPAG1e): plakin protein; cytoplasmic, binds keratin IFs via its IF-binding domain. (4) Plectin: giant plakin, links IF to hemidesmosomes. Extracellular anchoring: laminin-332 (alpha3beta3gamma2 trimer) → lamina lucida anchoring filaments → lamina densa (collagen IV) → sub-basal dense plaque (collagen VII anchoring fibrils looping through the lamina densa into the papillary dermis). Clinical: Bullous pemphigoid (anti-BP180/BP230 IgG4): subepidermal blister at lamina lucida level. Epidermolysis bullosa: mutations: alpha6beta4 (EBA junctionalis), laminin-332 (Herlitz junctional EB, lethal), collagen XVII (EB), BP230. Collagen VII mutations → dystrophic EB (anchoring fibril defect).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Hemidesmosomes"},
    {question:"Microvilli are non-motile, actin-rich surface specializations that increase absorptive surface area. In which cells are they most abundant and what structural proteins support them?",options:{A:"Microvilli are most abundant in goblet cells; supported by a microtubule core with dynein arms",B:"Microvilli (brush border) are most abundant in small intestinal enterocytes and proximal tubule cells of the kidney; the F-actin core of each microvillus (25-30 actin filaments, barbed ends toward the tip) is stabilized by villin (actin-bundling, also severs actin under high Ca2+), espin, and fimbrin (plastin); the rootlets insert into the terminal web (a meshwork of actin and myosin IIA, spectrin) at the microvillus base; the microvillus core is also linked to the plasma membrane via myosin-1a; the surface is coated with a glycocalyx containing digestive enzymes (lactase, sucrase-isomaltase, aminopeptidase N, SGLT1/GLUT2 transporters)",C:"Microvilli are most abundant in hepatocytes, where they project into the space of Disse to facilitate lipoprotein uptake",D:"Microvilli in the intestine contain a microtubule core (9+2 arrangement) identical to cilia; they move in a coordinated wave pattern to propel intestinal contents"},correct:"B",explanation:"Microvilli (brush border): In the small intestine, enterocyte microvilli are the primary site of nutrient absorption. Each microvillus: ~1-3 microns tall, 0.1 micron diameter, with a core of 25-30 parallel F-actin filaments with their barbed (fast-growing) ends at the tip (membrane) and pointed ends extending into the terminal web. Actin-bundling proteins: villin (Ca2+-regulated, bundles at low [Ca2+], severs at high [Ca2+] — e.g., in microvilli disassembly during wound healing), espin (most mechanically critical bundler), fimbrin/plastin (bundles adjacent filaments tightly). Myosin-1a (single-headed, links actin core to plasma membrane). Terminal web: actin + myosin IIA + spectrin network at the microvillus base, linked to the zonula adherens. Glycocalyx: covers microvilli with a 0.5-1 micron fuzzy coat of membrane-anchored enzymes (disaccharidases, peptidases) and transporters. Lactase-phlorizin hydrolase (LPH) deficiency → lactose intolerance. Glucose/galactose-sodium co-transporter (SGLT1) actively transports glucose from intestinal lumen. Microvilli number: ~3000/enterocyte, increasing surface area ~600x. Intestinal microvillus inclusion disease (MVID): MYO5B or STX3 mutation → microvilli trafficking defect → microvilli inclusions inside cells, absent surface brush border.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Microvilli"},
    {question:"Cilia are microtubule-based, motile surface specializations that propel substances along epithelial surfaces. What is the molecular basis of ciliary motility?",options:{A:"Cilia contain F-actin filaments that generate force by ATP-dependent polymerization/depolymerization cycles; dynein plays no role in ciliary movement",B:"Cilia have a 9+2 axoneme: 9 peripheral doublet microtubules (A tubule + B tubule) + 2 central singlet microtubules connected by the central pair; outer dynein arms (ODA — generated force, fast beat) and inner dynein arms (IDA — waveform control) are attached at regular intervals on the A-tubule; nexin links (now called N-DRC) connect adjacent doublets; radial spokes connect A-tubule to central pair; dynein arms use ATP hydrolysis to slide adjacent doublets → constrained by nexin → sliding converts to bending",C:"Cilia motility is generated by kinesin motors (not dynein) moving along the outer doublets toward the minus end of microtubules",D:"The 9+2 axoneme is found only in sperm flagella; respiratory cilia have a 9+0 arrangement (no central pair) and rely on a different mechanism"},correct:"B",explanation:"Ciliary axoneme and motility: The '9+2' axoneme (in motile cilia and sperm flagella): 9 peripheral doublets (A-tubule: 13 protofilaments, closed; B-tubule: 10-11 protofilaments, open, attaches to A of adjacent doublet) + 2 central singlet microtubules (central pair, connected by bridges and surrounded by central pair projections). Dynein arms: Outer dynein arms (ODA): 3-headed dynein (DNAI1 heavy chain, DNAI2 intermediate chain, others) repeat every 24 nm; responsible for beat frequency (fast power stroke). Inner dynein arms (IDA): multiple species repeat over 96 nm; control waveform shape and coordination. Mechanism: Dynein arms on A-tubule walk toward the minus end of the adjacent B-tubule → adjacent doublets attempt to slide past each other → nexin-regulatory dynein complex (N-DRC) and radial spoke/central pair interaction converts sliding into a bending wave. Primary ciliary dyskinesia (PCD/Kartagener syndrome): mutations in ODA components (DNAI1, DNAI2, DNAAF1-6 — assembly factors) → immotile or dyskinetic cilia → bronchiectasis, sinusitis, situs inversus (~50%), male infertility (immotile sperm). Note: 9+0 arrangement (no central pair) is seen in PRIMARY (non-motile, sensory) cilia — found on virtually every differentiated somatic cell; they are signaling antennae (Hedgehog pathway sensing via SMO/PTCH1).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Cilia"},
    {question:"The basement membrane (basal lamina) underlies epithelial sheets. What are the major structural components of the basal lamina and how are they organized?",options:{A:"The basal lamina consists mainly of fibronectin type III repeats and collagen I; collagen IV is only found in the basal lamina of kidney glomeruli",B:"The basal lamina has two layers: lamina lucida (electron-lucent, contains laminin, nidogen/entactin, and osteopontin) and lamina densa (electron-dense, contains collagen IV polymers — self-assembles via NC1 domains; also contains heparan sulfate proteoglycans perlecan/agrin). Laminin (alpha-beta-gamma heterotrimer, 'cross-shaped' molecule) binds integrins and dystroglycan; nidogen bridges laminin to collagen IV; perlecan binds FGF and VEGF",C:"The basal lamina is equivalent to the reticular lamina; they are different names for the same structure",D:"The basal lamina contains type I collagen fibrils that self-assemble into a mesh; laminin is found only in the adult kidney glomerulus"},correct:"B",explanation:"Basement membrane (BM) structure: The BM is a specialized ECM sheet (40-120 nm) underlying all epithelia, endothelia, muscle, and Schwann cells. Electron microscopy: Lamina lucida (lucent, 20-40 nm): contains the short arm of laminin (attached to cell surface via integrin alpha6beta4 and dystroglycan), nidogen/entactin (small, connecting protein), and agrin. Lamina densa (dense, 20-60 nm): contains the collagen IV network (alpha1-alpha6 chains, tissue-specific combinations; NC1 domains mediate chain association into heterotrimers; 7S domains mediate end-to-end tetramer formation → 2D lattice/gel — the structural scaffold of the BM), heparan sulfate proteoglycans (perlecan/HSPG2, agrin — bind FGF2, VEGF), nidogen (bridges laminin and collagen IV networks). Below the lamina densa (reticular lamina, not part of the basal lamina per se): additional ECM produced by underlying connective tissue cells (collagen III reticulin fibers, fibronectin). Clinical: Alport syndrome (X-linked hereditary nephritis): mutations in COL4A5 (alpha5) chain → defective GBM collagen IV alpha3-alpha4-alpha5 trimer → progressive renal failure, sensorineural hearing loss, ocular defects. Goodpasture syndrome: anti-GBM IgG against the NC1 domain of alpha3(IV) collagen → rapidly progressive GN and pulmonary hemorrhage.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Basement membrane"},
    {question:"Transitional epithelium (urothelium) lines the urinary tract. What unique features allow it to accommodate changes in volume?",options:{A:"Transitional epithelium is identical to stratified squamous epithelium; it simply thins as the bladder fills",B:"Urothelium is a pseudostratified epithelium; it thickens when the bladder is full due to cell proliferation",C:"Transitional epithelium has 3-7 cell layers with distinctive large, binucleate or polyploid superficial 'umbrella cells' (facet cells) with a scalloped apical surface; when distended, cells flatten and layer count decreases; umbrella cells contain unique fusiform vesicles (discoidal vesicles) whose membrane fuses with the apical plasma membrane to accommodate increased surface area; the luminal surface of umbrella cells is covered by uroplakins (UPIa, UPIb, UPII, UPIIIa/b — tetraspanins forming crystalline hexagonal plaques called urothelial plaques) that form an impermeable barrier to urine",C:"Transitional epithelium lacks a basement membrane, which allows it to expand and contract freely",D:"The cells of the transitional epithelium contain contractile proteins (actin + myosin) that actively change the cell's shape in response to osmotic signals from urine"},correct:"C",explanation:"Urothelium (transitional epithelium): Lines the renal pelves, ureters, bladder, and proximal urethra — all subject to changes in luminal volume. Layers: Empty/contracted state: 5-7 layers — basal cells (cuboidal, attached to BM), intermediate cells (pear-shaped, polygonal), and large superficial umbrella cells (binucleate, polyploid — up to 8N, wide, rounded). Distended state: 2-3 cell layers — all cells flatten dramatically as the lumen expands. Umbrella cell specializations: (1) Discoidal/fusiform vesicles (DFVs): membrane reservoirs in the subapical cytoplasm that are constitutively exocytosed into the apical plasma membrane when the bladder fills, allowing ~70% increase in apical surface area. Recycled by endocytosis when bladder empties. (2) Uroplakin plaques: 2D hexagonal crystalline arrays of uroplakin proteins (UPIa/UPIb tetraspanin heterodimers + UPII/UPIIIa heterodimers) covering ~90% of the umbrella cell apical surface. Uroplakins create an asymmetric unit membrane (AUM) that is highly impermeable to ions, water, and urea. Clinical: Loss of uroplakin function → urothelial permeability → painful bladder syndrome/interstitial cystitis. Urothelial carcinoma (TCC): flat high-grade → uroplakin loss + CK20+.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Transitional epithelium"},
    {question:"Goblet cells are unicellular mucous glands interspersed among epithelial cells. In which epithelia are they found, and what do they produce?",options:{A:"Goblet cells are found exclusively in the respiratory tract; they produce hyaluronic acid",B:"Goblet cells are found in the small and large intestinal epithelium (columnar epithelium), respiratory epithelium (pseudostratified ciliated columnar), and conjunctiva; they produce mucins (glycoproteins) — predominantly MUC2 in the intestine (gel-forming mucin, forms the inner adherent mucus layer in the colon that excludes bacteria) and MUC5AC/MUC5B in the respiratory tract; mucin is stored in apical secretory granules (TAS2R — bitter taste receptors — stimulate mucin secretion); goblet cells are absent from squamous epithelia and the urothelium",C:"Goblet cells are found only in the duodenum and proximal jejunum; they decrease in number toward the colon",D:"Goblet cells are always accompanied by Paneth cells; they cannot be found without Paneth cells in the same epithelium"},correct:"B",explanation:"Goblet cells: Interspersed among columnar epithelial cells in specific locations: (1) Small intestine: relatively sparse (fewer than in the colon); increase in number from duodenum to ileum. (2) Large intestine (colon): most abundant; high density of goblet cells is a characteristic feature; secrete MUC2 (gel-forming mucin). (3) Respiratory tract: pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium of trachea and bronchi contain goblet cells that secrete MUC5AC. (4) Conjunctiva: goblet cells in the conjunctival epithelium produce MUC5AC for tear film stability. Absent from: stratified squamous epithelia (skin, esophagus, oral cavity, vagina), transitional epithelium, and most glandular epithelia. Histology: goblet cells have a distended, pale cytoplasm (mucin granules) that compresses the nucleus basally — 'wine glass' shape (hence 'goblet'). PAS and Alcian blue positive. Disease: Chronic bronchitis: goblet cell hyperplasia (more than 5 goblet cells/mm basement membrane, or goblet cells extending into bronchioles) → excessive mucus → 'productive cough' > 3 months/year for 2+ years. UC and CD: altered goblet cell number and mucin composition.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Goblet cells"},
    {question:"Paneth cells are specialized secretory cells located at the base of intestinal crypts in the small intestine. What do they secrete and what is their function?",options:{A:"Paneth cells secrete mucins (identical to goblet cells) and are found in both small and large intestine",B:"Paneth cells are located at the base of crypts of Lieberkuhn in the small intestine (most abundant in the ileum) and secrete antimicrobial peptides and proteins into the crypt lumen: defensins (alpha-defensins HD5, HD6 — kill bacteria by permeabilizing membranes), lysozyme (cleaves peptidoglycan), phospholipase A2 (sPLA2-IIA), and RegIIIgamma; they protect intestinal stem cells (LGR5+ cells, located immediately above Paneth cells in the crypt base) from pathogenic bacteria and provide niche signals (EGF, Delta-4 for Notch signaling, Wnt3a) for stem cell maintenance",C:"Paneth cells secrete digestive enzymes (lipase, amylase) identical to pancreatic acinar cells",D:"Paneth cells are found at the villus tips (not crypts) and release IgA into the intestinal lumen"},correct:"B",explanation:"Paneth cells: Pyramidal secretory cells with eosinophilic granules in the apical cytoplasm (large, refractile, PAS-positive), located at the very bottom of crypts of Lieberkuhn in the small intestine (most abundant in the ileum; also in some sites of ectopic small intestinal metaplasia, e.g., Barrett's esophagus). They are long-lived cells (~60 days) that do not migrate out of the crypt (unlike other intestinal epithelial cells which migrate up toward the villus tip over 3-5 days). Secretions (exocytosed in response to bacteria, bacterial products like LPS/MDP, cholinergic stimulation, TNF-alpha): Alpha-defensins (human defensins HD5 and HD6): cationic antimicrobial peptides that form pores in bacterial membranes; HD6 forms 'nanonets' that trap bacteria. Lysozyme: hydrolyzes bacterial peptidoglycan. sPLA2-IIA: hydrolyzes bacterial phospholipid membranes. RegIIIgamma (C-type lectin): kills Gram+ bacteria. LGR5+ intestinal stem cells (ISCs) are immediately adjacent to Paneth cells in the crypt base columnar cell ('CBC') position; Paneth cells provide niche signals: Wnt3 (activates Wnt signaling in ISCs), EGF (activates EGFR), Delta-4 (Notch activation via Notch1/2 receptors on ISCs). Paneth cell metaplasia in the colon (colonic mucosa replacing goblet/absorptive cells with Paneth cells) is seen in Crohn's disease.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Paneth cells"},
    {question:"Enteroendocrine cells (EECs) are scattered throughout the gastrointestinal epithelium. Which statements about their general properties and the 'open' vs 'closed' subtypes are most accurate?",options:{A:"All EECs are 'open type' (apical surface contacts lumen) and sense luminal contents directly via taste-receptor-like receptors and nutrient sensors",B:"EECs comprise ~1% of intestinal epithelial cells, are derived from the same LGR5+ stem cells as other intestinal epithelial cells, and contain dense-core secretory granules at the basolateral pole; 'open type' EECs have apical cytoplasmic projections (cilia or microvilli) that project into the lumen to sample luminal contents (glucose, fat, amino acids, bile acids, microbiota metabolites) via GPCRs (TAS1R/TAS2R taste receptors, GPR119, GPR120, GPR41/43); 'closed type' EECs have no luminal contact and respond to stretch or paracrine/hormonal signals; signals propagate via hormone secretion into lamina propria capillaries or by paracrine effects on submucosal neurons",C:"EECs are only found in the stomach; they produce gastrin exclusively",D:"EECs produce only serotonin (5-HT); all other gastrointestinal hormones are produced by other cell types"},correct:"B",explanation:"Enteroendocrine cells (EECs): Also called 'DNES cells' (diffuse neuroendocrine system). Histology: Small cells with apical granules (goblet cells have apical mucin granules; EECs have basolateral dense-core secretory granules — 'flask-shaped cells'). IHC: synaptophysin+, chromogranin A+, CD56+. Major EEC subtypes and their products: I cells (duodenum/jejunum) → CCK (releases biliary secretion and pancreatic enzymes in response to fat/protein); S cells → Secretin (releases bicarbonate in response to luminal acid); K cells → GIP (glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide, incretin); L cells (ileum, colon) → GLP-1 (incretin, stimulates insulin, reduces glucagon, slows gastric emptying; GLP-1 analog liraglutide/semaglutide for T2DM/obesity), GLP-2 (intestinal trophic), PYY (reduces appetite); G cells (antrum) → Gastrin (stimulates acid); D cells (throughout) → Somatostatin (inhibits most GI hormones, acid, and motility); EC cells (enterochromaffin) → 5-HT (serotonin, regulates motility, secretion, pain). Neoplasms of EECs: carcinoid tumors (well-differentiated neuroendocrine tumors, WHO 2019). MEN1 syndrome: multiple gastrinomas (Zollinger-Ellison), insulinomas, pituitary adenomas (MEN1/menin mutation).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Enteroendocrine cells"},
    {question:"Intestinal villi increase the absorptive surface area of the small intestine. What is the correct description of the villus structure and the lamina propria contents?",options:{A:"Intestinal villi are folds of the muscularis mucosae; they contain large lymphatic channels and arterial arcades",B:"Intestinal villi are finger-like (jejunum) or leaf-like (duodenum) projections of the mucosa (epithelium + lamina propria) into the intestinal lumen; the lamina propria core contains: a central lacteal (blind-ending lymphatic capillary that absorbs dietary fat as chylomicrons via MTP-dependent synthesis in enterocytes), fenestrated capillaries (for amino acids, monosaccharides), smooth muscle cells (from muscularis mucosae, allow villus contraction to pump lymph), fibroblasts, plasma cells (IgA-producing), and macrophages; the villus epithelium contains absorptive enterocytes, goblet cells, and enteroendocrine cells",C:"Intestinal villi contain a core of striated skeletal muscle that actively pumps lymph from the lacteal into the thoracic duct",D:"Villi are found in both the small and large intestine; the large intestine has longer villi than the small intestine"},correct:"B",explanation:"Intestinal villus structure: Villi project 0.5-1.5 mm into the intestinal lumen. Shape varies: tongue/leaf-shaped in the duodenum; finger-shaped in jejunum and ileum. Epithelial covering: Absorptive enterocytes (tall columnar, brush border — SGLT1 for glucose/galactose, GLUT2, peptide transporter PepT1, bile acid transporter ASBT in ileum), goblet cells (MUC2), and EECs. Lamina propria core: (1) Central lacteal: wide, blind-ended lymphatic capillary; absorbs chylomicrons (reassembled dietary fat packaged by enterocytes with apoB-48, MTP → secreted into lacteals → thoracic duct → blood); also drains villus interstitial fluid. (2) Fenestrated capillaries: drain monosaccharides and amino acids to the portal system → liver. (3) Smooth muscle fibers from muscularis mucosae: villus contraction ('villus pump') compresses the lacteal and propels lymph. (4) Stromal cells: myofibroblasts (form a pericryptal sheath), macrophages, plasma cells (IgA-secreting), and T lymphocytes. Plicae circulares (valves of Kerckring): circular folds of mucosa + submucosa visible to the naked eye (most prominent in the jejunum). Villi ABSENT in the large intestine (colon has only flat mucosa with crypts). Celiac disease: villous atrophy (flat mucosa with hyperplastic crypts) from T-cell attack on gliadin-presenting enterocytes.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Intestinal villi"},
    {question:"The salivary glands contain serous and mucous acini. Which correctly distinguishes serous from mucous acini on routine H&E?",options:{A:"Serous acini: cells with eosinophilic granular cytoplasm, small round central nuclei, narrow lumen; mucous acini: cells with pale, foamy cytoplasm (mucin dissolved by processing), basally compressed flat nuclei, wide lumen; serous demilunes are crescents of serous cells capping the mucous acini in submandibular and sublingual glands",B:"Serous acini: cells with pale basophilic cytoplasm; mucous acini: cells with eosinophilic cytoplasm; both have identically positioned nuclei",C:"Serous and mucous acini cannot be distinguished on H&E; special stains (PAS and Alcian blue) are required for differentiation",D:"Mucous acini are found only in the parotid gland; serous acini are found only in the sublingual gland"},correct:"A",explanation:"Salivary gland histology: Serous acini: Pyramidal cells with well-defined spherical or ovoid nuclei in the basal third; abundant eosinophilic (pink) cytoplasm with secretory (zymogen) granules in the apical region (containing salivary amylase, proline-rich proteins, EGF, HGF, etc.); narrow intercellular canaliculi. Seen prominently in the parotid gland (purely serous). Mucous acini: Larger, paler cells; mucin in the apical cytoplasm is water-soluble and mostly washed out during processing → pale, 'empty,' foamy cytoplasm; nuclei are flattened and pushed to the base ('basal crescent' of flattened nuclei). Wide central lumen. Mucous acini predominate in the sublingual gland. Mixed glands: Submandibular gland: mostly serous acini + some mucous acini; serous demilunes (serous 'caps' or 'half-moons' of serous cells capping the outer surface of mucous acini). Traditional belief: serous demilunes are artifacts of fixation (mucous acini collapse, pushing serous cells into a crescentic shape); in reality, serous and mucous cells form 'mixed' acini. Sublingual gland: predominantly mucous. Special stains: PAS → mucous acini positive (magenta); Alcian blue pH 2.5 → acidic mucins (sialomucins in salivary mucus) positive (blue).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Glandular epithelium"},
    {question:"The respiratory epithelium of the trachea and main bronchi is a classic example of pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium. What are the five cell types found in this epithelium?",options:{A:"Ciliated cells, goblet cells, basal cells, Kulchitsky (neuroendocrine) cells, and brush cells (microvillous cells); all have cilia",B:"Ciliated columnar cells (most abundant; motile cilia propel mucus), goblet cells (mucin-secreting, MUC5AC/5B), basal cells (stem cells for the ciliated and goblet cells, express Trp63/p63, Krt5/14; maintain contact with basal lamina), Kulchitsky cells (neuroendocrine, dense-core granules, produce serotonin and other amines/peptides), and brush cells (microvillous, express bitter taste receptors TAS2R, linked to solitary chemosensory function; may be identical to tuft cells)",C:"Ciliated cells, mucous cells, chief cells, parietal cells, and enteroendocrine cells — identical to the gastric epithelium",D:"The respiratory epithelium contains only two cell types: ciliated cells and goblet cells; basal cells and neuroendocrine cells are limited to the alveolar epithelium"},correct:"B",explanation:"Pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium (PCCE): All cells contact the basal lamina but not all reach the luminal surface — hence 'pseudostratified' (nuclei at different heights). 5 main cell types: (1) Ciliated cells (~50%): tall columnar, ~300 cilia/cell, beating at 10-15 Hz; beat in coordinated metachronal waves; propel mucus (MCC — mucociliary clearance). (2) Goblet cells (~25%): wedge-shaped, mucin granules (MUC5AC predominantly); goblet cell hyperplasia in chronic bronchitis, asthma, and COPD. (3) Basal cells (~25%): cuboidal, on basal lamina only, do NOT reach the surface; Trp63 (p63)+, Krt5/14+; stem cells for ciliated and goblet cells. Also express p40 (deltaNp63). (4) Kulchitsky (K) cells (small granule cells): neuroendocrine cells; few in number; dense-core secretory granules (PGP9.5+, chromogranin+, synaptophysin+); produce serotonin, bombesin, calcitonin, somatostatin; origin of small cell lung carcinoma and carcinoid tumors. (5) Brush/tuft cells (microvillous cells): tall columnar with prominent apical microvilli (not cilia); express TAS2R (bitter) and TAS1R (sweet) taste receptors; linked to luminal chemosensation and TRPM5-mediated calcium signals → stimulate cholinergic reflex (increases mucus and ciliary beat).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Respiratory epithelium"},
    {question:"Mucous membranes (mucosae) are composed of an epithelium, lamina propria, and muscularis mucosae. Which organ's mucosa LACKS a muscularis mucosae?",options:{A:"The esophageal mucosa lacks a muscularis mucosae",B:"The gallbladder mucosa lacks a muscularis mucosae; it consists of a mucosal layer (epithelium + lamina propria) directly apposed to a smooth muscle layer (not separately organized as muscularis mucosae + submucosa)",C:"The stomach mucosa lacks a muscularis mucosae",D:"The colon mucosa lacks a muscularis mucosae because its flat surface does not need this layer"},correct:"B",explanation:"Standard mucosal organization in most of the GI tract: epithelium + lamina propria + muscularis mucosae + submucosa. Muscularis mucosae: a thin layer of smooth muscle (inner circular + outer longitudinal) that can contract to alter mucosal folds and crypt geometry. Gallbladder: exception — the gallbladder wall consists of: mucosa (simple columnar epithelium with microvilli + lamina propria; Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses = epithelium-lined diverticula into the muscular layer); directly underlies a muscularis (smooth muscle, not separated into mucosae layer and muscularis propria); perimuscular connective tissue; serosa (visceral peritoneum). There is NO submucosa and NO muscularis mucosae in the gallbladder. Clinical significance: gallbladder carcinoma staging differs from GI carcinoma staging because there is no muscularis mucosae or submucosa to define T-stage boundaries in the same way. Adenomyosis of the gallbladder: hyperplasia of the epithelium + muscular wall with abundant Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses. Other organs with modified mucosal organization: cornea (no muscularis mucosae), respiratory tract (muscularis mucosae absent in bronchioles).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Mucosal structure"},
    {question:"Metaplasia is the reversible replacement of one differentiated cell type with another. What is the most common metaplasia seen in the stomach and what is its significance?",options:{A:"Squamous metaplasia (replacement of gastric mucosa with stratified squamous epithelium); occurs due to GERD; no cancer risk",B:"Intestinal metaplasia (IM) of the gastric mucosa: replacement of normal gastric epithelium with intestinal-type epithelium containing goblet cells, absorptive cells, and sometimes Paneth cells; classified as type I (complete, with alkaline phosphatase-positive absorptive cells) and type II-III (incomplete, columnar cells producing sulfomucins — type III associated with increased gastric cancer risk); driven by Helicobacter pylori infection, chronic inflammation, bile reflux; Cdx2 TF is the 'master regulator' inducing intestinal differentiation in the stomach; IM → dysplasia → gastric adenocarcinoma (Correa's cascade)",C:"Pancreatic acinar metaplasia: replacement of gastric fundic glands with pancreatic acinar-like cells; common finding with high cancer risk",D:"Pseudopyloric metaplasia: replacement of oxyntic mucosa with mucous-type glands in the corpus; has the same cancer risk as intestinal metaplasia"},correct:"B",explanation:"Gastric intestinal metaplasia (GIM): The most clinically significant gastric metaplasia. Gastric mucosa is replaced by intestinal-type epithelium with goblet cells (required for diagnosis of IM), absorptive cells, and sometimes Paneth cells. The Silva classification: Type I (complete/small intestinal type): mature absorptive cells (straight crypts, regular goblet cells, Paneth cells); low cancer risk. Type II (incomplete): secretes both gastric and intestinal mucins; irregular crypts. Type III (incomplete): secretes sulfated sialomucins; most closely resembles intestinal metaplasia found adjacent to adenocarcinoma; highest cancer risk. Correa cascade: H. pylori infection → chronic superficial gastritis → atrophic gastritis → intestinal metaplasia → dysplasia → intestinal-type gastric adenocarcinoma. CDX1/CDX2 (caudal type homeobox TFs): normally expressed in the intestine; induced ectopically in the stomach by inflammatory mediators → drive intestinal gene expression (MUC2, villin, DPPIV, CDX2 self-maintenance). H. pylori eradication: can reduce H. pylori-associated gastritis and prevent progression, but may not reverse IM once established. Risk factors for GIM: H. pylori, smoking, high salt diet, bile reflux. Surveillance for patients with IM+: upper endoscopy with biopsies every 3-5 years.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Metaplasia"},
    {question:"The thyroid follicular cells (thyrocytes) are a unique type of simple cuboidal epithelium arranged around a central colloid. What is the unusual transport polarity of thyrocytes?",options:{A:"Thyrocytes have normal epithelial polarity: they absorb iodide from the basolateral capillary side and secrete thyroglobulin into the follicular lumen at the apical surface, then reabsorb colloid via apical endocytosis — this is called bidirectional transcytotic function",B:"Thyrocytes have reversed polarity compared to most simple epithelia: their 'secretory' surface faces the follicular lumen (apical), where they secrete thyroglobulin and iodinate it; their 'absorptive' surface faces the basolateral capillary, where they take up iodide (via NIS — sodium-iodide symporter, two Na+ and one I- per cycle, ATP-independent, driven by Na+ gradient); and take back up colloid from the lumen (via apical endocytosis), digest it in lysosomes, and release T3/T4 into basolateral capillaries",C:"Thyrocytes secrete T3 and T4 directly into the follicular lumen; thyroid hormone is then absorbed from the colloid by the circulation",D:"The sodium-iodide symporter (NIS) is located on the apical (luminal) surface of thyrocytes; iodide is therefore directly absorbed from the follicular lumen"},correct:"B",explanation:"Thyrocyte transport polarity: Basolateral surface (facing capillaries): (1) NIS (SLC5A5): secondary active transporter co-transporting 2 Na+ + 1 I- from blood into the cell, driven by the Na+ gradient created by basolateral Na+/K+-ATPase. This concentrates iodide ~30-40x relative to plasma. (2) Thyroid hormone transporters (MCT8, MCT10): release T3/T4 into capillaries. Apical surface (facing follicular lumen): (1) Pendrin (SLC26A4): Cl-/I- exchanger, secretes I- from thyrocyte into follicular lumen. (2) Thyroglobulin secretion: thyroglobulin synthesized on rER → Golgi → secretory vesicles → exocytosed apically into follicular lumen. (3) DUOX1/2 (dual oxidase) and TPO (thyroid peroxidase): at the apical membrane, TPO iodinates tyrosine residues of thyroglobulin (MIT — monoiodotyrosine, DIT — diiodotyrosine) and couples them (DIT + DIT → T4; DIT + MIT → T3) — reactions requiring H2O2 (generated by DUOX2). (4) Megalin (LRP2): mediates endocytosis of colloid at the apical surface. Intracellular: colloid droplets + lysosomes → proteolysis of thyroglobulin → T3/T4 released → diffuse through cell → secreted basolaterally. MIT and DIT recycled. Clinical: NIS deficiency → congenital hypothyroidism; Pendrin mutation → Pendred syndrome (goiter + sensorineural hearing loss).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Thyroid follicular cells"},
    {question:"The hepatocyte is a highly polarized epithelial cell with three distinct membrane domains. Which correctly describes hepatocyte polarity?",options:{A:"Hepatocytes have only two membrane domains (apical and basolateral), identical to simple columnar epithelial cells",B:"Hepatocytes are multipolar epithelial cells with: (1) Sinusoidal (basolateral) domain: faces the space of Disse (perisinusoidal space) and fenestrated sinusoidal endothelium — site of lipoprotein, albumin, and other plasma protein secretion; uptake of nutrients, drugs, hormones; (2) Canalicular (apical) domain: faces the bile canaliculus (narrow intercellular channel formed between adjacent hepatocytes); site of bile secretion (bile acid transport via BSEP/ABCB11, phospholipid transport via MDR3/ABCB4, bilirubin conjugate transport via MRP2/ABCC2, cholesterol via ABCG5/ABCG8); (3) Lateral domain: faces adjacent hepatocyte — contains gap junctions (Cx26, Cx32) and adherens junctions (E-cadherin-beta-catenin)",C:"Hepatocytes face only the space of Disse; all hepatocyte secretory products are released exclusively into the sinusoidal blood",D:"Hepatocytes are non-polar cells that secrete products indiscriminately in all directions; polarity is a property only of intestinal epithelial cells"},correct:"B",explanation:"Hepatocyte polarity (tripolar epithelium): Unlike simple columnar epithelia with one apical and one basolateral surface, hepatocytes form a unique 3D epithelial structure: (1) Sinusoidal (basolateral, ~70% of membrane area) domain: faces the perisinusoidal space of Disse. Basolateral transporters: NTCP (SLC10A1, sodium-taurocholate co-transporting polypeptide — takes up conjugated bile acids from portal blood), OATPs (SLCO1B1/1B3, organic anion transporting polypeptides — take up bilirubin-glucuronides, drugs, thyroid hormones), LDL receptor (apoB/E receptor), albumin secretion, glucose-6-phosphatase. (2) Canalicular (apical, ~15%) domain: forms the bile canaliculus (a sealed, narrow channel between 2-3 hepatocytes, ~1 micron diameter, sealed by tight junctions). Canalicular transporters: BSEP/ABCB11 (bile salt export pump — rate-limiting step in bile secretion; PFIC2 from BSEP mutation), MRP2/ABCC2 (conjugated bilirubin, drug glucuronides; PFIC3 from MDR3 mutation → phospholipid in bile → gallstones), MDR3/ABCB4 (phosphatidylcholine flippase), ABCG5/ABCG8 (cholesterol/sterols). (3) Lateral domain: Cx32/Cx26 gap junctions between adjacent hepatocytes (metabolic coupling); E-cadherin-beta-catenin adherens junctions. Cholestasis: loss of any canalicular transporter → bile accumulation in hepatocytes → hepatocellular damage.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Hepatocyte polarity"},
    {question:"Claudin-5 is the dominant claudin at the blood-brain barrier (BBB) tight junctions. What other molecular components characterize the BBB endothelium?",options:{A:"The BBB is formed by neuronal axons wrapping around brain capillaries; there are no tight junctions",B:"BBB tight junctions: claudin-5 (dominant, determines high electrical resistance ~1500-2000 ohm-cm2 vs 10-40 in most peripheral endothelia) + claudin-3 + occludin + ZO-1/2; additionally: P-glycoprotein (MDR1/ABCB1 — efflux pump for lipophilic drugs and toxins, responsible for pharmacological drug resistance in brain tumors), LAT1 (amino acid transporter, for large neutral amino acids), GLUT1 (glucose, bidirectional), transferrin receptor (iron uptake); astrocyte endfeet cover 99% of the brain capillary surface and provide inductive signals (via Wnt/beta-catenin, Angiopoietin-1, TGF-beta) that maintain BBB properties; pericytes (PDGFR-beta+) provide additional regulation",C:"The BBB has no tight junctions; selectivity is based entirely on transcellular transport through GLUT1",D:"Claudin-5 at the BBB is identical to claudin-2 at the renal proximal tubule; both form cation-selective pores that allow ion passage"},correct:"B",explanation:"Blood-brain barrier: The BBB is a specialized endothelium that controls passage between blood and the CNS. TJ proteins: Claudin-5 (the most important claudin at the BBB — CLDN5 knockout mice die at P0 from BBB permeability to small molecules <800 Da); claudin-3 (also restrictive); occludin (TER regulation); ZO-1/ZO-2 (scaffold). The BBB has one of the highest transendothelial electrical resistances (TER) of any barrier (~1500-2000 ohm-cm2 vs ~10-40 ohm-cm2 in peripheral capillaries and ~50-150 in the blood-testis barrier). Transport across BBB: Transcellular lipid diffusion (small, lipid-soluble molecules — O2, CO2, ethanol, anesthetics, most CNS drugs). Carrier-mediated transport: GLUT1 (glucose, bidirectional); LAT1/2 (SLC7A5/8 — amino acids — L-DOPA entry); MCT1 (ketone bodies, monocarboxylates); transferrin receptor (iron). Efflux transporters: P-gp (MDR1/ABCB1), BCRP (ABCG2), MRP4 — pump out xenobiotics and drugs → major cause of CNS drug treatment failure (e.g., HIV drugs, chemotherapy for brain tumors). Pericytes: contractile cells on the abluminal side (PDGFR-beta+, NG2+); regulate blood flow (capillary diameter) and maintain TJ integrity. Astrocyte endfeet: send inductive signals (Wnt3a, TGF-beta, Angiopoietin-1 via Tie2) to maintain claudin-5 expression. BBB breakdown: stroke, TBI, MS, meningitis, Alzheimer's.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Blood-brain barrier"},
    {question:"The corneal epithelium is a stratified squamous non-keratinized epithelium with 5-7 cell layers. What unique properties must the corneal surface epithelium maintain?",options:{A:"The corneal epithelium maintains mechanical strength only; transparency is provided solely by the corneal stroma",B:"The corneal epithelium must maintain: (1) Optical transparency (cells devoid of pigment, uniform refractive index, avascular — relies on diffusion from limbal capillaries and aqueous humor); (2) A smooth refracting surface (apical microvilli and glycocalyx stabilize the tear film — MUC16 and MUC5AC from goblet cells of the conjunctiva); (3) A tight barrier (claudin-1, -4, -7 and occludin-rich TJs prevent tear hyperosmolarity from affecting stroma); (4) Rapid wound healing (limbal stem cells in the basal epithelium of the corneoscleral limbus — p63+/ABCG2+ maintain and regenerate the corneal epithelium by centripetal migration); goblet cells are NOT present in the corneal epithelium itself",C:"The corneal epithelium is keratinized (identical to skin) to protect against evaporation; this cornification is necessary for transparency",D:"Limbal stem cells are found in the corneal center; they migrate outward toward the limbus as they differentiate"},correct:"B",explanation:"Corneal epithelium specializations: The cornea must be optically clear and mechanically protective simultaneously. Histology: 5-7 layers of stratified squamous non-keratinized epithelium (no corneum layer → remains transparent and moist); basal cells (columnar, mitotically active); intermediate cells (wing-shaped/polygonal); superficial cells (squamous, still nucleated, with tight junctions). Transparency requirements: avascular (would scatter light → must rely on diffusion); no melanocytes or Langerhans cells in the central cornea (normally); organized and uniform refractive index; highly smooth surface. Tear film: stabilized by mucins. Goblet cells in the conjunctiva (not the cornea) secrete MUC5AC; corneal cells themselves have GPI-anchored MUC16 (CA125) and MUC1 on apical microvilli → form glycocalyx that stabilizes the aqueous layer of the tear film. TJ barrier: claudin-1 and -4 in the outermost 2 layers → prevent hyperosmolar tears from penetrating to the stroma. Limbal stem cells (LSCs): p63+, ABCG2+, Δnp63alpha+; located in the basal layer at the corneoscleral limbus (transition zone); maintain proliferative capacity throughout life; daughter cells (transient amplifying cells) migrate centripetally across the corneal surface (X, Y, Z hypothesis of Thoft). LSC deficiency (burns, Stevens-Johnson, aniridia with PAX6 mutations) → conjunctivalization of the cornea (vascular ingrowth, goblet cells) → vision loss; treatment: limbal stem cell transplantation.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Corneal epithelium"},
    {question:"Which of the following correctly describes the structure and function of the juxtaglomerular apparatus (JGA) in the kidney?",options:{A:"The JGA consists of the macula densa, juxtaglomerular cells, and extraglomerular mesangial cells (lacis cells), and is the site of renin secretion, NaCl sensing, and tubuloglomerular feedback",B:"The JGA consists of podocytes and parietal epithelial cells of Bowman's capsule; it regulates GFR by changing the pore size of the filtration barrier",C:"The JGA is a specialized region of the loop of Henle that senses oxygen tension and regulates EPO production",D:"The JGA consists of principal cells and intercalated cells of the collecting duct; it is the site of aldosterone-regulated Na+ transport"},correct:"A",explanation:"Juxtaglomerular apparatus (JGA): Located at the vascular pole of each glomerulus, where the afferent and efferent arterioles meet the distal tubule. Three components: (1) Macula densa: specialized segment of thick ascending limb (TAL)/early DCT cells adjacent to the afferent arteriole; large, closely packed cells with apical Na-K-2Cl co-transporter (NKCC2) that sense tubular NaCl concentration; when NaCl is low (reduced GFR or volume depletion) → macula densa cells signal adjacent JG cells to increase renin release and cause afferent arteriolar dilation (tubuloglomerular feedback, TGF). (2) Juxtaglomerular (JG) cells (granular cells): modified smooth muscle cells in the media of the afferent arteriole (and to a lesser extent efferent arteriole); contain large PAS-positive granules of renin; stimuli for renin release: low renal perfusion pressure (baroreceptor mechanism), low NaCl at macula densa (macula densa mechanism), sympathetic stimulation (beta-1 adrenergic receptors), low extracellular fluid volume. (3) Extraglomerular mesangial cells (lacis cells, Polkissen cells): mesangial-like cells in the angle between afferent and efferent arterioles; may relay signals between macula densa and JG cells; also have phagocytic properties. Renin → cleaves angiotensinogen to angiotensin I → ACE → Ang II → AT1R → vasoconstriction + aldosterone secretion + ADH release + Na+ reabsorption.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue",subtopic:"Kidney tubule cells"}
  ];

  var epithelialTissue2023Questions = [
    {question:"Barrett's esophagus is a metaplastic transformation of the distal esophageal epithelium. What is the primary etiology and what defines Barrett's histologically?",options:{A:"Barrett's is caused by Helicobacter pylori infection; histologically defined by the presence of goblet cells in the gastric cardia",B:"Barrett's is caused by chronic gastroesophageal reflux (GERD) of acid and bile → proximal migration of the squamocolumnar junction (Z-line) → replacement of normal stratified squamous esophageal epithelium by columnar epithelium; the diagnosis requires the presence of specialized intestinal metaplasia (SIM): intestinal-type columnar epithelium with goblet cells (positive Alcian blue pH 2.5 for acidic mucins) in biopsies from the tubular esophagus; goblet cells express CDX2",C:"Barrett's is caused by radiation damage to the esophagus; defined solely by the endoscopic appearance of salmon-colored mucosa in the distal esophagus",D:"Barrett's is caused by eosinophilic esophagitis; defined by eosinophil infiltration of the squamous epithelium"},correct:"B",explanation:"Barrett's esophagus (BE): Chronic GERD → acid + bile reflux → recurrent damage to distal esophageal squamous epithelium → abnormal re-epithelialization by metaplastic columnar cells (via transdifferentiation of basal stem cells or proximal migration of gastric cardia cells; CDX2 is the key TF). US definition: BE requires both endoscopic evidence of salmon-colored columnar-lined mucosa extending > 1 cm proximal to the gastroesophageal junction AND histological evidence of specialized intestinal metaplasia (goblet cells expressing MUC2, CDX2, Alcian blue+) in biopsies from the tubular esophagus. Length: short-segment BE (<3 cm); long-segment BE (≥3 cm). Risk of progression to esophageal adenocarcinoma (EAC): ~0.3%/year in BE without dysplasia; dysplasia is a precursor. Correa-like sequence: GERD → BE without dysplasia → low-grade dysplasia (LGD) → high-grade dysplasia (HGD) → EAC. Dysplasia criteria: nuclear stratification beyond basal third, pleomorphism, loss of mucin, complex glandular architecture, mitoses. HGD → ablation (radiofrequency ablation, cryotherapy) or esophagectomy. Molecular: TP53 mutations early; CDKN2A (p16) silencing; HER2 amplification in EAC.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Barrett's esophagus"},
    {question:"Reactive oxygen species (ROS) and antioxidant defense systems are clinically relevant in epithelial pathology. Which antioxidant enzyme converts superoxide (O2.-) to H2O2?",options:{A:"Catalase — converts H2O2 to H2O + O2 (does not act on superoxide)",B:"Superoxide dismutase (SOD) — converts 2 O2.- + 2H+ → H2O2 + O2; three isoforms: SOD1 (Cu/Zn-SOD, cytoplasmic), SOD2 (Mn-SOD, mitochondrial matrix — critical for mitochondrial ROS defense), SOD3 (extracellular Cu/Zn-SOD)",C:"Glutathione peroxidase — converts 2 GSH + H2O2 → GSSG + 2H2O (acts on H2O2, not superoxide)",D:"Thioredoxin reductase — reduces thioredoxin using NADPH, acting downstream of both SOD and catalase"},correct:"B",explanation:"Antioxidant enzyme hierarchy: Superoxide (O2.-) is generated by the mitochondrial ETC (complex I and III are the main sites of electron leak to O2), NADPH oxidases (NOX enzymes, especially NOX2 in phagocytes), xanthine oxidase, and other oxidases. Dismutation: SOD catalyzes: 2O2.- + 2H+ → H2O2 + O2. Three mammalian SODs: SOD1 (CuZnSOD): cytoplasm, nucleus; mutations → familial ALS (aggregation, GOF toxicity). SOD2 (MnSOD): mitochondrial matrix; null mice die at birth from severe oxidative stress; polymorphism Ala16Val associated with various cancer risks. SOD3 (EC-SOD): extracellular; heparin-binding, located on endothelial surface. H2O2 disposal: Catalase (in peroxisomes): 2H2O2 → 2H2O + O2; Glutathione peroxidase (GPx1-8): H2O2 + 2GSH → 2H2O + GSSG; Peroxiredoxins (Prx1-6): 2Prx-SH + H2O2 → Prx-S-S-Prx + 2H2O. GSSG reduced back to GSH by glutathione reductase (NADPH-dependent). NADPH provided by glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD — pentose phosphate pathway). G6PD deficiency → hemolytic anemia in oxidative stress (primaquine, dapsone, fava beans). Nrf2/KEAP1 pathway: Nrf2 is the master transcription factor for antioxidant gene expression (HO-1, NQO1, SOD2, GPx, ferritin, thioredoxin); KEAP1 is the cytoplasmic repressor that degrades Nrf2 via ubiquitin-proteasome; electrophiles and ROS modify KEAP1 Cys residues → Nrf2 stabilization → nuclear translocation → ARE-driven transcription.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Oxidative stress"},
    {question:"Carcinoma in situ (CIS) is a high-grade preinvasive neoplasm. What histological criteria distinguish CIS from invasive carcinoma?",options:{A:"CIS has more mitoses than invasive carcinoma; the basement membrane is intact in CIS",B:"CIS shows full-thickness nuclear atypia (pleomorphism, increased N:C ratio, abnormal mitoses) throughout the epithelium WITHOUT breach of the basement membrane (no invasion into underlying stroma); stromal desmoplasia and irregular gland formation are features of invasive carcinoma only; CIS is confined to the epithelial compartment",C:"CIS cannot be distinguished from invasive carcinoma on H&E alone; IHC for E-cadherin is always required",D:"CIS is defined by less than 1 mm depth of invasion; it is not truly 'in situ' but minimally invasive"},correct:"B",explanation:"CIS vs invasive carcinoma: Carcinoma in situ (CIS): full-thickness cytological atypia confined to the epithelium by the intact basement membrane. Key histological features of CIS: loss of normal maturation and polarity from base to surface; enlarged, hyperchromatic, pleomorphic nuclei; prominent nucleoli; increased mitoses (including abnormal forms); loss of normal architectural organization; BUT the basement membrane is intact (no stromal invasion). Examples: urothelial CIS (flat, erythematous lesion on cystoscopy; high-grade nuclear atypia throughout), DCIS of the breast (acinar structures filled with malignant cells but surrounded by intact myoepithelial cells and basement membrane), LCIS (lobular CIS), cervical CIS/CIN3, high-grade esophageal dysplasia in BE. Invasion: breach of the basement membrane → irregular gland formation, single cells, cords in the stroma, stromal desmoplasia (reactive myofibroblast proliferation producing type I collagen), perineural invasion, lymphovascular invasion → risk of metastasis. IHC: Collagen IV and laminin (basement membrane markers) are disrupted in invasive carcinoma but intact in CIS. Myoepithelial cells (p63+, SMA+, calponin+, CK5/6+) are absent in invasive breast carcinoma but present in DCIS and benign lesions.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Histological diagnosis"},
    {question:"The junctional complex in columnar epithelium consists of tight junctions, adherens junctions, and desmosomes. In what order (from apical to basal) are they arranged?",options:{A:"Desmosomes (most apical) → adherens junctions → tight junctions (most basal)",B:"Tight junctions (zonula occludens, most apical) → adherens junctions (zonula adherens) → desmosomes (macula adherentes, scattered laterally, most basal of the three); gap junctions (macula communicantes) and hemidesmosomes are additional junctions found more basally",C:"Adherens junctions → tight junctions → desmosomes",D:"All three are at the same level (the terminal web) and cannot be placed in apical-to-basal order"},correct:"B",explanation:"Junctional complex organization (simple columnar epithelium, e.g., small intestine): The classic 'terminal bar' (visible as a dark line at the lateral apex of columnar cells on H&E) corresponds to the junctional complex. Apical to basal order: (1) Zonula occludens (ZO, tight junction, TJ): most apical; circumferential belt around the cell; claudins + occludin + ZO-1/2/3; highest-level barrier and polarity fence. (2) Zonula adherens (ZA, adherens junction, AJ): immediately below TJ; E-cadherin-beta-catenin complex linked to actin; transmits mechanical forces. (3) Macula adherentes (desmosomes): scattered as discrete spots/plaques along the lateral membrane below the ZA; Dsg/Dsc-desmoplakin-keratin; strongest mechanical linkage. Additional junctions (not classic junctional complex): Gap junctions (macula communicantes): scattered laterally; connexins; ion/metabolite passage. Hemidesmosomes: basal surface only; integrin alpha6beta4-laminin-332; attach basal cells to basement membrane. Understanding this organization is essential for interpreting the immunological basis of autoimmune blistering diseases: TJ disruption (cholera ZOT) = paracellular leak; AJ disruption (anti-E-cadherin) = loss of cohesion; desmosome disruption (pemphigus) = acantholysis; hemidesmosome disruption (bullous pemphigoid) = subepidermal blister.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Junctional complex"},
    {question:"Ion transport in the colon is critical for fluid homeostasis. Which statement correctly describes the primary mechanism of Na+ absorption in the distal colon?",options:{A:"The distal colon absorbs Na+ via paracellular 'leak' through tight junctions; ENaC channels are not present",B:"The distal colon absorbs Na+ primarily via ENaC (epithelial Na+ channel, composed of alpha-beta-gamma subunits) in the apical membrane of principal cells; driven by the electrochemical gradient created by basolateral Na+/K+-ATPase; regulated by aldosterone (increases ENaC synthesis and membrane insertion via SGK1-NEDD4L axis, and increases Na+/K+-ATPase units); luminal Na+ enters via ENaC → exported via Na+/K+-ATPase → water follows paracellularly",C:"The distal colon absorbs Na+ via SGLT1 (sodium-glucose co-transporter); glucose is required for Na+ absorption in the colon",D:"Na+ absorption in the distal colon is entirely dependent on NHE3 (Na+/H+ exchanger-3) and is not regulated by aldosterone"},correct:"B",explanation:"Colonic Na+ absorption: The colon absorbs ~90% of the water and electrolytes entering it from the ileum (~1.5-2 L/day). Mechanisms vary by segment: Proximal colon: electroneutral NaCl absorption via coupled NHE3 (Na+/H+ antiporter) + DRA (down-regulated in adenoma, Cl-/HCO3- antiporter). Sensitive to osmotic diarrhea. Distal colon: Electrogenic Na+ absorption via ENaC. ENaC (Epithelial Na+ Channel): trimeric channel (alpha-beta-gamma subunits; all three required for function); expressed only in principal cells (in collecting duct and distal colon). Aldosterone regulation of ENaC: aldosterone (from adrenal zona glomerulosa, stimulated by Ang II and K+) diffuses into cells → mineralocorticoid receptor (MR, a nuclear receptor) → transcriptional activation: (1) Induces SGK1 (serum/glucocorticoid kinase-1) → phosphorylates NEDD4L → NEDD4L cannot ubiquitinate ENaC → ENaC not degraded → increased apical ENaC expression; (2) Increases alpha-subunit of Na+/K+-ATPase → increased pump activity. Net: Na+ absorbed → Cl- follows passively/paracellularly → water follows osmotically. Pseudohypoaldosteronism type 1 (PHA1): ENaC loss-of-function → salt-wasting despite high aldosterone. Liddle syndrome: SCNN1B/G gain-of-function mutation in ENaC beta/gamma → increased ENaC activity → hypertension (treated with amiloride, direct ENaC blocker).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Intestinal ion transport"},
    {question:"The blood-testis barrier (BTB) is formed by tight junctions between adjacent Sertoli cells in the seminiferous tubules. What is its function and what happens to BTB integrity in Sertoli-cell-only syndrome?",options:{A:"The BTB separates Leydig cells from germ cells; its disruption causes testosterone deficiency but not azoospermia",B:"The BTB divides the seminiferous tubule into a basal compartment (containing spermatogonia and early spermatocytes, accessible to blood-borne factors) and an adluminal compartment (containing pachytene spermatocytes through spermatids, protected from immune surveillance); function: immunological privilege — post-meiotic germ cells (expressing unique antigens appearing after immune tolerance is established) are sequestered from the immune system; BTB disruption → autoimmune orchitis; Sertoli-cell-only syndrome (SCO): absence of germ cells; Sertoli cells still present and form BTB; men have azoospermia with elevated FSH",C:"The BTB surrounds each individual spermatogonium to prevent autoimmune recognition of sperm surface antigens",D:"The BTB is formed by Leydig cells (not Sertoli cells); it prevents testosterone from reaching the bloodstream"},correct:"B",explanation:"Blood-testis barrier (BTB): Formed by an elaborate system of tight junctions (claudin-3, -11 are testis-enriched; also claudin-1, claudin-2, occludin, JAM-A), adherens junctions, and gap junctions between adjacent Sertoli cells. These form at puberty, coinciding with the initiation of meiosis. Functional compartments: (1) Basal compartment (below BTB): accessible to blood-borne factors; contains spermatogonia (diploid, 2n) → primary spermatocytes in pre-leptotene/leptotene phase; regulated by FSH (FSHR on Sertoli cells), testosterone (from Leydig cells), SCF (kit ligand), and GDNF (glial cell-derived neurotrophic factor) for spermatogonial stem cell maintenance. (2) Adluminal compartment (above BTB): immunologically privileged, high local testosterone; contains pachytene spermatocytes → secondary spermatocytes → round spermatids → elongating spermatids → spermatozoa. Meiotic and post-meiotic germ cells express novel antigens not present during immune tolerance establishment → must be protected from anti-sperm autoimmune attack. BTB disruption (trauma, infection) → anti-sperm antibodies → male infertility. SCO syndrome (Sertoli cell-only): germ cells absent from seminiferous tubules; causes: Y chromosome microdeletions (AZF loci), Klinefelter syndrome (47,XXY), cryptorchidism, chemotherapy, radiation. Histology: tubules lined only by Sertoli cells; FSH elevated (no inhibin B from Sertoli cells' response to germ cells). Testicular sperm extraction (TESE) is required for ART.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Blood-testis barrier"},
    {question:"Type II pneumocytes are cuboidal cells covering ~5% of the alveolar surface but producing 100% of pulmonary surfactant. What are the key components of surfactant and the clinical significance of surfactant deficiency?",options:{A:"Surfactant consists mainly of type I collagen and fibronectin; deficiency causes alveolar proteinosis",B:"Pulmonary surfactant is a mixture of phospholipids (~80%) — predominantly dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine (DPPC, lecithin — the major surface-active component), phosphatidylglycerol, and phosphatidylethanolamine — plus four surfactant proteins: SP-A and SP-D (hydrophilic, collectins — involved in innate immunity, pathogen recognition, surfactant metabolism regulation) and SP-B and SP-C (hydrophobic, small, critical for surfactant adsorption and surface film formation); deficiency of SP-B or SP-C → lethal congenital surfactant deficiency; DPPC deficiency in premature neonates (<36 weeks) → neonatal respiratory distress syndrome (RDS/hyaline membrane disease); treatment: antenatal corticosteroids (induce surfactant synthesis 24-48h before delivery) + postnatal exogenous surfactant (Surfacta/Calfactant via ET tube)",C:"Surfactant is composed entirely of proteins (no lipid component); SP-A is the critical surface-active component responsible for reducing surface tension",D:"Surfactant is produced by type I pneumocytes (not type II); it is stored in lamellar bodies and secreted by exocytosis"},correct:"B",explanation:"Pulmonary surfactant: Synthesized by type II pneumocytes (cuboidal cells with lamellar bodies — multilayered phospholipid storage organelles visible on EM, stain with OsO4). Secreted by exocytosis (stimulated by stretch, beta-2 adrenergic agonists, ATP via P2Y receptors, surfactant-recycling by SP-A). Composition: ~80% phospholipids: DPPC (dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine/lecithin): accounts for ~60% of surfactant; the saturated dipalmitoyl chains pack tightly at the air-liquid interface → reduces surface tension at end-expiration (prevents alveolar collapse = atelectasis). PG (phosphatidylglycerol, ~8%): facilitates DPPC adsorption; ratio DPPC:PG (lecithin:sphingomyelin ratio on amniocentesis >2.0 with phosphatidylglycerol present = fetal lung maturity). ~10% proteins: SP-B (18 kDa, dimeric): required for formation of tubular myelin and adsorption of surfactant to air-water interface; deficiency → lethal congenital surfactant protein B deficiency (autosomal recessive, SFTPB mutations). SP-C (4.2 kDa, palmitoylated, most hydrophobic protein known): enhances spreading; SFTPC mutations → interstitial lung disease. SP-A (collectin) and SP-D (collectin): opsonize pathogens (Pneumocystis, Klebsiella, viruses), regulate surfactant metabolism (SP-A → AM phagocytosis of surfactant → recycling). RDS treatment: antenatal betamethasone (mature in 24-48h) + exogenous surfactant replacement via endotracheal tube. L:S ratio <2.0 + absent PG = immature lungs.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Alveolar epithelium"},
    {question:"A 65-year-old woman presents with a breast mass. Core needle biopsy shows invasive ductal carcinoma. IHC staining is performed. Which panel of IHC markers is routinely used for breast carcinoma classification and treatment selection?",options:{A:"CEA, CA19-9, and CA125 are the standard breast IHC markers used to determine prognosis",B:"Estrogen receptor (ER, clone SP1 or 6F11), Progesterone receptor (PR), and HER2 (human epidermal growth factor receptor 2, clone 4B5 or SP3) are the standard breast IHC trifecta; Ki-67 proliferation index is additionally assessed; results stratify carcinoma into: Luminal A (ER+/PR+, HER2-, Ki-67 low <14%), Luminal B (ER+/PR+, HER2- high Ki-67, or ER+/PR+ HER2+), HER2-enriched (ER-PR-, HER2+), and Triple-negative (ER-, PR-, HER2-); treatment: endocrine therapy (tamoxifen or aromatase inhibitors) for ER+; trastuzumab (Herceptin, anti-HER2 mAb) ± pertuzumab for HER2+; chemotherapy for TNBC (PD-L1 checkpoint inhibitors for TNBC)",C:"Only ER is needed for breast carcinoma IHC; HER2 is tested only in metastatic disease",D:"The standard IHC panel for breast carcinoma includes CK7, CK20, and TTF-1 to determine the primary site of origin"},correct:"B",explanation:"Breast carcinoma IHC classification: ER: nuclear staining of cancer cell nuclei by Allred score (proportion + intensity, 0-8) or H-score (proportion × intensity, 0-300); positive if ≥1% of tumor cells stain (ASCO/CAP 2020 guidelines). PR: similar scoring; PR positivity indicates hormone sensitivity and better prognosis. HER2: membrane staining assessed by IHC (0/1+/2+/3+) and FISH (HER2:CEP17 ratio; gene copy number): IHC 3+ (strong complete membrane, >10% cells) = positive; IHC 0 or 1+ = negative; IHC 2+ (equivocal) → reflex FISH. HER2-low: IHC 1+ or IHC 2+/FISH non-amplified — now a targetable category (trastuzumab deruxtecan/T-DXd for HR+/HER2-low or TNBC/HER2-low metastatic BC). Molecular subtypes (surrogate IHC): Luminal A (ER+/PR+, HER2-, low Ki-67): best prognosis; Luminal B HER2- (ER+, high Ki-67 or low PR): intermediate; Luminal B HER2+ (ER+, HER2+); HER2-enriched (ER-/PR-, HER2+); Triple-negative (ER-/PR-/HER2-): poorest prognosis, no targeted therapy until atezolizumab/pembrolizumab for PD-L1+. Oncotype DX (21-gene recurrence score): predicts chemotherapy benefit in ER+/HER2-/node-negative BC.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Breast carcinoma IHC"},
    {question:"Epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition (EMT) is a key process in cancer invasion and metastasis. What molecular changes define EMT?",options:{A:"EMT is defined by upregulation of E-cadherin and downregulation of vimentin; cells become more epithelial and less invasive",B:"EMT involves: loss of epithelial markers (E-cadherin, EpCAM, claudins, ZO-1, MUC1), gain of mesenchymal markers (N-cadherin, vimentin, fibronectin, alpha-SMA, FSP1), acquisition of migratory and invasive properties (MMP-2/9/14 expression, lamellipodia/invadopodia formation), and resistance to apoptosis (anoikis resistance); driven by TGF-beta, Wnt, Notch, HGF/Met, Snail, Slug (SNAI1/2), ZEB1/2, TWIST1 TFs",C:"EMT is a reversible process in cancer but not in normal development; in development it is irreversible",D:"EMT specifically requires loss of the p53 tumor suppressor; all p53 mutant tumors undergo EMT"},correct:"B",explanation:"Epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition (EMT): First described in developmental biology (gastrulation, neural crest delamination, heart valve formation), EMT is reactivated in cancer. Type 3 EMT (cancer EMT): partial or complete loss of epithelial characteristics and acquisition of mesenchymal features. Molecular changes: Loss: E-cadherin (CDH1, transcriptionally silenced by Snail1/2, ZEB1/2, TWIST1/2, which bind E-box elements in the CDH1 promoter); claudins; occludin; EpCAM; cytokeratins (epithelial IFs). Gain: N-cadherin (CDH2, 'cadherin switching' — promotes adhesion to stromal fibroblasts); vimentin (mesenchymal IF); fibronectin; alpha-smooth muscle actin (ACTA2); FSP1 (fibroblast-specific protein 1/S100A4); MMP-2, -9, -14 (matrix metalloproteinases for basement membrane invasion). Transcription factors driving EMT: Snail1 (SNAI1): E-cadherin repressor, induced by TGF-beta (Smad), HGF, EGF, IL-6; Snail2/Slug (SNAI2); ZEB1/2: represses miR-200 (which represses ZEB) → double-negative feedback loop; Twist1/2: represses CDH1. Signaling pathways: TGF-beta (Smad3-mediated, non-Smad — ERK, Akt); Wnt (Snail stabilization); Notch; HGF/Met; EGFR; NF-kB. Consequences: invasion, intravasation, anoikis resistance (anchorage-independent survival), circulating tumor cells (CTCs), metastasis initiation; cancer stem cell (CSC) properties (CD44high/CD24low in breast). The reverse process (MET — mesenchymal-to-epithelial transition) may be required for metastatic colonization.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"EMT"},
    {question:"The CFTR protein is critical for epithelial chloride transport. What is the molecular defect in classic cystic fibrosis (CF, F508del/F508del) and what does ivacaftor/lumacaftor/elexacaftor-tezacaftor-ivacaftor target?",options:{A:"CF is caused by a CFTR gene duplication; the extra CFTR protein is toxic to epithelial cells",B:"F508del: deletion of phenylalanine at position 508 in CFTR (class II mutation) → misfolded CFTR protein retained in the ER by CFAP/calnexin quality control and targeted for ERAD → virtually no CFTR reaches the apical membrane. Loss of CFTR Cl-/HCO3- channel → no Cl- secretion → compensatory Na+ hyperabsorption via ENaC → thick, dehydrated mucus → viscous plugging of airways, pancreatic ducts, vas deferens. Lumacaftor/tezacaftor/elexacaftor: CFTR 'correctors' that help F508del-CFTR fold correctly and escape ER retention → more CFTR at cell surface. Ivacaftor (VX-770): CFTR 'potentiator' — opens CFTR channel once it reaches the membrane (targets G551D gating mutation or F508del after correction). Triple therapy (elexacaftor-tezacaftor-ivacaftor, Trikafta): dramatically improves FEV1 and quality of life in F508del/F508del (>90% of CF patients)",C:"F508del causes CFTR to reach the plasma membrane normally but with reduced chloride channel conductance; treatment is replacing CFTR by gene therapy",D:"CFTR is a Na+ channel; F508del reduces Na+ absorption, causing diarrhea and hyponatremia"},correct:"B",explanation:"CFTR biology and pharmacology: CFTR (cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator): ABC transporter superfamily member; works as a Cl-/HCO3- channel (not a pump); activated by PKA phosphorylation (cAMP-dependent, via beta-2 adrenergic or VIP signaling) + ATP binding/hydrolysis at NBDs. Structure: 2 transmembrane domains (TMDs) + 2 nucleotide-binding domains (NBDs) + regulatory domain (R domain, phosphorylated by PKA). CF mutations classified by mechanism: Class I: stop/nonsense, no protein (e.g., W1282X); Class II: misfolding/ERAD (F508del, most common, ~70% of alleles); Class III: reaches membrane but gating defect (G551D — responds to ivacaftor alone); Class IV: reduced conductance; Class V: reduced production; Class VI: accelerated degradation at PM. F508del consequences: F508del-CFTR is >99% retained in ER by calnexin and CHIP/Hsc70 ERAD machinery and degraded by proteasomes → absent CFTR at apical membrane → no Cl- secretion → high-volume Na+ absorption via ENaC (CFTR normally inhibits ENaC) → mucus dehydration → viscous, acidic mucus → bronchiectasis, Pseudomonas aeruginosa chronic infection, pancreatic insufficiency (exocrine → endocrine eventually → CFRD), meconium ileus (15% neonates), male infertility (bilateral absence vas deferens). Therapeutics: Ivacaftor (VX-770): potentiator — increases channel open probability; effective for class III (G551D). Lumacaftor + ivacaftor (Orkambi): corrector + potentiator; modest benefit F508del. Tezacaftor + ivacaftor (Symdeko): better F508del corrector. Elexacaftor + tezacaftor + ivacaftor (Trikafta, 2019): highly effective for F508del — dramatically reduces sweat chloride, normalizes spirometry; approved age ≥2 years.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"CFTR"},
    {question:"Cholangiopathy refers to diseases of the biliary epithelium (cholangiocytes). Primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) is an immune-mediated cholangiopathy. What is its characteristic histological finding in the bile ducts?",options:{A:"Primary biliary cholangitis (PBC): florid duct lesion (granulomatous destruction of interlobular bile ducts); PSC: 'onion skin' fibrosis (concentric periductal fibrosis around medium to large bile ducts) with eventual duct obliteration and replacement by fibrotic cords",B:"PSC is characterized by eosinophilic infiltration of bile duct walls (eosinophilic cholangiopathy)",C:"PSC is characterized by IgG4-positive plasma cell infiltration around bile ducts; this distinguishes it from IgG4-related cholangiopathy",D:"PSC shows a 'chicken-wire' pattern of IgA deposits along the bile duct basement membrane by immunofluorescence"},correct:"A",explanation:"PSC vs PBC histology: Primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC): Etiology: idiopathic immune-mediated (strong association with IBD, especially UC; HLA-B8/DR3/DR2 haplotype). Affects medium and large bile ducts (extrahepatic and large intrahepatic — 'large duct PSC'). Hallmark histology: 'Onion-skin' (concentric periductal) fibrosis — layers of fibrous tissue concentrically surrounding bile ducts; duct lumen eventually obliterated and replaced by a characteristic fibrous scar ('tombstone' fibrous cord). Also: duct loss, cholestasis, and ultimately cirrhosis (biliary cirrhosis). Cholangiography (MRCP/ERCP): 'beaded' or 'pruned tree' appearance of the biliary tree (alternating strictures and dilatations). Complications: cholangiocarcinoma (10-15% lifetime risk), dominant strictures, bacterial cholangitis, portal hypertension. No proven medical therapy (no response to immunosuppression in trials); liver transplantation for advanced disease. Primary biliary cholangitis (PBC, formerly PBC = primary biliary cirrhosis): autoimmune destruction of small intrahepatic bile ducts; antimitochondrial antibodies (AMA, anti-PDC-E2, positive in ~95%); histology: florid duct lesion (granulomatous inflammation with lymphocytes and histiocytes surrounding and destroying interlobular bile ducts — a specific finding); treated with ursodeoxycholic acid. IgG4-related cholangitis: abundant IgG4+ plasma cells (IgG4:IgG ratio >40%); responds to steroids.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Biliary pathology"},
    {question:"The proximal convoluted tubule (PCT) reabsorbs approximately 67% of filtered Na+, water, glucose, amino acids, and bicarbonate. What is the mechanism of glucose reabsorption in the PCT?",options:{A:"Glucose is reabsorbed via GLUT2 (facilitated diffusion) on the apical membrane of PCT cells; no sodium is required",B:"Na+/glucose co-transport: SGLT2 (SLC5A2, sodium-glucose co-transporter 2) in the apical (luminal) membrane of the S1 segment of the PCT co-transports 1 Na+ and 1 glucose into the cell (secondary active transport driven by Na+ gradient maintained by basolateral Na+/K+-ATPase); GLUT2 (SLC2A2) on the basolateral membrane then exports glucose into the peritubular capillary by facilitated diffusion; SGLT1 in the S3 segment reabsorbs remaining glucose with 2 Na+:1 glucose stoichiometry",C:"PCT glucose reabsorption requires ATP-dependent glucose pumps on both the apical and basolateral membranes",D:"Glucose is not reabsorbed in the PCT; it is reabsorbed only in the loop of Henle"},correct:"B",explanation:"PCT glucose reabsorption: The kidney filters ~180 g of glucose per day; essentially all is reabsorbed in the PCT (no glucose in normal urine). Mechanism: S1 segment (early PCT): SGLT2 (SLC5A2) — high capacity, low affinity; 1:1 Na+:glucose stoichiometry; accounts for ~90% of glucose reabsorption. S3 segment (late PCT/proximal straight tubule): SGLT1 (SLC5A1) — low capacity, high affinity; 2:1 Na+:glucose stoichiometry; mops up remaining glucose. Basolateral export: GLUT2 (S1, S3) and GLUT1 (S3) → glucose exits to peritubular capillary. The driving force for SGLT-mediated transport: Na+/K+-ATPase on the basolateral membrane maintains low intracellular Na+ → inward Na+ electrochemical gradient drives Na+/glucose co-transport. Glucosuria (glucose in urine): when plasma glucose > renal threshold (~180 mg/dL in T2DM, ~180-200 mg/dL) → SGLT2 transport maximum exceeded → glucosuria. SGLT2 inhibitors (gliflozins: empagliflozin, dapagliflozin, canagliflozin): block SGLT2 → glucosuria → lower blood glucose, reduce HbA1c, reduce cardiovascular events and hospitalizations for heart failure (cardiorenal protection via multiple mechanisms), reduce diabetic kidney disease progression. Fanconi syndrome: generalized proximal tubule dysfunction → glucosuria + phosphaturia + aminoaciduria + bicarbonaturia despite normal plasma levels.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Renal tubule transport"},
    {question:"H. pylori eradication using 'triple therapy' includes a proton pump inhibitor (PPI). What is the mechanism of action of PPIs on gastric parietal cells?",options:{A:"PPIs are competitive antagonists of the histamine H2 receptor on parietal cells, preventing cAMP-mediated stimulation of the proton pump",B:"PPIs (omeprazole, pantoprazole, lansoprazole, rabeprazole, esomeprazole) are prodrugs that are acid-activated in the secretory canaliculus of parietal cells to form sulfenamide derivatives that irreversibly covalently bind (via disulfide bonds) to cysteine residues (C813 and C822 are critical) on the luminal domain of the H+/K+-ATPase (gastric proton pump) → permanent inhibition until new pump is synthesized; duration of acid suppression ~24-36 hours (limited by pump synthesis turnover, not PPI half-life)",C:"PPIs directly block the gastrin receptor (CCK2R) on ECL cells, preventing ECL cells from releasing histamine",D:"PPIs inhibit carbonic anhydrase in parietal cells, preventing CO2 hydration to H+ and HCO3-, thereby reducing the substrate for proton secretion"},correct:"B",explanation:"Proton pump inhibitor (PPI) mechanism: Gastric acid secretion: parietal cells (oxyntic cells) secrete HCl via the H+/K+-ATPase (gastric proton pump, P-type ATPase): electroneutral exchange of H+ into the canalicular lumen for K+ uptake; H+ generated by carbonic anhydrase II (CO2 + H2O → H2CO3 → H+ + HCO3-); Cl- secreted via CFTR/ClC-2. PPIs are weak bases (prodrugs, pKa ~4.0) that are orally absorbed as neutral molecules → enter systemic circulation → concentrated in the acidic secretory canaliculus of active parietal cells (pH ~1.0) → protonated twice → rearranges to active sulfenamide → reacts with cysteine residues (Cys813 in humans — in the proton-translocating domain; also Cys822 — in the K+-binding domain) of the alpha-subunit of H+/K+-ATPase → covalent disulfide bond → irreversible inhibition. Inhibition lasts until new pump protein is synthesized (gastric pump half-life ~18 hours → clinical effect 24-48h). PPIs require activation at acidic pH → should be taken 30-60 min before meals (when parietal cells are stimulated to secrete acid → canaliculi are acidic → more pump activation). Adverse effects: hypomagnesemia (long-term), vitamin B12 malabsorption (acid required for cobalamin release from food proteins; crystalline B12 not affected), C. difficile risk, osteoporosis/fractures (reduced Ca2+ absorption without acid), CKD risk (long-term). Compare H2 blockers (famotidine, ranitidine): competitive antagonists of histamine H2 receptor → reduce cAMP → less PKA → less pump activation → reversible, less effective acid suppression.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Gastric acid secretion"},
    {question:"The cervical transformation zone (TZ) is the junction between the ectocervix (stratified squamous) and endocervix (simple columnar). Why is the TZ particularly susceptible to HPV-related carcinogenesis?",options:{A:"The TZ is the most vascularized area of the cervix, providing HPV virions with easy access to the bloodstream",B:"The TZ contains metaplastic squamous cells (formed by squamous metaplasia of the original columnar epithelium) with a population of squamocolumnar junction (SCJ) cells (p63+/CK7+ reserve cells) that are immature and highly mitotically active; these reserve/immature metaplastic cells express alpha-6 integrin (the primary HPV receptor complex with laminin-5) in the basal layer, making them uniquely permissive to HPV infection and transformation; high-risk HPV (HPV 16, 18) integrates and expresses E6 (degrades p53) + E7 (inactivates Rb family) → CIN → SCC or adenocarcinoma",C:"The TZ is susceptible because it uniquely expresses the HPV receptor (the alpha-6 integrin) exclusively; no other epithelial cells express this integrin",D:"HPV infects only keratinized squamous epithelium; the TZ is keratinized and therefore uniquely susceptible"},correct:"B",explanation:"Cervical TZ and HPV carcinogenesis: The original SCJ is the meeting point of the ectocervical squamous and endocervical columnar epithelium. Under the influence of the acidic vaginal pH (and estrogen), the columnar cells of the ectocervix undergo squamous metaplasia via reserve cell hyperplasia → immature metaplastic squamous cells. The TZ (between the original SCJ and the new SCJ after metaplasia) contains a mix of original glands and overlying metaplastic squamous cells. The 'squamocolumnar junction cells' at the new SCJ are particularly susceptible to HPV because: they express alpha-6 integrin (HPV capsid L1 protein binds heparan sulfate proteoglycans on the cell surface → L2 exposes a binding site → L1/L2 bind alpha-6 integrin on the basal cell membrane as a secondary receptor → endocytosis); they are mitotically active (cycling cells needed for HPV genome replication); they are partially differentiated (HPV requires differentiating keratinocytes for vegetative replication). High-risk HPV (16 especially): E6 binds E6-AP (UBE3A) → forms an E3 ubiquitin ligase complex → ubiquitinates and degrades p53 → eliminates p53-mediated DNA damage checkpoint and apoptosis; E7 binds Rb family (pRb, p107, p130) via LXCXE motif → displaces E2F → uncontrolled S-phase entry + induction of INK4A/p16 (compensatory, used as biomarker of high-risk HPV cell transformation by p16 IHC). Progression: normal → CIN1 (HPV effect, low-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion/LSIL) → CIN2-3 (high-grade/HSIL) → invasive squamous cell carcinoma or adenocarcinoma.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Cervical pathology"},
    {question:"The collecting duct of the kidney has two major cell types: principal cells and intercalated cells. What are their respective functions?",options:{A:"Principal cells: H+ secretion via proton-ATPase; intercalated cells: Na+ and K+ transport and water reabsorption",B:"Principal cells (PC, ~65% of CD cells): Na+ reabsorption via ENaC (apical) + Na+/K+-ATPase (basolateral) → aldosterone-regulated Na+ reabsorption; K+ secretion via ROMK (renal outer medullary K+ channel, KCNJ1, apical) and BK (maxi-K) channels; water reabsorption via AQP2 (apical, inserted in response to ADH/vasopressin via V2 receptor → cAMP → PKA → AQP2 vesicle fusion) and AQP3/4 (basolateral, constitutive). Intercalated cells (IC, ~35%): A-type (alpha) IC: apical H+/K+-ATPase and V-type H+-ATPase (H+ secretion into urine → acid excretion); basolateral Cl-/HCO3- exchanger (AE1/SLC4A1) → HCO3- reabsorption. B-type (beta) IC: apical Cl-/HCO3- exchanger (pendrin/SLC26A4) → HCO3- secretion; basolateral H+-ATPase.",C:"Principal cells produce renin; intercalated cells produce aldosterone",D:"Principal cells are exclusively found in the cortical collecting duct; intercalated cells are exclusively in the medullary collecting duct"},correct:"B",explanation:"Collecting duct cell biology: Principal cells (PCs): The 'targets' of aldosterone and ADH (vasopressin). Aldosterone → SGK1 → NEDD4L phosphorylation → ENaC membrane stability; also increases Na+/K+-ATPase subunit expression → more Na+ absorbed, K+ secreted into tubular lumen (lost in urine). ROMK (KCNJ1) mutations → Bartter syndrome type 2. Vasopressin (ADH) → V2R (AVPR2, Gs-coupled) → cAMP → PKA → AQP2 phosphorylation at Ser256 → AQP2-containing vesicle fusion with apical membrane → water reabsorption (water exits via basolateral AQP3/4). Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus: V2R mutations (X-linked, AVPR2) or AQP2 mutations → no response to ADH → polyuria. Intercalated cells (ICs): Type A (alpha, acid-secreting): apical V-type H+-ATPase (vacuolar, ATP-dependent proton pump into urine — critical for net acid excretion); also apical H+/K+-ATPase (secretes H+, reabsorbs K+ — active in hypokalemia). Basolateral: Cl-/HCO3- exchanger (AE1/SLC4A1 or band 3 protein) exports HCO3- into blood (completes the bicarbonate reabsorption process). Distal renal tubular acidosis (dRTA type 1): AE1 or H+-ATPase mutations → failure to acidify urine. Type B (beta, base-secreting): apical pendrin (SLC26A4, Cl-/HCO3- exchanger) secretes HCO3- into tubular lumen (excretes alkali); important in metabolic alkalosis correction. Basolateral V-type H+-ATPase.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Collecting duct"},
    {question:"Oncocytes/Hurthle cells in thyroid gland and oncocytomas in kidney represent neoplastic cells with markedly increased mitochondria. What is the mechanism and why does this occur?",options:{A:"Oncocytes have lost their mitochondria entirely; the eosinophilic cytoplasm reflects accumulated glycogen",B:"Oncocytes have markedly increased mitochondrial number (mitochondrial accumulation) — visible as abundant eosinophilic granular cytoplasm on H&E (corresponding to the dense packing of abnormal mitochondria, many with abnormal cristae); caused by mutations in mitochondrial DNA (especially complex I subunit genes) or nuclear-encoded mitochondrial genes → impaired oxidative phosphorylation → compensatory mitochondrial biogenesis (via PGC-1alpha) → vicious cycle; found in: Hurthle cell (oncocytic follicular cell) neoplasms of the thyroid, oncocytoma of kidney (benign, with deletion of chromosome 1 and loss of Y), oncocytic variant of Warthin tumor (parotid gland), oncocytoma of the salivary glands, pheochromocytoma",C:"Oncocytes are plasma cells that have accumulated immunoglobulin light chains; the granular cytoplasm reflects Russell bodies",D:"Oncocytes develop as a result of amyloid deposition within the cytoplasm of normal cells"},correct:"B",explanation:"Oncocytes: Pathology: Cells with abnormally abundant, dysfunctional mitochondria. EM shows the cytoplasm packed with atypical mitochondria (many with abnormal, stacked cristae or cristolysis). H&E: large cells with abundant, uniformly eosinophilic, granular cytoplasm (the granularity = individual mitochondria too small to resolve by LM, but their density creates pink granularity); large round nuclei with prominent nucleoli. IHC: cytochrome c oxidase (COX) + in some but COX-deficient in others (mutant COX subunits). Pathogenesis: Mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) mutations: large deletions or point mutations in Complex I, III, IV subunit genes → electron transport chain dysfunction → impaired ATP synthesis → PGC-1alpha-driven compensatory mitochondrial biogenesis → more mitochondria generated but they are dysfunctional → cycle continues. Nuclear gene mutations encoding mitochondrial proteins (SDHA, etc.) can also drive oncocytic change. Clinical examples: (1) Hurthle cell (oncocytic) adenoma and carcinoma of the thyroid: aggressive behavior; RAS mutations, TERT promoter mutations in malignant; less likely to take up 131I than follicular carcinoma; (2) Renal oncocytoma: benign (usually); mitochondrial complex I mutations; loss of chromosome 1p and sex chromosomes; characteristic spoke-wheel architecture on CT; (3) Warthin tumor (cystadenolymphoma) of the parotid gland: bilayered oncocytic epithelium + lymphoid stroma; benign; bilateral in 10%; strong tobacco association.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Oncocytic lesions"},
    {question:"Intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasms (IPMN) of the pancreas arise from the ductal epithelium. What histological and molecular features are used to assess their malignant potential?",options:{A:"IPMN malignant potential is assessed only by imaging (CT/MRI); histology does not contribute to risk stratification",B:"IPMN malignant potential assessed by: (1) Growth pattern/type: main duct IPMN (higher risk >70% malignancy when >10mm dilation) vs branch duct IPMN (lower risk 20-30%); (2) Histological subtype: intestinal (MUC2+, CDX2+, low risk, associated with colloid carcinoma), gastric (MUC5AC+, most common, relatively low risk, associated with conventional PDAC), pancreatobiliary (MUC1+, MUC6+, high-grade, worst prognosis), oncocytic (ARHGAP26 mutations, distinct); (3) Dysplasia grade: low-grade vs high-grade dysplasia (previously moderate dysplasia eliminated from the 3-tier system); (4) Molecular: KRAS mutations early (60-80%), GNAS mutations (nearly pathognomonic for IPMN, ~60%, activates AC → cAMP → PKA → mucin secretion), SMAD4 loss and TP53 mutations in high-grade/invasive",C:"IPMN malignant potential is determined only by Ki-67 index; Ki-67 >3% = malignant",D:"All IPMNs are benign by definition; invasive carcinoma associated with an IPMN is classified separately as pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma without IPMN designation"},correct:"B",explanation:"IPMN (Intraductal Papillary Mucinous Neoplasm): Arise from main pancreatic duct or branch ducts. Grossly: mucin-producing cysts visible as grape-like clusters or dilated ducts. Histology: papillary epithelial proliferations lining the dilated ducts with variable dysplasia. Classification by epithelial subtype (2010 WHO): Gastric type (most common, 60-70%): low columnar mucous cells resembling gastric foveolar cells; MUC5AC+, MUC6+, CDX2-; associated with KRAS mutations; often in branch ducts; usually low-grade; associated with tubular carcinoma (conventional PDAC) if invasive. Intestinal type (~25%): tall columnar cells with apical mucin and pseudostratified nuclei resembling villous adenoma; MUC2+, CDX2+, MUC5AC+; in main duct; associated with colloid carcinoma (mucinous non-cystic) if invasive — better prognosis than PDAC. Pancreatobiliary type (5%): cuboidal cells with arborizing papillae; MUC1+, MUC6+; high-grade dysplasia common; if invasive → tubular carcinoma with poor prognosis. Oncocytic type: now considered IOPN (intraductal oncocytic papillary neoplasm); ARHGAP26 fusions. Molecular: KRAS (early activating mutations, G12D/V/R); GNAS (activating mutations Arg201Cys/His in Gs-alpha → cAMP → mucin secretion → pathognomonic for IPMN vs serous cystadenoma); high-grade progression: TP53, SMAD4 loss (as in PDAC). Management: main-duct IPMN (>10mm dilation, mural nodules, positive cytology) → surgery; branch-duct IPMN surveillance with MRI/EUS.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Pancreatic cystic neoplasms"},
    {question:"Adenoid cystic carcinoma (AdCC) is a salivary gland malignancy with characteristic histological patterns. What is its key molecular alteration?",options:{A:"AdCC is driven by KRAS mutations and shows mucinous differentiation similar to pancreatic adenocarcinoma",B:"AdCC is characterized by a translocation t(6;9) creating MYB-NFIB fusion gene in >55% of cases (or MYBL1-NFIB); myoepithelial and ductal differentiation with three growth patterns: tubular (best prognosis), cribriform (Swiss cheese/cylindromatous — most characteristic, pseudocysts filled with basophilic mucin/PAS+ material or eosinophilic basal lamina material), and solid (worst prognosis); perineural invasion is a hallmark; slow-growing but relentless with distant metastases to lung (decades later)",C:"AdCC is caused by EBV infection and shows dense lymphocytic infiltration identical to undifferentiated nasopharyngeal carcinoma",D:"AdCC has EGFR mutations in >90% of cases and responds to erlotinib treatment"},correct:"B",explanation:"Adenoid cystic carcinoma (AdCC): Most common malignant salivary gland tumor of the palate, sublingual, and submandibular glands; also occurs in the lacrimal gland, upper respiratory tract, breast, Bartholin gland. Histology: Biphasic proliferation of ductal epithelial cells (inner, CK7+, forming small luminal spaces) and myoepithelial cells (outer, p63+, SMA+, calponin+, S100+). Three growth patterns: (1) Cribriform ('Swiss cheese'): nests of cells with multiple round 'holes' (pseudocysts) filled with either basophilic glycosaminoglycans (AB+, PAS+) or eosinophilic PAS+diastase-resistant basement membrane-like material; the holes are extracellular matrix-filled spaces NOT true glandular lumina. Most common pattern. (2) Tubular: small ductal structures surrounded by myoepithelial cells; best prognosis. (3) Solid: sheets of cells without cribriform or tubular differentiation; high grade; worst prognosis. Perineural invasion (PNI): the hallmark — tumor cells invade peripheral nerves (express L1CAM and neurotrophin receptors); causes severe pain and recurrence along nerve pathways despite surgical resection. Molecular: MYB-NFIB fusion (from t(6;9)(q22;p23)) drives MYB oncogene expression → proliferation and survival. MYB amplification also occurs. Clinical: indolent locally but recurs frequently; distant metastases (lung, liver, brain) develop over 10-20 years. No effective systemic therapy currently; MYB inhibitors in development.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Salivary gland tumors"},
    {question:"Neuroendocrine tumors (NETs) arise from cells of the diffuse neuroendocrine system. The 2019 WHO classification of GEP-NETs (gastroenteropancreatic NETs) uses what grading criteria?",options:{A:"GEP-NETs are graded using tumor size only: <2cm = grade 1, 2-4cm = grade 2, >4cm = grade 3",B:"2019 WHO GEP-NET grading uses mitotic rate (/2mm2) and Ki-67 index (%): G1 (<2 mitoses AND Ki-67 <3%); G2 (2-20 mitoses OR Ki-67 3-20%); G3 (>20 mitoses OR Ki-67 >20%) — with a distinction between well-differentiated NET G3 and poorly differentiated NEC (neuroendocrine carcinoma) based on morphology, genetics, and behavior; NEC includes SCNEC (small cell type, DLL3+) and LCNEC (large cell type)",C:"GEP-NETs are graded solely by the presence or absence of lymph node metastases at diagnosis",D:"WHO 2019 classifies all neuroendocrine neoplasms as either benign or malignant using CEA levels only"},correct:"B",explanation:"2019 WHO GEP-NET classification: All neuroendocrine neoplasms (NENs) of the GI tract and pancreas are now classified as: Well-differentiated NETs (carcinoid-type morphology, organoid nesting, trabecular patterns): Graded G1, G2, or G3 by proliferation. G1 (low grade): <2 mitoses/2mm2 AND Ki-67 <3%; G2 (intermediate): 2-20 mitoses/2mm2 OR Ki-67 3-20%; G3 (high grade well-differentiated): >20 mitoses/2mm2 OR Ki-67 >20% (but retaining well-differentiated morphology; often harbor DAXX/ATRX mutations in PanNETs, or CDK4 amplification). Poorly differentiated NECs (neuroendocrine carcinomas): always high grade (>20 mitoses, Ki-67 often >55%); morphologically distinct from G3 NETs; two types: Small cell NEC (SCNEC): cells with scant cytoplasm, 'salt and pepper' chromatin; DLL3+; TP53/RB1 mutations; very poor prognosis; treated like SCLC (platinum + etoposide). Large cell NEC (LCNEC): large cells with prominent nucleoli; also TP53/RB1 mutations. Key distinction: well-differentiated G3 NET vs LCNEC — the former often has MEN1/DAXX/ATRX mutations and a better prognosis than LCNEC; they should NOT be treated with SCLC-type chemotherapy. IHC: all NETs/NECs: synaptophysin+, chromogranin+/- (weak in LCNEC), INSM1+. Ki-67 assessed in the 'hot spot' area (highest proliferating region).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Neuroendocrine tumors"},
    {question:"The inner ear contains specialized sensory epithelium. Hair cells of the organ of Corti transduce sound waves into electrical signals. What is the mechanoelectrical transduction (MET) mechanism?",options:{A:"Sound waves cause hair cell depolarization via voltage-gated Na+ channels that open when the basilar membrane vibrates",B:"Sound waves → basilar membrane vibration → deflection of stereocilia bundles toward the tall stereocilia (kinocilium in vestibular hair cells) → tip links (connecting adjacent stereocilia tips, composed of protocadherin-15 and cadherin-23) pull open MET channels (TMC1/TMC2 — transmembrane channel-like proteins, non-selective cation channels, K+ and Ca2+ conductance from endolymph) → K+ and Ca2+ influx → hair cell depolarization → basolateral voltage-gated Ca2+ channels open → synaptic vesicle exocytosis of glutamate onto Type I/II afferent fibers → auditory nerve signal to cochlear nucleus",C:"Hair cell depolarization occurs via stretch-activated chloride channels in the lateral membrane; sound waves laterally stretch the hair cell body",D:"Sound transduction requires ATP release by hair cells; ATP activates P2X receptors on spiral ganglion neurons, bypassing direct neurotransmitter release"},correct:"B",explanation:"Cochlear hair cell MET: The organ of Corti rests on the basilar membrane inside the scala media (cochlear duct, filled with endolymph — high K+, low Na+, low Ca2+ — maintained by the stria vascularis via K+ recycling through Cx26 gap junctions). Hair cells have stereocilia bundles (60-300 stereocilia, increasing in height from the modiolar to the abneural side; outer hair cells (OHCs) and inner hair cells (IHCs)). Tip links: extracellular filaments connecting the tip of a shorter stereocilium to the side of the adjacent taller one; composed of: upper end — CDH23 (cadherin-23, DFNB12 mutations → congenital deafness + Usher 1D); lower end — PCDH15 (protocadherin-15, DFNB23/Usher 1F). MET (mechanosensory transduction): Sound → basilar membrane deflection → stereocilia tilt (excitatory: toward the tall stereocilia; inhibitory: away) → tip link tension → TMC1/TMC2 channels (confirmed MET channels; controlled by stiffness of tip links; also require LHFPL5/TMIE as auxiliary subunits) open → K+ enters from endolymph (Ek=-90mV in endolymph vs -70mV inside hair cell) AND Ca2+) → depolarization → basolateral dihydropyridine-insensitive (Cav1.3) Ca2+ channels open → ribbon synapse exocytosis of glutamate. IHCs: primary auditory afferent cells (Type I spiral ganglion neurons). OHCs: electromotility via prestin (SLC26A5) — somatic electromotility amplifies cochlear mechanics. Connexin 26 (GJB2) mutations → most common genetic hearing loss (autosomal recessive DFNB1).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Sensory epithelium"},
    {question:"Pemphigoid gestationis (herpes gestationis) is an autoimmune blistering disease of pregnancy. What is the target antigen and which pregnancy-related mechanism triggers autoimmunity?",options:{A:"Pemphigoid gestationis targets desmoglein 3 (identical to pemphigus vulgaris) and is triggered by elevated progesterone stimulating Dsg3 expression in the amnion",B:"Pemphigoid gestationis targets BP180 (collagen XVII) — the same antigen as bullous pemphigoid; the immune mechanism involves aberrant MHC II expression (HLA-DR3, HLA-DR4 haplotype) on placental amnion cells → presentation of BP180 epitopes → maternal IgG1 anti-BP180 antibodies formed during pregnancy → cross-react with skin BP180 → subepidermal blistering; begins periumbilically, spreads; can affect the neonate transiently (neonatal pemphigoid gestationis) due to IgG placental transfer; direct IF: linear C3 ± IgG at BMZ",C:"Pemphigoid gestationis targets desmoglein 1 in the granular layer; it is caused by high estrogen levels stimulating Dsg1 expression in the epidermis",D:"Pemphigoid gestationis is an IgA-mediated disease targeting type VII collagen; it is not related to bullous pemphigoid"},correct:"B",explanation:"Pemphigoid gestationis (PG, formerly herpes gestationis — a misnomer, no herpes virus involvement): Pathogenesis: During pregnancy, placental trophoblast/amnion cells (HLA-DR3/DR4 positive) aberrantly express MHC class II molecules and present BP180 (COL17A1 — the NC16A domain of BP180, same immunodominant epitope as BP) to maternal CD4+ T helper cells → IgG1 anti-BP180 antibodies produced. These anti-BP180 IgG cross-react with maternal skin basement membrane → complement activation (linear C3 deposit) → eosinophil and neutrophil recruitment → MMP/elastase release → subepidermal blister formation. Clinical: Intensely pruritic urticarial papules and plaques beginning periumbilically, spreading to trunk and extremities; bullae form in more severe cases. Typically begins in the 2nd or 3rd trimester (occasionally 1st trimester or immediately postpartum). Direct IF: linear C3 (most sensitive and specific — >100%) ± linear IgG at BMZ (in 30-50% only). Indirect IF: circulating anti-BMZ IgG in ~80% (complement-fixing); confirmed on monkey esophagus. Neonatal PG: transplacental IgG transfer → neonatal skin blisters (self-limiting as maternal IgG catabolized). Treatment: topical clobetasol (mild) or systemic prednisolone (moderate-severe). Flares at delivery and with subsequent pregnancies (immunological 'boosting').",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Pregnancy-related dermatoses"},
    {question:"Mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphoma arises from B-cells in the mucosa. What is the pathogenic mechanism in gastric MALT lymphoma?",options:{A:"Gastric MALT lymphoma is caused by EBV infection of gastric mucosal B cells; H. pylori is not involved",B:"H. pylori infection → chronic antigen-specific T-cell activation (H. pylori-reactive CD4+ T helper cells) → T cell-dependent stimulation of B cells in the gastric lamina propria (which form reactive lymphoid follicles — MALT) → B cells undergo somatic hypermutation and class switching → clonal B cell expansion driven by continuous H. pylori antigen stimulation → MALT lymphoma; t(11;18)(q21;q21) creating API2-MALT1 fusion (most common translocation, ~30%) → NF-kB activation independent of antigen → antibiotic-resistant MALT lymphoma; Stage IE/IIE H. pylori-positive MALT lymphoma (without t(11;18)) → H. pylori eradication therapy → complete remission in ~75%",C:"Gastric MALT lymphoma is triggered by NSAID use; B cells are stimulated directly by prostaglandin E2 from the gastric mucosa",D:"Gastric MALT lymphoma arises from T cells, not B cells; the lymphoma is CD3+ and CD20-"},correct:"B",explanation:"Gastric MALT lymphoma (extranodal marginal zone lymphoma of MALT type): H. pylori gastritis → reactive MALT (mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue, normally absent from the stomach; H. pylori induces its formation). Pathogenesis: H. pylori-reactive T helper cells activate autoreactive/H. pylori-specific B cells via CD40L-CD40 interaction and cytokines (IL-2, IL-4) → B cell proliferation in gastric mucosa. The lymphoma is initially antigen-driven and dependent on T-helper cell stimulation for survival. Key translocations (NF-kB activation → antigen-independence): t(11;18)(q21;q21)/API2-MALT1 (most common, ~30%): MALT1 is a paracaspase; API2-MALT1 fusion protein constitutively activates NF-kB → H. pylori-independent growth → antibiotics alone NOT sufficient; t(1;14)(p22;q32)/BCL10-IGH (rarer, constitutive NF-kB via BCL10); t(14;18)(q32;q21)/MALT1-IGH. Treatment: H. pylori positive + no translocation (t11;18-negative) + Stage IE (confined to stomach): H. pylori eradication (PPI + clarithromycin + amoxicillin × 14 days) → 75-80% complete histological remission within 12-18 months. t(11;18)-positive or H. pylori-negative: require radiation therapy or rituximab-based chemotherapy. Histology: small lymphocytes with irregular nuclei (centrocyte-like) infiltrating the lamina propria; lymphoepithelial lesions (lymphocytes invading and destroying gastric glands — diagnostic); CD20+, CD5-, CD10-, BCL6 variably positive, CD43+ in some.",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"GI lymphoma"},
    {question:"Celiac disease (gluten-sensitive enteropathy) is an immune-mediated enteropathy. What is the sequence from gluten ingestion to villous atrophy?",options:{A:"Gliadin → direct toxic effect on enterocytes → enterocyte apoptosis → villous atrophy; no immune mechanism is involved",B:"Dietary gliadin (a proline-rich storage protein in wheat, rye, and barley) → digested incompletely by intestinal proteases → gliadin peptides cross the intestinal epithelium (via transcytosis or paracellular leak) → in the lamina propria, tissue transglutaminase 2 (TG2) deamidates specific glutamine residues → deamidated gliadin peptides (DGP) bind HLA-DQ2 (DQA1*05:01/DQB1*02:01, 90% of patients) or HLA-DQ8 (DQA1*03:01/DQB1*03:02) on APCs → presented to CD4+ Th1 cells → IFN-gamma, IL-21, IL-15 → intestinal inflammation → CD8+ cytotoxic T cell activation → enterocyte killing → villous atrophy; also humoral: TG2-specific IgA autoantibodies (anti-tTG IgA) and anti-DGP IgA/IgG produced",C:"Celiac disease is caused by allergy to gliadin (IgE-mediated type I hypersensitivity); mast cells degranulate in response to gliadin → rapid villous destruction",D:"Celiac disease affects only the colon; small intestinal histology is normal in active celiac disease"},correct:"B",explanation:"Celiac disease pathogenesis: Gliadin (the alcohol-soluble fraction of gluten; glutenin = glutathione-soluble fraction; together = gluten) is rich in proline-glutamine repeat sequences; human intestinal peptidases cannot efficiently cleave Pro-Pro or Pro-Gln bonds → large immunogenic peptides persist. Key peptides: α-gliadin 33-mer (resistant to all intestinal proteases); deamidated by TG2 (converts Gln → Glu, increasing negative charge) → better fit to HLA-DQ2/DQ8 binding groove → presentation to CD4+ T cells. Immune response: Innate: IL-15 from stressed enterocytes → NK-like intraepithelial lymphocytes (IELs, CD8+, NKG2D+) activated → kill enterocytes expressing MICA/MICB (MHC class I-related chain A/B, stress proteins). Adaptive: CD4+ Th1 cells → IFN-gamma, TNF-alpha, IL-21 → recruitment of CD8+ CTLs + macrophages → epithelial damage. Antibodies: TG2 (tTG) is the major autoantigen — anti-tTG IgA (>95% sensitivity in untreated celiac with normal IgA); also anti-endomysial IgA (EMA, stains monkey esophagus IF) and anti-DGP (deamidated gliadin peptide) IgG/IgA (useful in IgA deficiency — affects ~3% of celiac patients). Histology (Marsh-Oberhuber classification): Type 0 (normal); Type 1 (increased IELs >25/100 enterocytes); Type 2 (crypt hyperplasia + increased IELs); Type 3 (villous atrophy): 3a (partial), 3b (subtotal), 3c (total/flat mucosa with complete villous atrophy + crypt hyperplasia + increased IELs + cuboidal enterocytes). Refractory celiac: Type II has clonal IEL population (aberrant CD3+/CD8- IELs) → risk of enteropathy-associated T-cell lymphoma (EATL).",topic:"Epithelial Tissue 2023",subtopic:"Celiac disease"}
  ];

  var connectiveTissueQuestions = [
    {question:"Connective tissue proper is classified into loose (areolar) and dense types. What are the key differences between loose, dense regular, and dense irregular connective tissue?",options:{A:"Loose (areolar) CT: widely spaced collagen fibers (type I and III), abundant ground substance (hyaluronan, proteoglycans), numerous cells (fibroblasts, mast cells, macrophages, plasma cells, adipocytes); provides flexibility, a medium for diffusion, and immune surveillance. Dense regular CT: parallel bundles of thick type I collagen, few cells (fibroblasts/tenocytes), sparse ground substance; withstands unidirectional tension (tendons, ligaments, cornea). Dense irregular CT: randomly interwoven thick type I collagen bundles, sparse ground substance; withstands multidirectional forces (dermis reticular layer, organ capsules, joint capsules)",B:"Loose CT has no collagen; dense regular CT has only elastic fibers; dense irregular CT has type II collagen",C:"All three types contain equal amounts of collagen; the difference is only in cell type — loose CT has fibroblasts, dense regular CT has chondrocytes, dense irregular CT has osteoblasts",D:"Dense irregular CT is found in tendons; dense regular CT is found in the skin dermis; loose CT is found in the cornea"},correct:"A",explanation:"Connective tissue proper classification: Loose (areolar) CT: widely spaced, randomly arranged type I and III collagen fibers + elastic fibers in an abundant amorphous ground substance (hyaluronan, versican, fibronectin, chondroitin sulfate proteoglycans). Cellular: fibroblasts, mast cells, macrophages, lymphocytes, plasma cells, eosinophils, adipocytes. Found: in the submucosa (gut, trachea), the dermis (papillary layer), around blood vessels, nerves, and muscles (the 'packing material'). Dense regular CT: thick, parallel bundles of type I collagen aligned in the direction of stress; tenocytes (specialized fibroblasts) lie in rows between bundles (very few cells). Found: tendons (attach muscle to bone), ligaments (bone to bone), aponeuroses, cornea (orthogonally stacked layers = specialized). Withstands uniaxial tensile loads. Dense irregular CT: thick collagen bundles randomly interwoven in multiple directions; few cells (fibroblasts). Found: dermis (reticular layer), organ capsules (kidney, liver, spleen capsule), periosteum, perichondrium, sclera, tunica albuginea of testis. Withstands multidirectional tension.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"CT classification"},
    {question:"Fibroblasts synthesize the extracellular matrix components of connective tissue. What is the difference between a fibroblast and a myofibroblast?",options:{A:"Fibroblasts and myofibroblasts are identical; the terms are used interchangeably",B:"Fibroblasts: quiescent or proliferative spindle-shaped cells that synthesize collagen (types I, III, V), fibronectin, proteoglycans, and growth factors; express vimentin (IF marker) and sometimes CD34. Myofibroblasts: activated fibroblasts that additionally express alpha-smooth muscle actin (alpha-SMA/ACTA2, incorporated into stress fibers) conferring contractile ability; induced by TGF-beta1, PDGF, mechanical tension; present in granulation tissue during wound healing (promote wound contraction), in organ fibrosis, in desmoplastic stroma of carcinomas, and in myofibroblastomas; distinguished from smooth muscle cells by positive vimentin and negative h-caldesmon",C:"Myofibroblasts are embryonic fibroblasts; fibroblasts are adult myofibroblasts that have lost contractile proteins",D:"Myofibroblasts produce type IV collagen and laminin (basement membrane); fibroblasts produce only type I collagen"},correct:"B",explanation:"Fibroblast vs myofibroblast: Fibroblasts: The principal cells of connective tissue proper. Active (synthetic) fibroblasts: large, euchromatic nuclei, prominent nucleoli, abundant rER (for collagen/matrix synthesis). Quiescent fibroblasts (fibrocytes): smaller, heterochromatic nuclei. Fibroblast markers: vimentin (type III IF), CD90 (Thy1), prolyl-4-hydroxylase, PDGFR. They synthesize: fibrillar collagens (I, III, V), fibronectin, heparan sulfate proteoglycans (perlecan, syndecan), versican, decorin, biglycan, tenascin, SPARC, and growth factors (TGF-beta, FGFs, IGFs). Myofibroblasts: Fibroblasts activated by TGF-beta1 (from macrophages M2, platelets, tumor cells) and mechanical tension → acquire smooth muscle-like features: alpha-SMA+ stress fibers; expression of extra domain B fibronectin (ED-B FN), SM22 alpha. They: (1) Contract wound edges during healing (reduce wound size); (2) Synthesize granulation tissue ECM; (3) Participate in pathological fibrosis (IPF — idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis; liver cirrhosis: activation of hepatic stellate cells into myofibroblasts by TGF-beta + activated by ethanol; renal fibrosis: TGF-beta drives tubular EMT + pericyte activation into myofibroblasts). Distinction from smooth muscle cells: SMA+ but h-caldesmon-, desmin-, smoothelin-; often also vimentin+. Desmoplastic reaction in carcinomas: tumor stroma rich in cancer-associated fibroblasts (CAFs, myofibroblast-like) secreting TGF-beta, VEGF, ECM, SDF-1 → promote tumor invasion and angiogenesis.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Fibroblasts"},
    {question:"Mast cells are tissue-resident granular cells derived from bone marrow progenitors. What triggers mast cell degranulation in IgE-mediated allergy and what are the mediators released?",options:{A:"Mast cells degranulate when complement C3a and C5a bind to their surface receptors; IgE is not involved in classical allergy",B:"IgE antibodies (produced by plasma cells after first antigen exposure) bind to high-affinity FcepsilonRI receptors on mast cells; on subsequent antigen exposure, antigen crosslinks two or more IgE-FcepsilonRI complexes → receptor aggregation → intracellular signaling cascade (Lyn/Fyn → Syk → LAT → PLCgamma → IP3/DAG → Ca2+ mobilization/PKC activation) → degranulation: preformed mediators (histamine, heparin, tryptase, chymase, carboxypeptidase A3) released within seconds; also synthesis and release of newly formed mediators (PGD2, LTC4/D4/E4 via AA/5-LOX pathways) and cytokines (TNF-alpha, IL-4, IL-5, IL-13) within minutes to hours",C:"Mast cells degranulate constitutively at a slow rate regardless of antigen exposure; IgE only regulates the speed of degranulation",D:"Mast cells require direct contact with bacteria to degranulate; the FcepsilonRI receptor binds bacterial LPS, not IgE"},correct:"B",explanation:"Mast cell IgE-mediated degranulation: Sensitization phase (first exposure): dendritic cells present antigen → Th2 cells produce IL-4 and IL-13 → induce B cells to class-switch to IgE → IgE produced → binds FcepsilonRI (high-affinity IgE receptor, alpha-beta-gamma2 structure, Kd ~10-10 M) on mast cells and basophils → cells are primed. Elicitation phase (re-exposure): antigen (allergen) crosslinks ≥2 IgE-FcepsilonRI complexes → receptor aggregation → conformational change in gamma-ITAM → Lyn (src kinase, constitutively associated with beta subunit) phosphorylates ITAM on beta and gamma → Syk kinase recruited → Syk phosphorylates LAT (linker for activated T cells) → recruits PLCgamma1/2 → IP3 (→ Ca2+ from ER) + DAG (→ PKC activation) → SNARE-dependent exocytosis of granules. Preformed (granule-stored) mediators: Histamine (H1R on endothelial cells → vasodilation, vascular permeability, pruritus; H2R → gastric acid; H1R bronchial smooth muscle → bronchoconstriction); Heparin (anticoagulant); Tryptase (serine protease, diagnostic marker of anaphylaxis — serum tryptase rises within 30-60 min); Chymase; TNF-alpha. Newly synthesized: LTC4, LTD4, LTE4 (cysteinyl leukotrienes via 5-LOX/FLAP → bronchoconstriction, mucus secretion — targets for montelukast/zafirlukast); PGD2 (via COX-2 → vasodilation, bronchoconstriction); PAF. Cytokines (over hours): IL-4, IL-5, IL-13 (drive Th2 response); TNF-alpha (inflammation); IL-6. Mast cell tryptase on electron microscopy: scroll-like crystalline granule structure. Systemic mastocytosis: clonal mast cell neoplasm; KIT D816V mutation (90%); serum tryptase >20 ng/mL diagnostic criterion.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Mast cells"},
    {question:"Adipose tissue is classified into white (WAT) and brown (BAT) adipose tissue. How do they differ in function and cellular morphology?",options:{A:"WAT: multilocular lipid droplets (multiple small droplets), numerous mitochondria, expresses UCP-1, found throughout the body; BAT: unilocular lipid droplet, few mitochondria, found in the inguinal region",B:"WAT: unilocular lipid droplet (single large droplet), 'signet ring' nucleus pushed to cell periphery, few mitochondria, poor vascularization; functions: energy storage (triglycerides), endocrine (adipokines: leptin, adiponectin, resistin), thermal insulation. BAT: multilocular lipid droplets (numerous small droplets), abundant mitochondria (contain UCP-1 = thermogenin, uncouples oxidative phosphorylation → heat instead of ATP), rich vascularization; found in neonates/hibernators, and in adults (paraspinal, supraclavicular, perirenal areas); activated by cold and SNS (beta-3 adrenergic receptors)",C:"WAT and BAT have identical cytological features; the difference is only their location (WAT = subcutaneous, BAT = intra-abdominal)",D:"BAT is found only in fetuses; it disappears entirely in human adults by age 1 year"},correct:"B",explanation:"Adipose tissue types: White adipose tissue (WAT): Mature adipocyte: up to 150 microns diameter; single, large lipid droplet occupies ~95% of cell volume; nucleus peripherally displaced (crescentic, 'signet ring' appearance); thin rim of cytoplasm; few mitochondria and organelles (most cellular machinery was required only for lipid filling). Lipid stored as triglycerides. Endocrine functions: secretes adipokines — leptin (satiety signal to hypothalamus, regulates energy balance and appetite; leptin deficiency → morbid obesity; leptin resistance in common obesity); adiponectin (insulin sensitizer, anti-inflammatory; reduced in obesity, T2DM); resistin (insulin-antagonizing); FFA (free fatty acids, via ATGL/HSL lipase during fasting); inflammatory cytokines in obese adipose tissue (TNF-alpha, IL-6, MCP-1). Brown adipose tissue (BAT): Mature brown adipocyte: smaller; MULTIPLE small lipid droplets; round, centrally placed nucleus; ABUNDANT mitochondria (cristae-rich, dark on H&E = distinguishes from WAT). Brown color = iron-rich cytochrome-containing mitochondria. Key protein: UCP-1 (uncoupling protein 1, thermogenin): allows proton leak across the inner mitochondrial membrane, bypassing ATP synthase → generates heat instead of ATP. Activated by: cold exposure → sympathetic → norepinephrine → beta-3 adrenergic receptors → cAMP → PKA → HSL activation (lipolysis) + UCP-1 activity. Beige/brite adipocytes: WAT that can be 'browned' (by beta-3 agonists, cold, FGF21, Irisin from exercising muscle) — express UCP-1 when stimulated; therapeutic target for obesity and T2DM.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Adipose tissue"},
    {question:"Hyaline cartilage is the most common type of cartilage in the body. Which correctly describes its composition and the differences between the three types of cartilage?",options:{A:"Hyaline cartilage: type II collagen (fine fibrils not visible by LM) + large aggregating proteoglycans (aggrecan bound to hyaluronan via link protein) + chondrocytes in lacunae; characterized by a glassy, homogeneous matrix on H&E. Elastic cartilage: type II collagen + abundant elastic fibers (visible by LM, stain with orcein/Verhoeff) → flexible; found in auricle, epiglottis, auditory tube. Fibrocartilage: type I collagen (coarse, visible bundles) + type II collagen; chondrocytes in rows between fiber bundles; found at intervertebral discs (annulus fibrosus), pubic symphysis, menisci, tendon-bone junction (enthesis)",B:"Hyaline cartilage: type I collagen (visible on H&E); elastic cartilage: collagen IV; fibrocartilage: type III collagen only",C:"All three types of cartilage are identical in ECM composition; the difference is only in cell type (hyaline has chondrocytes; elastic has elastocytes; fibrocartilage has fibrochondrocytes)",D:"Hyaline cartilage contains a dense vascular supply; elastic cartilage is avascular; fibrocartilage is the most vascularized type"},correct:"A",explanation:"Cartilage types: Hyaline cartilage: Named for its glass-like (hyalos) appearance on H&E — the abundant proteoglycan-collagen matrix appears pale bluish-purple/pink without visible fibers (type II collagen fibrils are very fine, ~10-30 nm diameter, below LM resolution). Main proteoglycan: aggrecan (core protein + chondroitin sulfate + keratan sulfate chains) → forms 'bottle brush' structure → binds to hyaluronan via link protein → large aggregate that traps water (>80% water content) → osmotic pressure resists compressive loads. Chondrocytes in lacunae (enclosed spaces) surrounded by a pericellular matrix/capsule (type VI collagen-rich); isogenic groups (chondrocyte clusters from one parent cell). Avascular, aneural — nutrients diffuse from synovial fluid (articular) or perichondrium (non-articular). Examples: articular cartilage, costal cartilage, tracheal rings, bronchial rings, nasal septum, fetal skeleton. Elastic cartilage: type II collagen + abundant elastin fibers (visible as dense, winding fibers on H&E; best seen with Weigert's or orcein stain) → highly flexible. Perichondrium present. Examples: auricle (ear), epiglottis, cuneiform cartilages of larynx, auditory (Eustachian) tube walls. Fibrocartilage (fibrous cartilage): no perichondrium; type I collagen bundles dominate (visible on H&E); chondrocytes in lacunae in rows between collagen bundles; withstands tension as well as compression. Examples: intervertebral disc annulus fibrosus, pubic symphysis fibrocartilaginous joint, menisci, articular disc of the temporomandibular and acromioclavicular joints, tendon-to-bone enthesis.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Cartilage"},
    {question:"Chondrocytes maintain articular cartilage through synthesis and degradation of ECM. Which enzymes are primarily responsible for cartilage matrix degradation in osteoarthritis?",options:{A:"Hyaluronidase and glucuronidase — lysosomal enzymes released by dying chondrocytes",B:"ADAMTS-4 and ADAMTS-5 (aggrecanases) — cleave aggrecan between the Glu373-Ala374 bond in the interglobular domain; MMP-13 (collagenase-3) — cleaves type II collagen at the 3/4-1/4 ratio site; MMP-3 (stromelysin-1) — activates pro-MMP-13 and cleaves proteoglycans; IL-1beta and TNF-alpha from synovial macrophages and chondrocytes drive this catabolic cascade",C:"Cathepsin K — the primary collagenase in articular cartilage (identical to its role in osteoclast bone resorption)",D:"RANKL — activates osteoclasts that migrate into cartilage and degrade it; proteolytic enzymes play no direct role"},correct:"B",explanation:"Osteoarthritis (OA) cartilage degradation: In OA, the balance between anabolic (IGF-1, TGF-beta, BMP-2/7) and catabolic pathways is disrupted. Inflammatory cytokines (IL-1beta, TNF-alpha, IL-17 from synovial macrophages/chondrocytes/subchondral bone) → upregulate catabolic enzymes. Aggrecan degradation: ADAMTS-4 (aggrecanase-1) and ADAMTS-5 (aggrecanase-2) — a disintegrin and metalloproteinase with thrombospondin motifs; cleave aggrecan specifically at the Glu373-Ala374 bond in the interglobular domain (IGD) between G1 and G2 — this releases the GAG-bearing portion of aggrecan from the HA-binding G1 domain → loss of proteoglycans (first detectable change in OA — Safranin-O staining is lost from the cartilage surface). ADAMTS-5 knockout mice are protected from OA-like cartilage degradation. Type II collagen degradation: MMP-13 (collagenase-3, the primary type II collagen-degrading MMP in cartilage): cleaves the triple helix at the Gly-Ile site (3/4 from N-terminus) — gelatinases (MMP-2, MMP-9) then further degrade the denatured collagen (gelatin). MMP-3 activates pro-MMP-13 and directly cleaves proteoglycans. Other factors: RANKL upregulation → osteoclast activation in subchondral bone → subchondral sclerosis, osteophytes. Therapeutic targets: ADAMTS inhibitors (no approved drug yet), MMP-13 inhibitors (challenges with side effects), IL-1 antagonists (little clinical benefit despite preclinical promise — complexity of OA inflammatory mediators).",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Cartilage pathology"},
    {question:"Bone is a mineralized connective tissue. What are the two types of bone tissue based on structural organization, and which is found in which anatomical locations?",options:{A:"Woven bone (primary, immature): randomly arranged collagen fibers (seen in polarized light as randomly oriented birefringent domains), round osteocyte lacunae, low mineral density; first bone formed (in fracture repair, embryonic skeleton, Paget's disease, tumors — any rapid bone formation). Lamellar bone (secondary, mature): parallel collagen layers arranged in lamellae (orthogonal orientation of adjacent lamellae — 'plywood' structure seen by polarized light microscopy), flattened osteocyte lacunae in regular rows between lamellae, high mineral density; found in cortical (compact) bone and trabeculae of cancellous (spongy) bone in mature skeleton",B:"Woven bone: found in the cortex of long bones; lamellar bone: found only in the vertebral bodies",C:"Both types of bone are identical histologically; they differ only in their calcium hydroxyapatite content",D:"Woven bone is found only in articular surfaces; lamellar bone only in the diaphysis of long bones"},correct:"A",explanation:"Bone tissue types: Woven (primary) bone: Characteristics: randomly arranged collagen fibers (type I, as in all bone, but randomly interwoven → isotropic; appears equally dark on polarized LM as opposed to lamellar bone which shows alternating bright and dark lamellae). More cellular (more osteocytes per unit volume). Lower mineral content. Rapidly formed. Found: Fetal/neonatal skeleton (subsequently replaced by lamellar bone during remodeling). Fracture repair (fracture callus: woven bone formed by ossification within the cartilaginous callus → remodeled to lamellar bone). Pathological conditions requiring rapid bone formation: Paget's disease of bone (excessive osteoclastic resorption → compensatory rapid osteoblastic activity → woven bone mosaic pattern); high-grade osteosarcoma (tumor bone = woven, osteoid). Healing periapical cementum (dental). Lamellar (secondary) bone: Organized into lamellae (3-7 micron thick sheets). In cortical (compact) bone: lamellar bone organized into osteons (Haversian systems): central Haversian canal (contains blood vessels, nerves, lymphatics) surrounded by concentric lamellae with osteocyte lacunae between them; osteocytes connected by canaliculi. Interstitial lamellae: remnants of older, partially resorbed osteons. Outer and inner circumferential lamellae. In cancellous (trabecular/spongy) bone: lamellar bone arranged as trabecular sheets (no Haversian systems; relies on diffusion from marrow spaces).",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Bone tissue"},
    {question:"Osteoclasts are the cells responsible for bone resorption. What is their origin, histological appearance, and mechanism of bone resorption?",options:{A:"Osteoclasts are derived from osteoblast precursors; they are mononuclear cells with a ruffled border; they digest bone matrix using alkaline phosphatase",B:"Osteoclasts: derived from monocyte/macrophage lineage (hematopoietic progenitors — myeloid); large, multinucleated (up to 100 nuclei), located in Howship's lacunae (resorption pits); the ruffled border (extensive membrane infoldings increasing surface area) faces the bone surface and creates the 'sealed zone' (actin ring/sealing zone); V-type H+-ATPase secretes H+ → pH ~4.5 acidifies the resorption lacuna → dissolves hydroxyapatite; Cathepsin K (lysosomal cysteine protease) secreted → degrades collagen and non-collagenous proteins; regulated by RANKL (TNFSF11, from osteoblasts, stromal cells, activated T cells) → binds RANK on osteoclast precursors → fusion → activation; osteoprotegerin (OPG, decoy receptor for RANKL, secreted by osteoblasts) inhibits osteoclastogenesis",C:"Osteoclasts are derived from neural crest cells; they produce parathyroid hormone-related peptide (PTHrP) that dissolves bone",D:"Osteoclasts have a clear zone (ruffled border) and secrete matrix metalloproteinases exclusively; acid production plays no role in resorption"},correct:"B",explanation:"Osteoclast biology: Origin: monocyte/macrophage lineage; multipotent myeloid progenitor → macrophage colony-stimulating factor (M-CSF, CSF1) + RANKL → osteoclast precursor proliferation → fusion → multinucleated osteoclast (5-50+ nuclei). RANKL (receptor activator of NF-kB ligand): expressed on osteoblasts, stromal cells, osteocytes, activated T cells and dendritic cells; binds RANK on osteoclast precursors → NF-kB, NFATc1 activation → osteoclast differentiation and activation. OPG (osteoprotegerin): secreted by osteoblasts as a decoy receptor for RANKL → sequesters RANKL → inhibits RANK-RANKL interaction → suppresses osteoclastogenesis. OPG/RANKL ratio determines net bone resorption or deposition. PTH and PTHrP: reduce OPG and increase RANKL expression on osteoblasts → net increase in RANKL → osteoclast activation → bone resorption → Ca2+ release (PTH raises serum Ca2+ by stimulating osteoclastic resorption). Osteoclast resorption mechanism: (1) Attachment: osteoclast attaches to bone matrix via integrins (alphavbeta3 binds vitronectin, osteopontin RGD motifs) → sealing zone (actin ring/podosomes around the resorption pit — isolates the 'sub-osteoclastic space'); (2) Acidification: V-type H+-ATPase in ruffled border → H+ pumped → pH 4.5 → dissolves hydroxyapatite (Ca10(PO4)6(OH)2); CI- provided by ClC-7 (CLC-7) exchanger. (3) Collagenolysis: Cathepsin K (CTSK, a cysteine protease, active at pH 4-6) degrades type I collagen (unique triple-helical cleavage), TRAP (tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase, dephosphorylates OPN and bone sialoprotein). Clinical: Bisphosphonates: accumulate in bone, internalized by osteoclasts → inhibit farnesyl diphosphate synthase (FPPS) in mevalonate pathway → prevent geranylgeranylation of Rab GTPases → ruffled border disassembly → apoptosis → reduced bone resorption. Denosumab: monoclonal antibody against RANKL → prevents osteoclastogenesis.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Osteoclasts"},
    {question:"Osteoblasts synthesize and mineralize the bone matrix (osteoid). What are the key transcription factors controlling osteoblast differentiation and what markers identify osteoblasts?",options:{A:"Osteoblast differentiation is controlled by RUNX2 (Cbfa1/Osf2) — the 'master regulator,' also Osterix (Sp7), DLX5; markers: alkaline phosphatase (ALP, early, used to assess osteoblast activity clinically), osteocalcin (Gla protein, mature marker, secreted into the osteoid and blood — serum osteocalcin is a bone formation marker), osteopontin, bone sialoprotein, collagen type I",B:"Osteoblasts are controlled by Sox9 (the master regulator of chondrogenesis, not osteoblast differentiation); markers: type II collagen and aggrecan",C:"Osteoblasts are controlled by PPARG (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma), the master regulator of adipogenesis; bone formation markers include adiponectin and leptin",D:"Osteoblasts are identified by cathepsin K and TRAP positivity; RUNX2 is expressed only in osteoclasts"},correct:"A",explanation:"Osteoblast differentiation: Mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) commit to the osteoblast lineage via: RUNX2 (Runt-related TF 2, formerly CBFA1/OSF2): the master osteogenic transcription factor. Haploinsufficiency → cleidocranial dysplasia (absent or hypoplastic clavicles, large fontanelle, extra teeth). RUNX2 targets: osteocalcin (Bglap), bone sialoprotein, type I collagen, ALP, OPN. Osterix (Sp7): required downstream of RUNX2 for osteoblast maturation; Sp7 knockout mice form cartilage but no bone. DLX5 and DLX6: also osteogenic TFs. Wnt/beta-catenin: promotes osteoblast over adipocyte fate; LRP5/LRP6 co-receptor mutations → osteoporosis-pseudoglioma (LRP5 loss) or high bone mass (LRP5 GOF). BMP-2/4/7: potent osteogenic signals (downstream of BMPR → Smad1/5/8 → RUNX2 induction). Osteoblast markers: Alkaline phosphatase (ALP, ALPL): ectoenzyme on osteoblast surface; bone-specific ALP isoform; serum ALP rises in conditions of increased osteoblast activity (Paget's disease, healing fracture, hyperparathyroidism, bone metastases from prostate cancer). Mechanism: ALP cleaves pyrophosphate (PPi) → inorganic phosphate (Pi); PPi is a potent mineralization inhibitor; ALP's hydrolysis of PPi is essential for mineralization. Osteocalcin (bone Gla protein, BGP): synthesized by mature osteoblasts; requires vitamin K for gamma-carboxylation of glutamate residues (Gla) → binds hydroxyapatite; serum osteocalcin = bone formation marker. Osteopontin (OPN): acidic phosphoprotein; binds hydroxyapatite and integrins; involved in osteoclast attachment. COL1A1: most abundant bone matrix protein.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Osteoblasts"},
    {question:"Primary bone tumors include osteosarcoma, chondrosarcoma, and Ewing sarcoma. What is the characteristic histological and molecular feature that distinguishes each?",options:{A:"Osteosarcoma: neoplastic chondrocytes forming cartilage (no osteoid); chondrosarcoma: neoplastic osteoblasts forming osteoid; Ewing sarcoma: neoplastic fibroblasts forming collagen",B:"Osteosarcoma: high-grade malignant tumor with neoplastic osteoblasts forming malignant osteoid (woven bone produced directly by tumor cells — the defining feature); most common in metaphysis of distal femur/proximal tibia; Codman's triangle on X-ray; TP53, RB1 mutations; p16 deletion. Chondrosarcoma: malignant chondrocytes in cartilaginous matrix; central (within medullary cavity, often IDH1/2 mutations) or peripheral (arising from osteochondroma, EXT1/2 mutations); graded I-III based on cellularity, atypia, mitoses. Ewing sarcoma: small round blue cell tumor, monotonous sheets, necrosis, glycogen+ (PAS+); EWS-FLI1 fusion (t(11;22)) most common — diagnostic translocation",C:"Osteosarcoma and Ewing sarcoma are both defined by NF-kB signaling activation; chondrosarcoma is defined by loss of SMAD4",D:"All three primary bone tumors are histologically identical; molecular testing is the only diagnostic tool"},correct:"B",explanation:"Primary bone tumor pathology: Osteosarcoma: Most common primary malignant bone tumor (excluding myeloma and lymphoma). Age: peak 10-20 years (high bone turnover), second peak >65 (Paget's disease, radiation-associated). Location: metaphysis of long bones (65% distal femur, proximal tibia, proximal humerus — regions of fastest growth). Histology: malignant spindle cells (osteoblasts) directly producing malignant osteoid (pink, amorphous material — 'lace-like' pattern) — this osteoid production is required for diagnosis even if only focal. Subtypes: osteoblastic (most common, dense osteoid), chondroblastic (cartilaginous matrix predominates), fibroblastic (fibrous matrix). Molecular: TP53 mutations (inherited Li-Fraumeni — TP53 germline), RB1 mutations (inherited retinoblastoma → osteosarcoma risk), CDKN2A deletion, MDM2 amplification (parosteal OSA). X-ray: Codman's triangle (periosteal reaction), 'sunburst' pattern. Chondrosarcoma: Second most common primary bone malignancy. Malignant chondrocytes in lacunae within cartilaginous matrix (bluish, chondroid matrix without osteoid production). Central grade I often has IDH1 R132H (Maffucci syndrome), IDH2 mutations. Peripheral (from osteochondroma cap): EXT1/2 mutations. Grade I (low): low cellularity, mild atypia; Grade II: moderate; Grade III: high cellularity, pleomorphism, necrosis. Ewing sarcoma/PNET: t(11;22)(q24;q12) — EWS (EWSR1) fused to FLI1 (FEV family ETS TF) → chimeric oncoprotein; EWSR1-ERG (t(21;22)) and EWSR1-ETV1 are variant fusions. CD99+ (MIC2, 013 antigen) membrane staining is characteristic. PAS+ (glycogen). NKX2.2+ nuclear TF. Small, uniform round blue cells, high N:C ratio. Treatment: multiagent chemotherapy + surgery ± radiation.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Bone tumors"},
    {question:"The intervertebral disc has two distinct histological zones. What is the composition of the nucleus pulposus and annulus fibrosus, and what happens in disc degeneration?",options:{A:"Nucleus pulposus: dense type I collagen bundles; annulus fibrosus: loose areolar connective tissue with type III collagen",B:"Nucleus pulposus: notochordal remnant (nuclear pulposus cells + notochordal cells in early life), rich in water (80-88% in youth, decreasing with age), type II collagen, large aggregating proteoglycans (aggrecan, versican — high GAG content → osmotic swelling pressure resists compression); annulus fibrosus: dense fibrocartilage with concentric lamellae of type I collagen (outer) and type II collagen (inner) fibers arranged in alternating oblique directions; outer AF is anchored to vertebral endplate by Sharpey's fibers. Degeneration: decreased proteoglycan content (aggrecanase activity) → dehydration → reduced disc height → annular fissures → nuclear herniation (protrusion, extrusion, sequestration)",C:"Nucleus pulposus: chondrocytes in lacunae identical to hyaline cartilage; annulus fibrosus: type IV collagen and laminin matrix identical to basement membrane",D:"Both the nucleus pulposus and annulus fibrosus are composed entirely of elastin; degeneration occurs when elastase activity increases with age"},correct:"B",explanation:"Intervertebral disc: The disc provides shock absorption (compression) and allows flexion/extension between vertebral bodies. Nucleus pulposus (NP): Embryological origin: remnant of the notochord. Young adult NP: predominantly large proteoglycan aggregates (aggrecan + hyaluronan + link protein) in a sparse type II collagen network, with NP cells (chondrocyte-like, low O2 threshold — poorly vascularized); ~80-88% water in youth. The highly negative charges from chondroitin sulfate and keratan sulfate GAG chains create a strong osmotic pressure that draws water → turgid gel-like core that acts as a hydraulic pressure distributor. Annulus fibrosus (AF): Fibrocartilaginous, concentric lamellae (12-15 lamellae, each ~0.4 mm): outer AF — coarse type I collagen fibers anchored to vertebral body Sharpey's fibers; inner AF — type II collagen; fibers of adjacent lamellae alternate in direction (approximately 60 degrees from horizontal) → resists torsion as well as compression. Disc degeneration: Age-related (or accelerated by mechanical overload, smoking, genetic factors): Loss of proteoglycans (ADAMTS-4/5 aggrecanase activity) → dehydration (MRI: decreased disc height, dark signal on T2) → reduced disc compressibility → annular fissures (radial tears) → nuclear herniation ('disc herniation,' slipped disc): NP material protrudes through AF tears → compresses adjacent nerve root (radiculopathy) or spinal cord (myelopathy). L4-L5 and L5-S1 most commonly affected. Most herniations cause posterolateral protrusion (the posterior longitudinal ligament is thinner laterally) → compresses the exiting nerve root at that level.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Intervertebral disc"},
    {question:"Tendons are dense regular connective tissue connecting muscle to bone. What is the hierarchical structure of a tendon and what is its primary ECM protein?",options:{A:"Tendon's primary ECM protein is type II collagen (identical to cartilage); the structural hierarchy is: tropocollagen → fibril → fiber → fascicle → tendon",B:"Tendon primary ECM protein: type I collagen (~60-85% dry weight); structural hierarchy: tropocollagen (triple helix, ~300 nm) → collagen fibril (50-500 nm diameter, staggered D-period = 67 nm, cross-linked by lysyl oxidase) → collagen fiber (1-20 microns, the primary structural unit, imparts crimp pattern visible by LM) → collagen fibril bundle/subfascicle → fascicle (100-500 microns, surrounded by endotenon) → tendon (surrounded by epitenon/paratenon); tenocytes (fibrocytes, flat, with long cytoplasmic processes) lie in rows between fibers; crimped waveform is a stress-relief mechanism ('toe region' of the stress-strain curve)",C:"Tendon primary ECM protein: elastin (to allow high extensibility); structure: elastic fiber → subfibril → fascicle; tendons have virtually no collagen",D:"Tendon primary ECM protein: fibronectin; tenocytes are identical to chondrocytes in lacunae"},correct:"B",explanation:"Tendon structure: Tendons transmit tensile forces from contracting muscle to bone. Composition: ~60-85% type I collagen (dry weight), ~2-5% proteoglycans (biglycan and decorin — small leucine-rich proteoglycans that regulate collagen fibril diameter and alignment; decorin binds along the gap region of collagen fibrils → inhibits fibril-fibril fusion → maintains precise fibril diameter), elastin (<1%), fibronectin, tenascin-C (marks sites of mechanical stress), water (~65-70% wet weight). Structural hierarchy: Tropocollagen (1.5 nm × 300 nm) → cross-linked by lysyl oxidase (LOX) → collagen fibril (50-500 nm diameter, with characteristic 67 nm D-period banding from staggered triple helix arrangement) → collagen fiber (primary structural unit, 1-20 microns) → collagen fiber bundles (subfascicles, 50-300 microns) → fascicles (100-500 microns, surrounded by loose connective tissue endotenon through which blood vessels, lymphatics, and nerves run) → tendon (surrounded by peritenon/epitenon — thin connective tissue sheath; surrounded by paratenon in tendons not enclosed in synovial sheaths, or by tendon sheath/synovial sheath in fingers and ankle tendons). Crimp pattern: wavelike (sinusoidal) pattern of collagen fibers visible by LM or polarized light; 'toe region' of the stress-strain curve — crimp is straightened (elastic recoil) before collagen fibers begin to bear full load. Tenocytes: specialized fibroblasts aligned in rows between collagen fibers; long cytoplasmic processes wrap around fiber bundles; Scx (scleraxis) TF is the master regulator of tenocyte identity.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Tendon"},
    {question:"Wound healing in connective tissue proceeds through overlapping phases. What is the specific role of macrophages in coordinating each phase?",options:{A:"Macrophages are only involved in the inflammatory phase; they play no role in proliferation or remodeling",B:"M1 (pro-inflammatory, classically activated) macrophages dominate early healing (days 1-5): phagocytose bacteria and debris, produce IL-1beta, TNF-alpha, IL-6 (amplify inflammation), and reactive oxygen and nitrogen species (antimicrobial). M2 (anti-inflammatory/pro-regenerative, alternatively activated) macrophages dominate proliferative phase (days 5-14+): produce TGF-beta1 and PDGF (activate fibroblasts → myofibroblasts, collagen synthesis), VEGF (angiogenesis), IL-10 (anti-inflammatory). Resolution/remodeling: tissue-resident macrophages phagocytose myofibroblasts undergoing apoptosis; coordinate MMP production for matrix remodeling. Macrophage depletion experiments (liposome clodronate) markedly impair all phases",C:"Macrophages are exclusively phagocytic; they play no cytokine or growth factor secretory role in wound healing",D:"Macrophages in wounds are exclusively derived from circulating monocytes; tissue-resident macrophages do not participate in wound healing"},correct:"B",explanation:"Macrophage polarization in wound healing: Wound healing phases: (1) Hemostasis (minutes): platelets → clot + TGF-beta, PDGF release → early chemotaxis. (2) Inflammation (days 1-5): Neutrophils first (polymorphonuclear cells, peak day 1-2): phagocytose debris and bacteria; release reactive oxygen species (MPO, elastase, cathepsin G → tissue damage if excessive); apoptose after 24-48h; phagocytosed by macrophages (efferocytosis). Monocyte-derived macrophages arrive day 2-3 and become classically activated (M1): IFN-gamma (from T cells) + LPS → M1 polarization → pro-inflammatory cytokines (TNF-alpha, IL-1beta, IL-6, IL-12, IL-23), ROS/RNS → amplify inflammation + antimicrobial defense. (3) Proliferative (days 5-14): Macrophage polarization → M2 (anti-inflammatory/pro-repair): driven by IL-4, IL-13 (from Th2 cells, mast cells), IL-10, glucocorticoids, efferocytosis (phagocytosis of apoptotic neutrophils is a key M2 polarization signal). M2 secretion: TGF-beta1 → myofibroblast activation (collagen I/III synthesis); PDGF → fibroblast chemotaxis and proliferation; VEGF-A → angiogenesis (endothelial sprouting); IGF-1 → epithelial proliferation. (4) Remodeling (weeks-months): macrophages secrete MMPs (MMP-1, -8, -13) and TIMPs → balance collagen remodeling. Clinical implication: diabetes mellitus impairs macrophage M1→M2 transition (due to AGE-RAGE signaling) → impaired wound healing, chronic wounds. Macrophage dysfunction in aging contributes to delayed healing.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Wound healing"},
    {question:"The synovial membrane (synovium) lines the inner surface of joint capsules. What are the two main cell types of the synovium and what do they produce?",options:{A:"The synovium contains only fibroblasts; there are no macrophage-like cells in normal synovium",B:"Synoviocytes/synovial cells are of two types: Type A synoviocytes (macrophage-like, CD68+, FcgammaRIII+): phagocytic, derived from monocytes/macrophages, clear cellular debris from the joint space. Type B synoviocytes (fibroblast-like, CD44+, CD90+/Thy1+, cadherin-11+): synthesize synovial fluid components — particularly hyaluronan (HA, high molecular weight, produced by HAS1/2 synthase, lubricating the joint by increasing viscosity) and lubricin (proteoglycan 4/PRG4, glycoprotein that reduces friction between cartilage surfaces = boundary lubrication); the synovium has no basement membrane, enabling rapid exchange of molecules between the synovial fluid and the subsynovial vasculature",C:"The synovium has three cell types: Type A (osteoblastic), Type B (chondrogenic), and Type C (adipogenic); all produce lubricin",D:"Synoviocytes are identical to endothelial cells; the synovial membrane contains fenestrated capillaries rather than specialized secretory cells"},correct:"B",explanation:"Synovial membrane histology: The synovium is a thin membrane (1-3 cell layers thick in normal joints) lining the internal surface of the joint capsule, tendon sheaths, and bursae — but NOT the articular cartilage surface. Unique feature: NO basement membrane beneath the synovial cell layer → allows rapid bidirectional exchange of molecules between the joint cavity and the subsynovial vascularized connective tissue. Type A synoviocytes (macrophage-type, ~30%): bone marrow-derived (monocyte lineage), HLA-DR+, CD68+ (KiM2R, HAM56), CD14+/-, FcgammaRIII (CD16)+; phagocytose debris, cellular fragments, foreign material in the joint space; antigen presenting cells in the synovium. Type B synoviocytes (fibroblast-type, ~70%): CD44+ (hyaluronan receptor), CD90/Thy1+, cadherin-11 (CDH11, specific adhesion molecule), vimentin+. Produce: (1) Hyaluronan (HA): high MW (5-20 MDa); gives synovial fluid its characteristic viscoelastic properties (viscosity helps resist rapid shear forces; elasticity helps resist slow compressive forces). (2) Lubricin (proteoglycan 4, PRG4): secreted meglycoprotein that forms a brush-like layer on the cartilage surface and at the synovium/cartilage interface → reduces friction (boundary lubrication) and wear during joint movement. Lubricin deficiency → camptodactyly-arthropathy-coxa vara-pericarditis (CACP) syndrome. Rheumatoid arthritis: synovial hyperplasia — type A and B synoviocytes both hyperproliferate → 'pannus' tissue (invasive synovium) → cartilage destruction by MMPs and RANKL-driven osteoclastic erosion.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Synovial membrane"},
    {question:"Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (EDS) is a group of inherited connective tissue disorders. What are the three most clinically significant types and their molecular defects?",options:{A:"Classical EDS: type I/II collagen mutations (COL1A1/2) causing osteogenesis imperfecta features; hypermobile EDS: fibrillin-1 mutations (identical to Marfan); vascular EDS: elastin mutations",B:"Classical EDS (types I and II): mutations in COL5A1 or COL5A2 (type V collagen, regulates type I collagen fibril diameter) → skin hyperextensibility, abnormal scarring (thin atrophic 'cigarette paper' scars), joint hypermobility. Hypermobile EDS (hEDS, type III): most common, no molecular defect identified (diagnosis by clinical criteria); generalized joint hypermobility, chronic pain. Vascular EDS (type IV): COL3A1 mutations → type III collagen deficiency → vascular and organ fragility; life-threatening: spontaneous arterial dissection/rupture (aorta, celiac, renal arteries), intestinal perforation, uterine rupture; skin is thin but NOT hyperextensible in contrast to classical EDS",C:"All EDS types are caused by lysyl hydroxylase (PLOD1) deficiency; they are biochemically identical but clinically distinct",D:"EDS is caused by elastin (ELN) haploinsufficiency; fibrillin mutations cause Marfan syndrome but not EDS"},correct:"B",explanation:"Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (EDS): A heterogeneous group of heritable connective tissue disorders characterized by varying combinations of joint hypermobility, skin extensibility, and fragility. 13 subtypes (2017 criteria). Three major types: (1) Classical EDS (cEDS): AD; COL5A1/2 mutations (type V collagen normally inhibits lateral fusion of type I collagen fibrils → COL5 deficiency → thicker, irregular fibrils). Skin: hyperextensible (>3 cm at forearm), thin, soft, velvet-like; atrophic ('cigarette paper') scarring over pressure points (elbows, knees); molluscoid pseudotumors (soft tissue masses over scars); joints: hypermobile with easy dislocations; easy bruising. EM: irregular, 'cauliflower' collagen fibrils. (2) Hypermobile EDS (hEDS): Most common form (~1:500); genes: unknown (not yet identified, despite extensive research); clinical diagnosis by Beighton score (joint hypermobility ≥4/9) + systemic features; generalized joint hypermobility, joint dislocations, chronic pain, autonomic dysfunction, anxiety/depression; frequently comorbid with POTS, MCAS. (3) Vascular EDS (vEDS): AD; COL3A1 mutations → defective type III procollagen → reduces structural integrity of blood vessels, hollow organs, uterus. Type III collagen is the major collagen in vessel walls and hollow organs. Clinical: medium-to-large artery spontaneous dissection/rupture (SMA, celiac, renal, splenic, aorta), intestinal perforation (especially sigmoid), uterine rupture during pregnancy. Skin: thin, translucent (veins visible), minimal extensibility; acrogeria (aged extremity appearance). Arteries have no warning — rupture without dissection symptoms. Median survival 48 years. Additional: Kyphoscoliotic EDS (kEDS): PLOD1 (lysyl hydroxylase 1) mutations → deficient lysyl hydroxylation → abnormal cross-links → severe kyphoscoliosis, joint laxity, ocular fragility.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Heritable CT disorders"},
    {question:"Elastic fibers provide recoil to tissues. What is the composition of elastic fibers and what disease results from elastin or fibrillin deficiency?",options:{A:"Elastic fibers: elastin core (crosslinked via desmosine and isodesmosine from lysine residues by lysyl oxidase — these unique cross-links are the basis for elastin's rubber-like properties; ELN gene) surrounded by fibrillin microfibrils (fibrillin-1/FBN1, fibrillin-2/FBN2); the microfibrillar scaffold template allows elastin secretion and cross-linking. FBN1 mutations → Marfan syndrome (aortic root aneurysm, lens subluxation (ectopia lentis), skeletal — tall, arachnodactyly, scoliosis); FBN2 mutations → congenital contractural arachnodactyly (Beals syndrome). ELN haploinsufficiency → supravalvular aortic stenosis/Williams syndrome (7q11.23 microdeletion of ELN + TF genes)",B:"Elastic fibers: all fibrillin, no elastin; desmosine cross-links are found only in collagen",C:"Elastic fibers: type IV collagen core surrounded by laminin; fibrillin mutations cause Alport syndrome",D:"Elastic fibers: elastin core surrounded by type III collagen; fibrillin-1 mutations cause Marfan syndrome via overproduction of TGF-beta (not structural defect)"},correct:"A",explanation:"Elastic fiber structure: Two-component structure: (1) Elastin core: encoded by ELN gene (chromosome 7q11.23); secreted as tropoelastin (70 kDa, soluble) → cross-linked by lysyl oxidase (LOX, copper-dependent enzyme) at lysine residues → unique cross-links: desmosine and isodesmosine (from 4 lysine residues, 3 from one tropelastin chain and 1 from another — isodesmosine) and lysinonorleucine. These covalent cross-links between chains create a hydrophobic amorphous polymeric network with rubber-like properties (entropic elasticity — extending elastin increases conformational entropy disorder → elastic restoring force). (2) Fibrillin microfibrils: fibrillin-1 (FBN1, chromosome 15q21) and fibrillin-2 (FBN2, chromosome 5q23) form 10-12 nm microfibrils via head-to-tail polymerization stabilized by TB (TGF-beta-binding protein) domains. Microfibrils provide the scaffold for tropoelastin deposition (especially during development) and serve as a reservoir for TGF-beta (bound via fibrillin-LTBP-TGF-beta complex). Marfan syndrome (FBN1 mutations): AD. Pathogenesis: not only structural loss of microfibril integrity but also enhanced TGF-beta signaling (fibrillin-1 sequesters TGF-beta; FBN1 mutation → TGF-beta released → SMAD2/3 → MMP upregulation → aortic aneurysm, mitral valve prolapse). Features: cardiovascular (aortic root aneurysm, dissection type A → leading cause of death; mitral valve prolapse/regurgitation); ocular (ectopia lentis, superotemporal displacement; myopia); skeletal (dolichostenomelia, arachnodactyly, pectus deformity, scoliosis, high arched palate; arm span > height; positive wrist/thumb signs). Ghent criteria for diagnosis. Treatment: beta-blockers (reduce aortic wall shear stress), losartan (AT1R blocker, reduces TGF-beta signaling), prophylactic aortic root replacement when aortic root >5.0 cm.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Elastic fibers"},
    {question:"Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) is an autoimmune disease that attacks the connective tissue of multiple organs. What are the classic autoantibodies and the lupus nephritis histological findings?",options:{A:"SLE autoantibodies: anti-Sm (Smith) and anti-dsDNA (double-stranded DNA) — most specific for SLE (anti-Sm: 25-30% sensitivity, ~99% specificity; anti-dsDNA: 50-70% sensitivity, ~95% specificity, correlates with disease activity/nephritis). Also anti-histone (drug-induced lupus, also SLE), anti-Ro (SSA)/anti-La (SSB) (neonatal lupus, congenital heart block), anti-phospholipid (SLE + APS: anti-cardiolipin, anti-beta2GP1, lupus anticoagulant → thrombosis, recurrent pregnancy loss). Lupus nephritis: immune complex deposition → complement activation → inflammation; WHO/ISN-RPS classification: Class III (focal proliferative, <50% glomeruli) and Class IV (diffuse proliferative, >50% glomeruli): 'wire loop' lesion (subendothelial deposits → basement membrane thickening, visible on H&E); 'full house' immunofluorescence (IgG+IgA+IgM+C3+C1q positive, all isotypes and complement)",B:"SLE autoantibodies: only anti-SSA and anti-SSB (identical to Sjogren's syndrome); lupus nephritis characterized by mesangial IgA deposits only",C:"SLE autoantibodies: anti-GBM (same as Goodpasture syndrome); lupus nephritis shows linear IgG pattern on IF",D:"SLE has no autoantibodies; diagnosis is clinical only; lupus nephritis shows no immune deposits (pauci-immune)"},correct:"A",explanation:"SLE autoimmunity: SLE is characterized by loss of tolerance to nuclear antigens (nucleosomes — DNA-histone complexes released from apoptotic cells → inadequately cleared → activate autoreactive B and T cells). Autoantibody spectrum: Anti-dsDNA: 50-70% sensitivity, ~95-99% specific; titers correlate with disease activity (complement consumption, nephritis flares); tested by CLIFT (Crithidia luciliae hemoflagellate immunofluorescence). Anti-Sm (Smith, snRNP U1-U6): 25-30% sensitive, ~99% specific; marker for SLE. Anti-histone: drug-induced lupus (procainamide, hydralazine, isoniazid → 100% sensitive but low specificity for drug-induced). Anti-Ro (SSA) and anti-La (SSB): SLE + Sjogren's; neonatal lupus (anti-Ro crosses placenta → congenital complete heart block — anti-Ro targets Ro52 on AV node cells). Anti-phospholipid (aPL): SLE + antiphospholipid antibody syndrome (APS): anti-cardiolipin (aCL), anti-beta2-glycoprotein 1 (anti-beta2GP1), lupus anticoagulant (LA, prolonged aPTT) → venous thromboembolism (DVT, PE), arterial thrombosis, recurrent early pregnancy loss (thrombosis of decidual vessels), thrombocytopenia. Lupus nephritis (ISN/RPS 2003, revised 2018): Class I: minimal mesangial. Class II: mesangial proliferative. Class III: Focal (<50% glomeruli): segmental/global endocapillary proliferation with subendothelial deposits. Class IV: Diffuse (≥50% glomeruli): most severe, most common, global endocapillary proliferation + 'wire loop' lesion on H&E (subendothelial immune complex deposits thickening the GBM, giving a rigid 'wire loop' appearance). Class V: Membranous (subepithelial deposits, like idiopathic membranous nephropathy + mesangial deposits). Class VI: Advanced sclerosing. IF pattern: 'full house' (IgG+IgA+IgM+C3+C1q) — pathognomonic for lupus nephritis.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"CT disorders"},
    {question:"The lymph node has a specific architectural organization. What is the function of the germinal center within a secondary lymphoid follicle?",options:{A:"Germinal centers contain plasma cells that secrete IgM; they form in primary immune responses only",B:"Germinal centers (GCs) form within primary follicles during T-cell-dependent B cell responses; GCs are sites of: clonal B cell (GC B cell/centroblast) proliferation, somatic hypermutation (SHM) of immunoglobulin variable regions (activation-induced cytidine deaminase, AID, mutates the Ig V gene rapidly), antigen selection (centrocytes compete for antigen displayed on follicular dendritic cells, FDCs; those with higher-affinity BCR survive via CD40L-CD40 interaction with T follicular helper cells, Tfh; low-affinity cells undergo apoptosis and are phagocytosed by tingible body macrophages), and class-switch recombination (CSR, AID-mediated, replacing IgM with IgG, IgA, IgE) → generates high-affinity, class-switched memory B cells and plasma cells",C:"Germinal centers are the site of T cell education (positive and negative selection identical to the thymus)",D:"Germinal centers produce cytotoxic T cells; B cells are not present in GCs"},correct:"B",explanation:"Germinal center (GC) reactions: GCs are specialized microenvironments that form within primary B cell follicles after antigen stimulation. Histology of a secondary follicle (with GC): Mantle zone (dark peripheral zone of naive IgM+IgD+ B cells surrounding the GC); Light zone (centrocytes — smaller, irregular, non-dividing GC B cells; FDCs — follicular dendritic cells with antigen-Ig complex deposits on their surface dendrites; Tfh cells — CD4+, CXCR5+, PD-1+, ICOS+, Bcl-6+, IL-21-secreting TF helpers); Dark zone (centroblasts — large, rapidly dividing GC B cells undergoing SHM). GC reaction sequence: Naive B cells activated by T-cell-dependent antigen → enter primary follicle → differentiate into centroblasts in the dark zone → divide rapidly (~12h doubling time) → AID mutates IgV gene at ~10-6/bp/division (106x faster than normal somatic mutation) → become centrocytes → migrate to light zone → test affinity of mutated BCR for antigen on FDCs → high affinity: rescued from apoptosis by Tfh-derived CD40L and IL-21 + BCL6 expression → more rounds of mutation (Darwinian selection) or exit GC as: (a) Long-lived plasma cells (to bone marrow, secrete high-affinity class-switched antibodies = humoral memory); (b) Memory B cells (class-switched or IgM+IgD+, long-lived, respond rapidly on re-exposure). Low affinity: apoptosis → phagocytosed by tingible body macrophages (large, dark nucleus macrophages in the GC, phagocytosing apoptotic centrocytes — the 'starry sky' pattern in high-grade lymphomas). BCL6 is the master regulator of GC B cells — represses p53, ATR, BLIMP-1. BCL6 translocation t(3;variable) in diffuse large B cell lymphoma.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Lymphoid tissue"},
    {question:"Scurvy is caused by vitamin C (ascorbic acid) deficiency. Which histological and molecular consequences are directly attributable to impaired collagen synthesis?",options:{A:"Scurvy: impaired lysosomal degradation of collagen → excess collagen accumulation in dermis; vitamin C is a lysosomal cofactor",B:"Vitamin C deficiency → impaired prolyl-4-hydroxylase (and lysyl hydroxylase) activity — these enzymes require ascorbate as a cofactor to reduce the enzyme-bound iron (Fe2+ required; hydroxylation of proline to 4-hydroxyproline requires Fe2+, alpha-ketoglutarate, O2, and ascorbate to regenerate Fe2+ from Fe3+ after each hydroxylation cycle) → underhydroxylated collagen → unstable triple helix (hydroxyproline contributes ~50% of collagen triple helix stability via hydrogen bonds through water molecules) → defective secretion → intracellular procollagen accumulation → deficient mature cross-linked collagen → perifollicular hemorrhage, bleeding gums, poor wound healing, perifollicular hyperkeratosis, corkscrew hairs, Frankel lines on X-ray",C:"Vitamin C deficiency causes impaired copper absorption → reduced lysyl oxidase activity → no collagen cross-linking; prolyl hydroxylase is not affected",D:"Scurvy specifically impairs type IV collagen synthesis only (not type I); basement membranes are the primary target"},correct:"B",explanation:"Scurvy pathogenesis: Vitamin C (ascorbic acid, L-ascorbic acid) is an essential micronutrient in humans (no endogenous synthesis due to loss of the GULO gene encoding gulonolactone oxidase). The most critical biochemical role in connective tissue: Prolyl-4-hydroxylase (P4H) mechanism: P4H is an alpha2-beta2 tetramer; the beta subunit is PDI (protein disulfide isomerase). The alpha subunit (catalytic) is a 2-oxoglutarate (alpha-ketoglutarate) dioxygenase. Reaction: L-Proline + alpha-KG + O2 + Fe2+ → 4-Hydroxyproline (in procollagen Gly-X-Pro sequences, specifically Pro in the Y position) + succinate + CO2 + Fe3+. After each hydroxylation cycle, the active-site Fe2+ is oxidized to Fe3+ (inactive) → ascorbate (vitamin C) regenerates Fe2+ from Fe3+ (reducing agent) → enzyme is recycled. Without ascorbate: Fe2+ not regenerated → P4H becomes inactive after a few catalytic cycles → underhydroxylated collagen. Consequences of underhydroxylated collagen: 4-Hydroxyproline stabilizes the collagen triple helix by forming hydrogen bonds through ordered water molecules (~50% of triple helix thermal stability comes from 4-Hyp). Underhydroxylated collagen: (1) Cannot form a stable triple helix at body temperature (melts at ~37°C instead of >37°C) → collagen is degraded intracellularly before secretion. (2) Cannot be secreted efficiently → accumulates in ER. (3) Lacks substrate for lysyl oxidase cross-linking. Result: severe deficiency of mature, functional collagen → clinical scurvy: perifollicular hemorrhage (periorbital, gum, and perifollicular hemorrhage — small vessel walls lack supporting type IV collagen → microhemorrhage), gingival swelling and bleeding, impaired wound healing, painful joints (hemarthrosis), corkscrew hairs (follicle structure affected), 'woody' edema.",topic:"Connective Tissue",subtopic:"Collagen disorders"}
  ];

  var bloodHematopoiesisQuestions = [
    {question:"A peripheral blood smear shows cells with bilobed nuclei connected by a thin strand, abundant pink (eosinophilic) cytoplasm with specific granules. These are neutrophils. What are the different granule types in neutrophils and what do they contain?",options:{A:"Neutrophils have only one granule type (azurophilic) containing all enzymes uniformly distributed",B:"Neutrophils have three major granule types: (1) Azurophilic (primary) granules — appear first during differentiation, contain myeloperoxidase (MPO, generates HOCl from H2O2 + Cl-), lysozyme, defensins (alpha-defensins), elastase (ELANE), cathepsin G, proteinase 3, azurocidin; (2) Specific (secondary) granules — contain lactoferrin, collagenase (MMP-8), B12-binding protein, NGAL, complement receptor 3 (CR3/CD11b/CD18); (3) Tertiary/gelatinase granules — contain gelatinase (MMP-9), MMP-25; also secretory vesicles that fuse first with the plasma membrane upon activation"},correct:"B",explanation:"Neutrophil granule biology: Neutrophils are the most abundant circulating leukocytes (~55-70% of WBCs). They are the primary cellular defense against bacteria and fungi. Granule types by appearance and function: (1) Azurophilic (primary) granules: large, purple (azurophilic) granules visible on Romanowsky-stained smear; appear first during promyelocyte stage. Key enzymes: MPO (myeloperoxidase — produces hypochlorous acid/HOCl from H2O2 and Cl-, powerful oxidant for bacterial killing — MPO deficiency: susceptibility to Candida infections, common polymorphism); lysozyme (peptidoglycan hydrolysis); alpha-defensins (antimicrobial peptides); elastase/ELANE (degrades ECM proteins; ELANE mutations → cyclic/severe congenital neutropenia); cathepsin G. (2) Specific (secondary) granules: smaller, do not stain strongly; appear at myelocyte stage; most abundant. Lactoferrin (sequesters iron from bacteria — bacteriostatic); collagenase (MMP-8, degrades ECM at inflammatory sites); B12-binding protein (transcobalamin I); NGAL (lipocalin-2, iron sequestration, antimicrobial); integrins (CR3/CD11b, fMLP receptors) stored here and rapidly expressed on the cell surface upon activation — accounting for rapid neutrophil integrin upregulation after stimulation. (3) Tertiary (gelatinase) granules: contain gelatinase B (MMP-9, degrades collagen IV and gelatin; useful for basement membrane penetration during extravasation). Secretory vesicles: smallest; exocytose first; rapidly recycle formyl-peptide receptors (FPR1/2) and CD35 (complement receptor 1) to the surface. Clinical: Chronic granulomatous disease (CGD): NADPH oxidase defect → no superoxide/H2O2 → no HOCl → catalase-positive organisms (Staph aureus, Aspergillus, Klebsiella, Serratia) cause recurrent, life-threatening infections; NBT (nitroblue tetrazolium) test: fails to turn blue in CGD neutrophils. Chediak-Higashi: LYST gene mutation → giant lysosome/granule formation → impaired degranulation and NK cell cytotoxicity.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Neutrophils"},
    {question:"Erythropoiesis is the process of red blood cell formation. Which transcription factors and cytokines are essential for erythroid commitment and differentiation?",options:{A:"Erythroid differentiation requires only EPO; transcription factors play no role in lineage commitment",B:"EPO (erythropoietin, produced by peritubular fibroblast-like cells in the renal cortex in response to hypoxia — HIF-2alpha → EPO gene transcription) binds EPOR (dimeric, activates JAK2-STAT5) on erythroid progenitors (BFU-E → CFU-E → proerythroblast → erythroblast stages) → promotes survival, proliferation, and differentiation. Key TFs: GATA-1 (master erythroid/megakaryocyte TF) + SCL/TAL1 (basic HLH) + KLF1/EKLF (drives adult beta-globin expression) + FOG-1 (GATA-1 co-factor). EPO-independent early stages require SCF (KIT ligand) and IL-3 for BFU-E expansion"},correct:"B",explanation:"Erythropoiesis regulatory network: Erythroid progenitor hierarchy: HSC → LMPP → MEP (megakaryocyte-erythroid progenitor) → BFU-E (burst-forming unit erythroid, EPO-independent, requires SCF + IL-3) → CFU-E (colony-forming unit erythroid, EPO-dependent, high EPOR expression) → Proerythroblast → Basophilic erythroblast → Polychromatic erythroblast → Orthochromatic erythroblast → Reticulocyte (enucleated; still contains residual RNA, mitochondria; matures in blood over ~24h losing these) → Mature erythrocyte. Key transcription factors: GATA-1: C4-type zinc finger; binds GATA motif (WGATAR); essential for erythroid, megakaryocyte, mast cell differentiation; activates globin genes, EPOR, alas2 (erythroid ALAS), heme biosynthesis enzymes; GATA-1 mutations → Diamond-Blackfan anemia-like phenotype, thrombocytopenia. KLF1 (EKLF): activates beta-globin LCR-globin gene interaction (required for fetal-to-adult Hb switch). BCL11A: repressor of gamma-globin (fetal) → target of HbF-inducing therapy (BCL11A inhibition → HbF derepression → sickle cell disease treatment strategy). EPO-EPOR-JAK2: JAK2 phosphorylates STAT5 → STAT5 dimer → nucleus → BCL-XL (anti-apoptotic), ID1 (proliferative) → survival. Polycythemia vera: JAK2 V617F gain-of-function → EPO-independent erythropoiesis. Anemias: EPO deficiency (CKD → normocytic anemia; treatment: recombinant EPO/darbepoetin); EPO insensitivity (inflammation → hepcidin ↑ → iron-restricted; also EPOR deficiency).",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Erythropoiesis"},
    {question:"The peripheral blood smear can reveal many pathological processes. What abnormal red blood cell morphologies are associated with specific disease states?",options:{A:"Schistocytes: spherical RBCs seen in hereditary spherocytosis; target cells: fragmented cells in microangiopathic hemolytic anemia",B:"Schistocytes (helmet cells, fragmented RBCs): mechanical destruction in microangiopathic hemolytic anemia (TTP — ADAMTS13 deficiency; HUS — Shiga toxin; DIC; HELLP). Spherocytes: loss of membrane surface area relative to volume — hereditary spherocytosis (spectrin/ankyrin defects) or autoimmune hemolytic anemia (AIHA, warm IgG). Target cells (codocytes): increased membrane-to-volume ratio — thalassemia, iron deficiency, liver disease, hemoglobin C disease, post-splenectomy. Sickle cells (drepanocytes): HbS polymerization under deoxygenation → HbS disease. Teardrop cells (dacrocytes): bone marrow fibrosis (myelofibrosis), extramedullary hematopoiesis. Elliptocytes: hereditary elliptocytosis (spectrin mutations). Bite cells: G6PD deficiency (denatured Hb/Heinz bodies removed by spleen). Acanthocytes (spur cells): abetalipoproteinemia, liver disease"},correct:"B",explanation:"Peripheral smear RBC morphology: The peripheral blood smear (PBS) is a crucial diagnostic tool — RBC morphology reflects RBC membrane composition, intracellular environment, and mechanical forces. Key morphologies: Schistocytes: irregular, angular, fragmented RBCs; result from mechanical shearing of RBCs by fibrin strands in small vessels (microangiopathy) or artificial heart valves. Seen in: TTP (thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura — ADAMTS13 deficiency → ultra-large VWF multimers → platelet aggregation in microvessels; treated with plasma exchange), HUS (Shiga toxin from E. coli O157:H7 → endothelial injury → TMA; treated supportively), DIC, HELLP syndrome in pregnancy, mechanical valve hemolysis. Spherocytes: small, dense, no central pallor (~3x normal MCHC); lack spectrin-ankyrin anchor for lipid bilayer → membrane blebs → osmotic fragility. HS from ANK1 (ankyrin-1), SPTA1 (alpha-spectrin), SPTB (beta-spectrin), SLC4A1 (Band 3/AE1) mutations → AD/AR. AIHA: IgG (warm) or IgM (cold) antibodies coat RBCs → complement-mediated or Fc-receptor-mediated splenic destruction → spherocytosis. Target cells: thin central staining with surrounding ring of Hb and another outer ring — the central 'target' consists of Hb concentrated in the center. Thalassemia: globin chain imbalance → hypochromic, microcytic, target cells. Sickle cells (drepanocytes): characteristic crescent/sickle shape; HbS (Glu6Val beta-globin); polymerize when deoxygenated → vaso-occlusion, pain crises, infarcts. Teardrop cells (dacrocytes): released from bone marrow with fibrosis → inclusion bodies deform the cell during egress. Burr cells (echinocytes): regular projections; uremia, pyruvate kinase deficiency. Acanthocytes (spur cells): irregular projections; abetalipoproteinemia (no ApoB → no chylomicrons, no VLDL, neurological damage), severe liver disease (altered membrane lipid composition).",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"RBC morphology"},
    {question:"Hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) reside in the bone marrow. What surface markers identify human long-term HSCs, and what niche signals maintain HSC quiescence?",options:{A:"HSCs are identified by CD3+CD4+ markers (identical to T helper cells); quiescence is maintained by IL-2 from bone marrow fibroblasts",B:"Human long-term HSCs (LT-HSCs): Lin- (lineage negative — no CD3, CD19, CD14, CD56, GlyA markers), CD34+, CD38-, CD90+/Thy1+ (low), CD45RA-, CD49f+, CD133+ (PROM1). Murine: Lin-Sca-1+c-Kit+ (LSK), CD150+ (SLAM), CD48-, Flt3-. Niche signals maintaining quiescence: (1) SCF (stem cell factor, KIT ligand) from endothelial cells and osteoblasts → KIT signaling; (2) CXCL12 (SDF-1) from perivascular reticular (CXCL12-abundant reticular, CAR) cells → CXCR4 on HSCs → retention in niche; (3) TPO (thrombopoietin) → Mpl receptor → quiescence; (4) Angiopoietin-1 (Ang-1) from osteoblasts → Tie-2 receptor → quiescence; (5) TGF-beta1 from megakaryocytes → Smad2/3 → quiescence maintenance; HSCs reside in hypoxic niches (HIF-1alpha drives glycolytic metabolism preferred by quiescent HSCs)"},correct:"B",explanation:"HSC identification and niche: Human LT-HSCs constitute ~0.01% of bone marrow mononuclear cells. Phenotype: Lin- (excluding all mature lineage markers) + CD34+ + CD38- + CD90(Thy1)+ (low/dim) + CD45RA- + CD49f (integrin alpha6, laminin receptor). Long-term repopulation potential: defined functionally (xenograft models: NSG mice). Bone marrow niches: (1) Endosteal (osteoblastic) niche: osteoblasts produce SCF, Ang-1, OPN (osteopontin), CXCL12, Jagged-1/2 (Notch ligand); supports quiescence and self-renewal. (2) Perivascular (vascular) niche: sinusoidal endothelial cells produce SCF, CXCL12; CXCL12-abundant reticular (CAR) cells/perivascular stromal cells. Most LT-HSCs are actually in the perivascular niche but can interact with endosteum. HSC quiescence: LT-HSCs are mostly quiescent (G0 phase, ~60-70%); quiescence protects against replicative stress and DNA damage accumulation. CXCL12-CXCR4: retention signal; disrupted by G-CSF → HSC mobilization to blood (basis of peripheral blood stem cell mobilization for transplantation). AMD3100 (plerixafor, CXCR4 antagonist) rapidly mobilizes HSCs. Cyclophosphamide + G-CSF: standard mobilization regimen. HSC aging: Increased in number but decreased in function; skewed toward myeloid differentiation; increased DNA damage; epigenetic changes (DNA methylation, H3K4me3/H3K27me3 alterations).",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"HSCs"},
    {question:"The complement system is activated in inflammatory states and hemolytic diseases. Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria (PNH) results from impaired complement regulation. What is the molecular defect?",options:{A:"PNH: mutation in C3 gene → uncontrolled complement activation via all three pathways",B:"PNH: somatic mutation in PIG-A gene (phosphatidylinositol glycan class A, X-linked) in a hematopoietic stem cell → deficient GPI anchor biosynthesis → absence of GPI-anchored complement regulatory proteins on blood cell surfaces: CD55 (DAF, decay accelerating factor — inactivates C3/C5 convertases) and CD59 (protectin — blocks MAC/C5b-9 assembly by binding C8/C9) → unrestrained terminal complement → lysis of red cells, platelets, and WBCs → intravascular hemolysis, hemoglobinuria, thrombosis; treated with eculizumab (anti-C5 mAb) or ravulizumab (long-acting anti-C5)"},correct:"B",explanation:"PNH pathophysiology: PIG-A gene is located on chromosome Xp22.1; it encodes an enzyme (GPI transamidase complex component) required for the first step of GPI anchor biosynthesis. PIG-A mutation in one HSC (only one X-chromosome copy is needed due to X-inactivation in females, or hemizygous in males) → complete loss of GPI anchor production in all progeny cells. Consequences: All GPI-anchored proteins are absent from the PNH clone: CD55 (DAF, decay-accelerating factor): accelerates decay of C3bBb (alternative pathway C3 convertase) and C4b2a (classical/lectin C3 convertase) → without CD55, C3 convertases are more stable → more C3b deposition on cell surface → more C5 convertase → more MAC (C5b-6789 membrane attack complex) formation. CD59 (CD59/protectin/MIRL): the most important MAC inhibitor; inserts into the MAC pore between C8 and C9, preventing poly-C9 polymerization → without CD59, MAC assembles freely → intravascular hemolysis. Also absent: CD14 (LPS receptor, monocytes), CD58 (LFA-3), CD16 (FcgammaRIII, NK/neutrophil), urokinase receptor (uPAR/CD87). Clinical triad: (1) Intravascular hemolysis (dark urine in morning — 'paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria,' though hemoglobinuria occurs throughout the day and is not always nocturnal); (2) Thrombosis (venous, especially unusual sites: Budd-Chiari syndrome, portal vein, dural sinus — activated platelets from complement exposure release microparticles and form thrombi; NO scavenging by free Hb → endothelial dysfunction); (3) Cytopenias (marrow failure). Labs: flow cytometry of blood cells for CD55/CD59 (both absent on PNH cells) — gold standard diagnosis (FLAER assay — fluorescent aerolysin binds GPI anchors). Eculizumab (anti-C5 mAb): prevents C5 cleavage → no MAC → prevents hemolysis and reduces thrombosis; requires N. meningitidis vaccination. Ravulizumab: longer half-life, q8-weekly dosing. Iptacopan (oral factor B inhibitor): controls proximal complement, new approval for PNH.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Complement disorders"},
    {question:"Platelets are derived from megakaryocytes in the bone marrow. What is the process of thrombopoiesis, and how does thrombopoietin (TPO) regulate platelet production?",options:{A:"Platelets bud off from megakaryocyte surface membranes via cytoplasmic membrane pinching; TPO stimulates platelet destruction",B:"Megakaryocytes undergo endomitosis (repeated DNA replication without cell division) → polyploid nuclei (4N-128N); in the sinusoidal niche, megakaryocytes extend long cytoplasmic projections (proplatelets) into the bone marrow sinusoids → proplatelet fragments enter the bloodstream → further fragmentation in the pulmonary circulation and mechanically by blood flow → platelets (anucleate, 2-4 microns). TPO (thrombopoietin, liver-derived, binds Mpl/c-MPL receptor on megakaryocytes and HSCs → JAK2-STAT5 → promotes megakaryocyte differentiation and proplatelet formation); TPO levels inversely correlate with platelet mass (platelets/megakaryocytes sequester TPO via Mpl → low platelet mass → high TPO → more megakaryopoiesis)"},correct:"B",explanation:"Megakaryopoiesis and thrombopoiesis: Megakaryocyte differentiation: HSC → MEP (megakaryocyte-erythroid progenitor) → MkP (megakaryocyte progenitor) → promegakaryoblast → megakaryoblast → megakaryocyte. Key feature: endomitosis — DNA replication without cytokinesis → giant polyploid cell (modal ploidy 16N in humans, range 4N-128N). Larger megakaryocytes produce more platelets (~2000-5000 platelets per megakaryocyte). Megakaryocyte markers: CD41 (GPIIb/integrin alphaIIb), CD61 (GPIIIa/integrin beta3), CD42b (GPIbalpha), von Willebrand factor (VWF), vWF factor VIII, GPIX. Master TF: GATA-1, FOG-1, NF-E2 (activates thromboxane synthase and GPIbalpha). Proplatelet formation: Megakaryocytes migrate to the sinusoidal niche (near fenestrated capillaries); cytoplasmic extensions (proplatelets) extend through endothelial pores into the sinusoidal lumen → fragmented by blood flow turbulence in the pulmonary circulation (megakaryocyte nuclei also shed here = nude nuclei). TPO-Mpl axis: TPO is constitutively produced by hepatocytes (liver is the primary source; kidneys secondary); free TPO binds Mpl on platelets and megakaryocytes → internalized and degraded → serum TPO inversely correlates with platelet mass (and megakaryocyte mass). Thrombocytopenia → low Mpl-bearing cells → more free TPO → stimulates megakaryopoiesis → platelet production restored. This 'consumption-based' regulation contrasts with EPO (oxygen-sensitive). TPO receptor agonists (romiplostim, eltrombopag): treat ITP by stimulating TPO-Mpl pathway. Congenital amegakaryocytic thrombocytopenia (CAMT): Mpl mutations → absent megakaryocytes → severe thrombocytopenia → progresses to aplastic anemia.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Megakaryopoiesis"},
    {question:"Eosinophils play a central role in parasitic infections and allergic diseases. What are their granule contents and the cytokines that regulate their production?",options:{A:"Eosinophils contain the same granules as neutrophils (MPO and lysozyme); regulated by G-CSF",B:"Eosinophil granules: (1) Specific (secondary) granules: bicrystalline core + matrix structure; core contains major basic protein (MBP-1, MBP-2 — toxic to parasites and host tissue), matrix contains eosinophil cationic protein (ECP/RNase3 — neurotoxin, ribonuclease, antiparasitic), eosinophil-derived neurotoxin (EDN/RNase2), eosinophil peroxidase (EPO, generates reactive halogens). (2) Primary granules: Charcot-Leyden crystal protein (galectin-10/CLC). Regulation: IL-5 (Th2 and ILC2-derived) — the key cytokine driving eosinophil production (bone marrow), activation, and survival; IL-3 and GM-CSF also promote eosinophil development; eotaxins (CCL11, CCL24, CCL26) via CCR3 recruit eosinophils to tissues"},correct:"B",explanation:"Eosinophil biology: Eosinophils (2-4% of blood WBCs; <500/microL normal) are identified on PBS by their large, bright eosinophilic (pink-orange) specific granules (stain intensely with eosin due to positive charge of MBP at physiological pH), bilobed nucleus. They are primarily tissue-resident cells in the gut, lung, and skin. Granule proteins: MBP-1/2 (major basic protein): positively charged, creates pores in membranes → kills helminths (e.g., Strongyloides, Toxocara, Schistosoma, Fasciola), also causes mast cell degranulation and bronchial hyperreactivity. ECP (eosinophil cationic protein, RNase3): ribonuclease + pore-forming → antiparasitic; serum ECP is a clinical marker of eosinophil activation. EPO (eosinophil peroxidase): generates hypohalous acids (HOBr from Br-) + H2O2 → antiparasitic. Charcot-Leyden crystals: elongated, bipyramidal crystals of galectin-10 (CLC protein) found in eosinophil-rich tissues (asthma sputum, parasitic infection sites). Cytokine regulation: IL-5 (primary): produced by Th2 cells and ILC2s (innate lymphoid cells type 2); stimulates eosinophil differentiation (CFU-Eo), survival, activation, and release from bone marrow. Anti-IL-5 (mepolizumab, reslizumab) and anti-IL-5Ralpha (benralizumab) reduce peripheral eosinophil counts and asthma exacerbations. IL-4 and IL-13: Th2 cytokines; IL-4 drives Th2 differentiation; IL-13 drives goblet cell metaplasia, smooth muscle hypertrophy in asthma. Eotaxins (CCL11/CCL24/CCL26): chemokines binding CCR3 on eosinophils → tissue recruitment. Eosinophilic esophagitis (EoE): >15 eosinophils per high-power field in esophageal biopsies; driven by food/aeroallergens + IL-5/IL-13/eotaxin-3; treated with elimination diet, swallowed fluticasone, dupilumab (anti-IL-4Ralpha).",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Eosinophils"},
    {question:"The ABO blood group system is based on carbohydrate antigens on red blood cell surfaces. What are the ABO antigens, the naturally occurring antibodies, and the consequences of ABO-incompatible transfusion?",options:{A:"ABO antigens are proteins encoded by the ABO gene directly; type O individuals have both A and B proteins on their cells",B:"ABO antigens are carbohydrate structures on glycoproteins and glycolipids: Type A: N-acetylgalactosamine (GalNAc) added by alpha-1,3-GalNAc transferase (encoded by ABO gene, A allele) to H antigen (which is FUT1-gene-derived Fuc-Gal-GlcNAc structure). Type B: galactose (Gal) added by alpha-1,3-Gal transferase (B allele). Type O: loss-of-function ABO gene mutation → no transferase → H antigen only. Type AB: both A and B transferases. Naturally occurring isohemagglutinins (anti-A IgM and anti-B IgM) develop in the first 6 months of life by exposure to environmental/gut bacteria with ABO-like antigens (T-independent antigens). ABO-incompatible transfusion → acute hemolytic transfusion reaction (AHTR): IgM anti-A/anti-B → complement activation → intravascular hemolysis → hemoglobinuria, renal failure, DIC, fever, back pain → potentially fatal; most common cause is clerical error"},correct:"B",explanation:"ABO system: The ABO system is the most clinically important blood group system. Gene: ABO gene on chromosome 9q34.2 encodes glycosyltransferases. H antigen (precursor): formed by FUT1 (alpha-2-fucosyltransferase — adds Fuc to Gal on Type 2 chain glycans) on RBCs; FUT2 in secretions. Bombay phenotype (h/h or Oh): rare FUT1 null mutation → no H antigen → no A or B antigen → anti-H + anti-A + anti-B antibodies → compatible only with Bombay blood. ABO alleles: A1 > A2 > B > O in immunogenicity/antigen density. O allele: 1-base deletion causing frameshift → truncated, inactive protein → no transferase activity → H antigen only. Antibodies: Naturally occurring IgM anti-A and anti-B: develop in first 3-6 months of life from exposure to cross-reactive environmental antigens (E. coli O86 resembles B antigen; B. fragilis/S. pneumoniae A-like antigens). IgM is pentameric → efficiently activates complement → intravascular hemolysis (vs IgG anti-D in Rh-incompatibility → extravascular hemolysis in the spleen). AHTR (acute hemolytic transfusion reaction): Incompatible red cell transfusion → preformed IgM binds incompatible RBC antigens → classical complement pathway activation → C3b opsonization + C5b-9 MAC assembly → intravascular hemolysis → free Hb → hemoglobinuria, methemoglobin → renal tubular injury (acute tubular necrosis) + DIC (activation of coagulation cascade by free Hb and membrane phospholipids). Symptoms: fever, chills, back/flank pain, hypotension, tachycardia, hemoglobinuria. Management: stop transfusion immediately, supportive care, aggressive IV fluids to prevent renal failure.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Blood groups"},
    {question:"Basophils and mast cells share many characteristics but have different origins and locations. How do they differ?",options:{A:"Basophils and mast cells are identical; they are the same cell type at different maturation stages",B:"Basophils: circulate in blood (~0.5-1% of WBCs), short-lived (~2-3 days), bilobed/multilobed dark purple nucleus (often obscured by granules), bone marrow-derived mature cells; do NOT enter normal connective tissue (only migrate to tissues during inflammation). Mast cells: tissue-resident, long-lived (months-years), arise from bone marrow progenitors that enter blood then mature in tissues (final maturation under SCF/KIT signaling and IL-3); round nucleus; never found in blood; two types: MCT (mucosal mast cells, tryptase only) and MCTC (connective tissue mast cells, tryptase + chymase). Both express high-affinity FcepsilonRI and contain histamine, but mast cell granules also differ by tissue type"},correct:"B",explanation:"Basophil vs mast cell comparison: Both basophils and mast cells are granulocytic cells with high-affinity IgE Fc receptors (FcepsilonRI) and histamine-containing granules, but they differ in many key ways: Basophils: Origin: bone marrow (from basophil progenitor, BaP); complete final maturation in bone marrow → enter circulation as mature cells. Location: circulating in blood (~0.1-0.3% of WBCs; counts rise in basophilia of CML, polycythemia vera, hypothyroidism). Never normally resident in tissues in the healthy state. Lifespan: ~2-3 days in circulation. Morphology: dark purple/dark blue bilobed or multilobed nucleus (often covered by granules making it hard to see), large dark blue/purple basophilic granules (metachromatic with toluidine blue). Markers: CD123 (IL-3Ralpha)+, FcepsilonRI+, CD49b+, CRTH2 (CD294/prostaglandin D2 receptor)+. Produce: histamine, LTC4, LTD4, IL-4, IL-13, TSLP upon FcepsilonRI crosslinking. In type 2 immunity: recruited to skin and mucosae during IgE responses; amplify Th2 and ILC2 responses. Mast cells: Origin: bone marrow progenitors (mast cell progenitor, MCp) → enter bloodstream as immature → home to tissues → complete maturation in local tissue under SCF (KIT ligand) signaling. Location: connective tissue throughout the body (skin, gut submucosa, lung, around blood vessels, nerves). Lifespan: months to years. Morphology: round/oval nucleus, cytoplasm packed with metachromatic granules. Two types: MCT (mucosal/IMMC): tryptase only; alpha and beta tryptase; found in intestinal mucosa and lung; IL-3-dependent. MCTC (connective tissue/CTMC): tryptase + chymase + CPA3 + cathepsin G; in skin, submucosa; SCF-dependent. Systemic mastocytosis: KIT D816V activating mutation → clonal mast cell accumulation; Darier's sign (urticaria on stroking skin). c-kit (KIT) receptor: CD117; SCF → KIT → JAK2, PI3K → survival and proliferation.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Basophils and mast cells"},
    {question:"Lymphopoiesis involves the generation of T and B lymphocytes from common lymphoid progenitors. Where do T and B cell maturation occur, and what events define each?",options:{A:"B cells mature in the thymus; T cells mature in the bone marrow; both undergo positive and negative selection",B:"B cell maturation: bone marrow (fetal liver in fetal life). Stages (pro-B → pre-B → immature B → transitional → mature naive B): VDJ recombination of IgH (pro-B), VJ recombination of IgL (pre-B), surface IgM/IgD expression; negative selection eliminates autoreactive B cells (receptor editing then anergy then deletion). T cell maturation: thymus. DN (CD4-CD8-) → TCRbeta rearrangement + allelic exclusion (beta selection) → DP (CD4+CD8+) → TCRalpha rearrangement + TCR expression → positive selection (DP cells expressing TCR that can bind self-MHC peptide survive) → negative selection (DP/SP cells with too-high self-MHC/peptide affinity undergo clonal deletion → central tolerance) → SP CD4+ (class II restricted) or SP CD8+ (class I restricted) T cells exported to periphery"},correct:"B",explanation:"Lymphopoiesis: B cell development (bone marrow): CLP (common lymphoid progenitor) → Pro-B cell: V-to-DJ recombination (heavy chain): RAG1/RAG2 (recombinase activating genes) mediate VDJ recombination at the IgH locus → D-to-J joining first, then V-to-DJ joining; TdT (terminal deoxynucleotidyl transferase) adds N-nucleotides → junctional diversity → mu heavy chain expression. Pre-B cell: successful mu chain (heavy chain) pairs with surrogate light chain (lambda5 + VpreB) → pre-BCR → proliferation and allelic exclusion (prevents second rearrangement). Immature B cell: VJ recombination at IgL locus → kappa then lambda → surface IgM. Negative selection: autoreactive immature B cells → receptor editing (RAG reactivated → new IgL rearrangement) → if still autoreactive → deletion or anergy. Mature naive B: IgM + IgD (alternative splicing). T cell development (thymus): Thymic progenitors (ETPs — early T cell progenitors from bone marrow) enter thymus at corticomedullary junction → cortex. CD44+CD25-CD4-CD8- (DN1) → CD44+CD25+ (DN2): commitment to T lineage, TCRbeta, gamma, delta rearrangement. DN3 (CD44-CD25+): TCRbeta rearrangement; allelic exclusion; beta selection (pre-TCR = TCRbeta + pTalpha + CD3 complex → proliferation + allelic exclusion). DN4 (CD44-CD25-) → DP (CD4+CD8+): TCRalpha rearrangement → mature alphabeta TCR. Positive selection (thymic cortex): DP cells whose TCR binds self-peptide-MHC on cortical thymic epithelial cells (cTECs, expressing unique proteasome and CATH-L — generate unique peptide repertoire) with low-intermediate affinity survive → those binding MHC II → CD4+ T; those binding MHC I → CD8+ T. Failure to bind self-MHC → death by neglect (~95% of thymocytes). Negative selection (thymic medulla): SP cells migrating to the medulla encounter medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTECs, expressing AIRE — autoimmune regulator — which drives ectopic expression of tissue-restricted antigens like insulin, thyroglobulin, IRBP) presenting self-antigens + dendritic cells. High-affinity interactions → clonal deletion (FASL-FAS, Bim-mediated) → central tolerance. Regulatory T cells (Tregs): thymocytes with intermediate-high affinity may become Foxp3+CD25+ natural Tregs instead of deletion. DiGeorge syndrome: TBX1 deletion (22q11.2) → third/fourth pharyngeal pouch failure → thymic aplasia → T cell deficiency.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Lymphopoiesis"},
    {question:"Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) is characterized by the Philadelphia chromosome. What is the molecular defect and how does imatinib work?",options:{A:"CML: t(15;17) creating PML-RARalpha fusion; treated with ATRA (all-trans retinoic acid)",B:"CML: t(9;22)(q34;q11.2) creating the Philadelphia chromosome — BCR (breakpoint cluster region on chr22) fused to ABL1 (Abelson tyrosine kinase on chr9) → BCR-ABL1 fusion oncoprotein (most commonly p210 BCR-ABL1 in CML; p190 in B-cell ALL). BCR-ABL1 is a constitutively active, cytoplasmic tyrosine kinase (ABL1 kinase domain is constitutively in the 'open'/active conformation due to BCR domain dimerization) → activates RAS/MAPK, PI3K/AKT, JAK/STAT5, BCL-XL → uncontrolled myeloid proliferation + inhibited apoptosis. Imatinib (Gleevec, STI571): ATP-competitive inhibitor of BCR-ABL1 kinase → binds the inactive conformation of the ABL1 kinase domain → prevents ATP binding → inhibits BCR-ABL1 phosphorylation of substrates → induces apoptosis → eliminates CML cells; also inhibits PDGFR and KIT (c-KIT)"},correct:"B",explanation:"CML molecular pathogenesis and treatment: CML is a myeloproliferative neoplasm (MPN) of the pluripotent HSC. Philadelphia chromosome (Ph): discovered by Nowell and Hungerford (1960) — the first cancer chromosomal abnormality. Molecular: t(9;22)(q34;q11.2) → Philadelphia chromosome (derivative 22, der(22)) contains the BCR-ABL1 fusion. ABL1 (chromosome 9): a non-receptor tyrosine kinase; normally regulated by SH3-SH2 interdomain interactions (inactive conformation) and nuclear localization. BCR (chromosome 22): BCR coiled-coil (CC) domain in the fusion protein drives ABL1 dimerization → CC domain occludes the SH3 domain intramolecular inhibition → constitutive ABL1 kinase activity. BCR-ABL1 isoforms: p210 (major in CML, minor in ALL): e13a2 or e14a2 junction; p190 (major in Ph+ ALL, minor in CML): e1a2 junction; p230 (rare CML variant). Downstream signaling: RAS-MAPK (proliferation), PI3K-AKT-mTOR (survival), STAT5 (BCL-XL, oncomiR-17-92, proliferation), BCL-XL (antiapoptotic). Imatinib mechanism: ATP-competitive inhibitor of ABL1 (and KIT, PDGFRA, PDGFRB, ARG); binds the catalytic site when ABL1 is in the inactive (DFG-out) conformation → conformational lock → prevents ATP binding → no substrate phosphorylation. Resistance mechanisms: ABL1 kinase domain point mutations (T315I 'gatekeeper' mutation — most resistant; E255K, G250E) → imatinib cannot bind. BCR-ABL1 amplification. Activation of alternative pathways. Treatment of resistance: 2nd generation TKIs (dasatinib, nilotinib — bind slightly different conformations, overcome most mutations); 3rd generation: ponatinib (targets T315I); asciminib (STAMP inhibitor — binds myristoyl pocket, allosteric, most specific ABL1 inhibitor, targets T315I at high dose).",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Leukemia"},
    {question:"The bone marrow biopsy is essential for diagnosing hematological malignancies. What is the difference between a hypercellular and a hypocellular bone marrow, and what conditions cause each?",options:{A:"Hypercellular marrow always indicates malignancy; hypocellular marrow always indicates anemia",B:"Normal marrow cellularity (% hematopoietic cells vs fat): ~age-dependent: roughly [100 - age]% (e.g., 40% at age 60). Hypercellular marrow (cellularity >age-adjusted normal): myeloproliferative neoplasms (CML, PV, ET, MF in early phase), leukemias (AML, ALL), lymphomas involving marrow, reactive conditions (severe hemolytic anemia, iron deficiency with compensatory erythroid hyperplasia, megaloblastic anemia, chronic infection). Hypocellular marrow (cellularity <25-30%): aplastic anemia (immune-mediated HSC destruction — T cell-mediated, responds to ATG + cyclosporine + eltrombopag; or constitutional: Fanconi anemia, Diamond-Blackfan, Shwachman-Diamond), radiation/chemotherapy effect, myelodysplastic syndrome (hypocellular MDS), paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria (PNH), aleukemic leukemia"},correct:"B",explanation:"Bone marrow biopsy interpretation: Trephine biopsy provides the definitive cellularity assessment (aspirate gives morphology/cytogenetics/flow cytometry but cannot assess cellularity or marrow architecture). Cellularity: Hematopoietic cells fill the intertrabecular spaces, with the remainder occupied by adipocytes. The '100 minus age rule' provides a rough normative reference: ~80% at age 20, ~50% at age 50, ~30% at age 70. Hypercellular marrow: Malignant (neoplastic): AML (blasts >20%, CD34+/CD117+/MPO+/CD33+), ALL (blasts >20%, TdT+, CD10+, CD19+ for B-ALL), CML (granulocytic hyperplasia, trilinear hyperplasia + megakaryocyte hyperplasia with increased eosinophils/basophils, Ph+), PV (panmyelosis — trilinear hyperplasia + megakaryocyte pleomorphism + absent iron stores + JAK2 V617F), ET (megakaryocytic hyperplasia with large mature-appearing, hyperlobulated 'stag-horn' megakaryocytes, JAK2/MPL/CALR mutations), MF early (hypercellular with atypical megakaryocytes in clusters → drives fibrosis). Reactive: severe hemolytic anemia → erythroid hyperplasia (E:G ratio >1:1 vs normal 1:3-4); iron deficiency → erythroid hyperplasia + absent iron stores (Prussian blue negative). Hypocellular marrow: Aplastic anemia (AA): <25% cellularity with predominantly fat cells and lymphocytes; three severity grades. Immune AA: aberrant autoreactive T cells (Th1, CTL) attack HSC → mediated by IFN-gamma, TNF-alpha; HLA-DR15 associated; responds to immunosuppression (horse ATG + cyclosporine) in ~60-70%; eltrombopag added to IST improves response. Allogenic BMT curative. Severe AA criteria: <25% cellularity + at least 2 of: neutrophils <0.5×10⁹/L, platelets <20×10⁹/L, reticulocytes <20×10⁹/L.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Bone marrow pathology"},
    {question:"Natural killer (NK) cells are innate lymphoid cells that kill virally infected and tumor cells without prior sensitization. What determines whether NK cells kill a target cell?",options:{A:"NK cells kill all nucleated cells indiscriminately; they only spare cells that express specific 'spare me' surface markers",B:"NK cell activation is regulated by a balance of activating and inhibitory receptors. Inhibitory receptors (KIRs — killer immunoglobulin-like receptors, and CD94/NKG2A heterodimer): recognize self-MHC class I (HLA-A, B, C, E) on normal cells → inhibitory signal → NK cell does NOT kill. Activating receptors (NKG2D, NKp30, NKp44, NKp46): recognize stress ligands upregulated on infected or transformed cells (MICA/MICB — NKG2D ligands; viral hemagglutinin for NCRs). Tumor cells that downregulate MHC class I (to escape CTL killing) lose KIR inhibition → NK cells kill them ('missing self' hypothesis). Cells with stress ligands + reduced MHC I → maximal NK activation"},correct:"B",explanation:"NK cell cytotoxicity regulation: NK cells (CD56+CD3-, CD16+, NKp46+ innate lymphoid cells) survey body tissues for abnormal cells. The key conceptual framework is the balance model: Inhibitory signals (stop killing): Killer immunoglobulin-like receptors (KIRs): Type I transmembrane proteins with Ig-like ectodomains. KIRs recognizing HLA-A/B/C (e.g., KIR2DL1 recognizes HLA-C2, KIR3DL1 recognizes HLA-B Bw4) have ITIM (immunoreceptor tyrosine-based inhibitory motif) in their cytoplasmic tail → SHP-1/SHP-2 phosphatases → dephosphorylate activation substrates → inhibition. CD94/NKG2A heterodimer: lectin-type receptor recognizing HLA-E (which presents leader peptides from classical MHC I) → ITIM → inhibition. Activating signals: NKG2D (C-type lectin-like, associates with DAP10 or DAP12): recognizes MICA, MICB (MHC class I-related chains A and B), and ULBP1-6 (UL16 binding proteins) → induced on cells by heat shock, DNA damage, viral infection, oncogenic transformation. Natural cytotoxicity receptors (NCRs): NKp30 (NCR3), NKp44 (NCR2), NKp46 (NCR1): recognize viral and tumor ligands (viral hemagglutinin, B7H6, heparan sulfate proteoglycans). DNAM-1 (CD226): recognizes PVR (CD155) and Nectin-2 (CD112) — upregulated on tumor cells. Killing mechanisms: (1) Exocytosis of cytolytic granules: perforin (creates pores in target cell membrane) + granzymes A and B (granzyme B activates caspase-3/9 → apoptosis) → directed release (immune synapse). (2) ADCC (antibody-dependent cellular cytotoxicity): CD16a (FcgammaRIIIA) on NK cells binds Fc of IgG bound to target cell → NK activation → killing (mechanism of trastuzumab, rituximab, cetuximab enhancement via Fc). (3) TRAIL and FasL: death receptor-mediated apoptosis. NK cells are critical against CMV, EBV (NK cell deficiency → fatal EBV infection in XLP1/SAP deficiency), and tumor surveillance.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"NK cells"},
    {question:"Hemolytic disease of the fetus and newborn (HDFN) is caused by maternal antibodies crossing the placenta. What is the most common serious form and how does it occur?",options:{A:"HDFN most commonly results from ABO incompatibility with IgM anti-A or anti-B antibodies crossing the placenta",B:"Rh (D) HDFN: most serious form. First pregnancy: Rh-negative mother + Rh-positive fetus → feto-maternal hemorrhage at delivery → RhD antigen exposure → maternal B cell response → IgG anti-D antibodies produced (IgG, not IgM → can cross the placenta via FcRn). Subsequent Rh-positive pregnancy: IgG anti-D crosses placenta → coats fetal Rh-positive RBCs → extravascular hemolysis in fetal spleen (macrophage Fc-mediated) → fetal anemia → erythropoiesis in spleen/liver (extramedullary hematopoiesis → erythroblastosis fetalis) → high-output cardiac failure → fetal hydrops. Prevention: anti-D immunoglobulin (Rho-GAM) given to Rh-negative mothers at 28 weeks and within 72h of delivery/sensitizing event → passive anti-D coats fetal RBCs in maternal circulation → prevents maternal B cell activation (exact mechanism debated: clearance of RhD+ fetal RBCs before sensitization, or direct B cell inhibition via FcgammaRIIB signaling)"},correct:"B",explanation:"Rh HDFN pathogenesis: Rh (Rhesus) blood group system: RhD antigen (encoded by RHCE/RHD genes on chromosome 1p36). RhD is absent in Rh-negative individuals (15% of Caucasians; much rarer in Asians and Africans — different null alleles). Sensitization events that can trigger anti-D response in Rh-negative mothers: Delivery (term or preterm); miscarriage; ectopic pregnancy; amniocentesis; chorionic villus sampling; feto-maternal hemorrhage; blood transfusion. Why first pregnancy is usually spared: the initial sensitization takes time to generate IgG memory cells; the primary response produces mainly IgM (cannot cross placenta). Secondary response in subsequent pregnancies: rapid, high-titer IgG anti-D → crosses placenta via FcRn (neonatal Fc receptor) in syncytiotrophoblast → reaches fetal circulation → binds Rh+ fetal RBCs → splenic macrophages (Fc-mediated extravascular hemolysis) → fetal hemolytic anemia → compensatory erythropoiesis in liver and spleen (hence 'erythroblastosis fetalis' — nucleated RBCs and erythroblasts in blood) → hematopoietic tissue expansion → portal hypertension → hypoalbuminemia → hydrops fetalis (anasarca, ascites, pleural effusion, pericardial effusion — due to low oncotic pressure + anemia + cardiac failure). Antenatal monitoring: MCA (middle cerebral artery) Doppler peak systolic velocity > 1.5 MoM → fetal anemia → intrauterine transfusion. Bilirubin management: unconjugated bilirubin (fat-soluble) → kernicterus (crosses BBB → basal ganglia/cerebellum damage) → phototherapy (converts bilirubin to water-soluble isomers) → exchange transfusion if severe. ABO HDFN: usually mild (anti-A/anti-B IgG can cross placenta — but ABO antigens are not fully developed on fetal RBCs; A and B antigens are widely expressed on other tissues 'absorbing' some IgG); first pregnancy can be affected; mild jaundice.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"HDFN"},
    {question:"Myelodysplastic syndromes (MDS) are clonal hematopoietic stem cell disorders characterized by ineffective hematopoiesis. What are the key histological features in the bone marrow?",options:{A:"MDS bone marrow shows hypocellular marrow with no dysplasia; it is diagnosed only by genetics",B:"MDS bone marrow (trephine biopsy + aspirate smear): (1) Hypercellular marrow (despite peripheral cytopenias — hallmark of 'ineffective hematopoiesis'; cells are produced but die in the marrow before reaching the blood); (2) Dyspoiesis in one or more lineages: erythroid dysplasia (nuclear budding, karyorrhexis, nuclear-cytoplasmic dyssynchrony, ringed sideroblasts — RARS: Prussian blue+ iron-laden mitochondria in a ring around the nucleus, seen in SF3B1-mutated MDS); myeloid dysplasia (hypogranular neutrophils, pseudo-Pelger-Huet cells — bilobed 'pince-nez' nuclei); megakaryocyte dysplasia (micromegakaryocytes, monolobed or hypolobed nuclei, widely separated nuclear lobes); (3) Blasts <20% (if ≥20% = AML); (4) Cytogenetics: del(5q), del(7q), del(20q), trisomy 8, complex karyotype"},correct:"B",explanation:"MDS pathology and classification: MDS are clonal disorders of the HSC (marked by somatic mutations: SF3B1 — most common in MDS-RS; TET2, DNMT3A, ASXL1 — epigenetic regulators; SRSF2 — splicing; RUNX1, TP53 — transcription/checkpoint; NPM1 — sometimes in MDS, more commonly in AML). Key concept: ineffective hematopoiesis — hypercellular marrow + peripheral cytopenias (the two seem contradictory, but elevated intramedullary apoptosis removes cells before they reach the blood; in contrast, aplastic anemia = hypocellular marrow + pancytopenia). WHO 2022 MDS classification (updated from 2016): MDS with defining genetic abnormality: MDS-SF3B1 (ringed sideroblasts, usually low-grade; SF3B1 splicing mutation causes aberrant mitochondrial iron metabolism → ringed sideroblasts); MDS-biallelic TP53 mutation (complex karyotype, poor prognosis). MDS with morphologic abnormality: MDS with low blasts (MDS-LB, <5% blasts); MDS hypoplastic (MDS-h, <25% cellularity); MDS with increased blasts (MDS-IB): IB1 (5-9% blasts), IB2 (10-19% blasts, dismal prognosis → often treated as AML). Ringed sideroblasts: iron-laden mitochondria form a ring (≥5 granules encircling ≥1/3 of nucleus) around the nucleus on Prussian blue staining; require SF3B1 mutation (in ~80%) for the MDS-SF3B1 designation. Dysplasia criteria: ≥10% of cells in a lineage show dysplastic features. Pseudo-Pelger-Huet: acquired bilobed (pince-nez) neutrophil morphology seen in MDS (vs. congenital Pelger-Huet anomaly from heterozygous LBR mutations); associated with del(17p) or del(17q). Treatment: Luspatercept (TGF-beta trap) for MDS-SF3B1 transfusion-dependent; lenalidomide for del(5q); azacitidine (HMA) for higher-risk; allogeneic SCT the only cure.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"MDS"},
    {question:"The coagulation cascade has intrinsic (contact) and extrinsic (tissue factor) pathways. What is the 'cell-based model' of coagulation, and which factors are tested by PT and aPTT?",options:{A:"The classic cascade model is used clinically; the cell-based model has no clinical relevance",B:"Cell-based coagulation model: (1) Initiation: tissue factor (TF, factor III) expressed on subendothelial cells (fibroblasts, smooth muscle) upon vascular injury → binds circulating FVII → TF:FVIIa complex → activates FX and FIX; small amount of thrombin (Ila) generated. (2) Amplification: trace thrombin → activates platelets (PAR1/4), FV (→ FVa), FVIII (→ FVIIIa on platelet surface), FXI. (3) Propagation: on the platelet surface: FIXa + FVIIIa (intrinsic tenase) → large FXa generation; FXa + FVa (prothrombinase) → large thrombin burst → fibrin clot. PT (prothrombin time): tests extrinsic and common pathways (FVII, FX, FV, FII, fibrinogen); prolonged by warfarin, liver disease, FVII deficiency. aPTT (activated partial thromboplastin time): tests intrinsic and common pathways (FXII, XI, IX, VIII, X, V, II, fibrinogen); prolonged by heparin, hemophilia A (FVIII) or B (FIX), lupus anticoagulant"},correct:"B",explanation:"Coagulation system: Cell-based model (Hoffman, 2003) replaced the classic waterfall cascade as the more physiologically accurate model. Three overlapping phases: (1) Initiation (on TF-bearing cells): TF exposed by vessel injury → TF:FVIIa → activates FX (→ FXa) and FIX (→ FIXa). FXa on TF-cell surface + FVa (present on cell surface) → small thrombin (FIIa) burst (insufficient for clot, but critical for amplification). (2) Amplification (on platelet surface): Trace thrombin activates: platelets (via PAR1, PAR4 — protease-activated receptors → platelet activation → GP IIb/IIIa activation → aggregation); FV → FVa; FVIII (normally circulates with VWF) → FVIIIa released from VWF; FXI → FXIa (amplifies further FIX activation); FXIIIa forms crosslinks in fibrin. (3) Propagation (platelet surface, intrinsic tenase and prothrombinase complexes): FIXa (from TF pathway + FXIa) + FVIIIa → intrinsic tenase complex on platelet phosphatidylserine (PS) surface → massive FXa generation; FXa + FVa → prothrombinase complex → massive thrombin burst → fibrinogen (FI) → fibrin monomers → fibrin polymer + FXIIIa crosslinking → stable clot. Clinical tests: PT: tissue factor + CaCl2 added to citrated plasma → time to clot. Tests: FVII (extrinsic, uniquely), FX, FV, FII, fibrinogen (common). Expressed as INR (international normalized ratio) for anticoagulation monitoring (warfarin, vitamin K deficiency). aPTT: phospholipid + contact activator (kaolin, ellagic acid) added to plasma → tests FXII, FXI, FIX, FVIII (intrinsic) + FX, FV, FII, Fbg (common). Prolonged by: unfractionated heparin (UFH, monitors therapy); hemophilia A (FVIII deficiency) or B (FIX deficiency); lupus anticoagulant (phospholipid-dependent — aPTT prolonged in vitro but thrombosis in vivo). Both PT and aPTT prolonged: common pathway defects (FX, FV, FII, fibrinogen), DIC, supratherapeutic anticoagulation.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Coagulation"},
    {question:"Sickle cell disease results from a point mutation in the HBB gene. What is the molecular mechanism of HbS polymerization and what are the complications of vaso-occlusion?",options:{A:"HbS has a deletion of the entire beta-globin gene; oxygen binding is reduced but polymerization does not occur",B:"HbS: Glu6Val mutation in the beta-globin gene (HBB, chromosome 11p15.4) → valine (hydrophobic) replaces glutamate (hydrophilic) → on deoxygenation, the beta-6 Val inserts into a hydrophobic acceptor pocket (formed by beta-85 Phe and beta-88 Leu on an adjacent HbS molecule) → staggered, double-stranded helical polymer of HbS tetramers → elongated polymer → deforms RBC into sickle shape → ↑ viscosity + occludes microvessels. Complications: vaso-occlusive pain crises (bone, chest, abdomen), acute chest syndrome (pulmonary vaso-occlusion → most common cause of death), stroke (large vessel + small vessel), splenic sequestration and autosplenectomy (functional asplenia → encapsulated organisms: Streptococcus pneumoniae, H. influenzae, N. meningitidis), priapism, avascular necrosis (femoral head), chronic kidney disease (renal medullary infarction, sickle cell nephropathy), pulmonary hypertension, retinopathy"},correct:"B",explanation:"Sickle cell disease molecular pathogenesis: HbS (alpha2-betaS2): the single nucleotide change GAG→GTG (codon 6) creates the hydrophobic valine that drives polymerization. Key factors affecting polymerization: (1) Deoxy-HbS concentration: high intracellular HbS concentration drives polymer formation exponentially; (2) Oxygen saturation: low PO2 → deoxy-HbS → polymerization; HbF (fetal hemoglobin, alpha2gamma2): inhibits polymerization (gamma chain CANNOT enter the acceptor pocket) → patients with high HbF (via HPFH or induced by hydroxyurea) have milder disease; (3) Temperature: fever accelerates sickling; (4) Cellular dehydration: dehydrated RBCs have higher HbS concentration → more polymerization → Gardos channel (KCNN4) inhibitor (senicapoc) aimed to prevent dehydration. Vaso-occlusion pathogenesis: Not only polymerization — adhesion is key. Sickle cells and reticulocytes express VLA-4 (alpha4beta1) and CD44 → adhere to VCAM-1 on inflamed endothelium; also interact with VWF and ICAM-1. Polymerized cells + adherent cells → capillary occlusion → ischemia-reperfusion → ROS → more inflammation. Therapies: Hydroxyurea: ribonucleotide reductase inhibitor → induces HbF (by inducing stress erythropoiesis/gamma-globin gene expression via unknown TF) → reduces polymer frequency; also reduces WBC (reduces adhesion molecules). L-glutamine: reduces oxidative stress, approved 2017. Crizanlizumab (anti-P-selectin): prevents sickle RBC adhesion to endothelium. Voxelotor (GBT440, Oxbryta): allosteric HbS oxygen affinity modifier (keeps HbS in oxy-conformation, resists polymerization). Curative: gene therapy (BetaGene/Zynteglo — lentiviral gamma-globin; Casgevy — CRISPR/Cas9 BCL11A enhancer knockout → HbF reactivation) or allogeneic HSC transplantation.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Hemoglobinopathy"},
    {question:"Multiple myeloma is a plasma cell neoplasm characterized by monoclonal immunoglobulin production. What are the key diagnostic criteria and pathological features?",options:{A:"Multiple myeloma diagnosis requires only an elevated serum protein electrophoresis (SPEP) M-spike; bone marrow biopsy is not required",B:"Multiple myeloma (MM) diagnostic criteria (IMWG 2014): clonal bone marrow plasma cells ≥10% OR biopsy-proven plasmacytoma PLUS at least one CRAB criterion (Calcium elevated >11 mg/dL, Renal failure Cr >2 mg/dL or CrCl <40, Anemia Hb <10, Bone lesions — lytic lesions on CT/PET-CT) OR one biomarker: bone marrow clonal PCs ≥60%, sFLC ratio ≥100, >1 focal lesion on MRI. Histology: sheets of plasma cells (CD138+/syndecan-1, CD38+, MUM1/IRF4+, monotypic cytoplasmic Ig by ISH/IHC, CD19-, CD20-usually); EM: abundant rER ('cartwheel' nucleus), Russell bodies (condensed Ig in cytoplasm, pink-red PAS+), Dutcher bodies (intranuclear Ig). Complications: lytic bone lesions (RANKL from myeloma cells → osteoclast activation, SOST/sclerostin → osteoblast inhibition), AL amyloidosis (lambda light chain deposition → Congo red+), cast nephropathy (Bence-Jones protein → tubular obstruction → 'myeloma kidney')"},correct:"B",explanation:"Multiple myeloma histopathology and criteria: MM is a neoplastic plasma cell disorder, arising from the germinal center (post-GC B cells that have undergone somatic hypermutation and class-switch recombination). BM plasma cells: normally <5%; in MGUS (monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance) 3-9%; in smoldering MM 10-60%; in MM ≥10% with end-organ damage. Plasma cell histology: eccentric nucleus with 'clock-face' (cartwheel) heterochromatin pattern; abundant basophilic cytoplasm (abundant rER for Ig synthesis); perinuclear 'hof' (pale Golgi zone). Russell bodies: large, eosinophilic, PAS+ globular inclusions of condensed immunoglobulin in the ER → when they fill the cell = Mott cell (soap bubble appearance); Dutcher bodies = intranuclear Ig inclusions (technically PAS+ intranuclear pockets). IHC panel: CD138+ (syndecan-1, the defining plasma cell marker), CD38+ (SLAMF7, target of daratumumab/elotuzumab), CD79a+ (weakly), MUM1/IRF4+, cIg kappa or lambda (monotypic by ISH/IHC — demonstrates clonality), PAX5-, CD19- (unlike normal plasma cells which may retain some CD19), CD20 variably; CD56 expression is a negative prognostic marker (loss of CD56 in circulating plasma cell leukemia). Genetics/prognosis: FISH for t(4;14) (FGFR3/MMSET), t(14;16) (c-MAF), t(11;14) (cyclin D1, the most common), del(17p13) (TP53 — worst), del(13q14 — RB1), amp(1q21) (CKS1B). High-risk: t(4;14), t(14;16), t(14;20), del(17p), amp(1q), complex karyotype. Treatment: proteasome inhibitors (bortezomib, carfilzomib, ixazomib), IMiDs (thalidomide, lenalidomide, pomalidomide), anti-CD38 mAbs (daratumumab), BCMA-targeted CAR-T cells (idecabtagene vicleucel, ciltacabtagene autoleucel), autologous SCT.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Plasma cell neoplasm"},
    {question:"Diffuse large B cell lymphoma (DLBCL) is the most common aggressive lymphoma. What are the two molecular subtypes defined by gene expression profiling and their clinical significance?",options:{A:"DLBCL has no molecular subtypes; all cases are treated identically with chemotherapy",B:"DLBCL is divided by gene expression profiling into: GCB (germinal center B cell) subtype: BCL6+, CD10+, CD20+; BCL2 translocation t(14;18) from the GC B cell of origin; BCL6 translocations; EZH2 mutations (gain-of-function); better prognosis with R-CHOP (rituximab + cyclophosphamide + doxorubicin + vincristine + prednisone), overall survival ~60%. ABC (activated B cell) subtype: MUM1/IRF4+, CD20+; chronic active BCR signaling (CD79B/MYD88 mutations → NF-kB pathway activation); CARD11 mutations; poorer prognosis, ~40% OS with R-CHOP. Double/triple hit lymphoma (DHL/THL): concurrent MYC/BCL2/BCL6 rearrangements → 'high-grade B cell lymphoma'; extremely poor prognosis; treated with intensive regimens (R-DA-EPOCH)"},correct:"B",explanation:"DLBCL molecular classification: DLBCL is defined as a diffuse proliferation of large B cells (>2x the size of a normal lymphocyte) replacing normal lymph node architecture. Cell of origin (COO) classification by gene expression profiling (GEP, Hans algorithm by IHC surrogates): GCB DLBCL: Originates from or resembles a germinal center B cell. IHC pattern (Hans algorithm): CD10+ OR BCL6+/MUM1- = GCB. BCL2 translocation t(14;18)(q32;q21): BCL2 juxtaposed to IgH enhancer → BCL2 overexpression → antiapoptotic; this translocation is common in follicular lymphoma that transforms to DLBCL. EZH2 gain-of-function mutations (Y641, A677) → histone H3K27 trimethylation → gene silencing → promotes GC B cell expansion. SGK1, TNFRSF14, CREBBP, KMT2D mutations also enriched in GCB. ABC DLBCL: Resembles post-GC activated B cells. IHC: MUM1+ AND (CD10- AND BCL6- or BCL6+) = ABC by Hans. Characterized by: chronic active BCR (B cell receptor) signaling → BTK-mediated NF-kB activation. Key mutations: MYD88 L265P (in ~29%): activates TLR-IRAK4-NF-kB; CD79A/B ITAM mutations: prevent BCR internalization → prolonged BCR signaling; CARD11 (mutations in linker domain → constitutive MALT1/BCL10/CARD11 complex → NF-kB); also BCL2 amplification (not translocation) in many ABC cases. Ibrutinib (BTK inhibitor) plus R-CHOP improves outcomes in ABC-DLBCL (not GCB) — confirmed in PHOENIX trial in younger patients. Double-hit lymphoma (DHL): concurrent translocations of MYC (Burkitt gene) + BCL2 and/or BCL6 → high-grade aggressive; IHC surrogates: MYC protein >40% cells + BCL2 >50% cells = 'double expressor lymphoma' (DEL, poor prognosis even without actual DHL). DEL ≠ DHL (must confirm rearrangements by FISH). R-DA-EPOCH or similar intensive regimens used for DHL.",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Lymphoma"},
    {question:"Von Willebrand disease (VWD) is the most common inherited bleeding disorder. What is the role of von Willebrand factor (VWF) in hemostasis?",options:{A:"VWF activates the extrinsic (tissue factor) coagulation pathway; VWD causes thrombosis, not bleeding",B:"VWF (a large, multimeric glycoprotein synthesized by endothelial cells in Weibel-Palade bodies and by megakaryocytes in alpha-granules): two functions in hemostasis: (1) Platelet adhesion: at sites of vascular injury, subendothelial collagen (types I, III) is exposed → VWF binds collagen (via A3 domain) → VWF undergoes conformational change (uncoiling) under high shear stress → exposes the A1 domain → binds GPIb-alpha (GPIb/IX/V complex) on platelets → tethering of platelets to subendothelium (required for normal platelet plug formation); (2) FVIII carrier: VWF binds FVIII in plasma (1:1 complex) → protects FVIII from proteolytic degradation → VWF deficiency leads to secondary FVIII deficiency. Type 1 VWD (most common, ~75%): quantitative partial deficiency; mild bleeding. Type 2 VWD: qualitative defects. Type 3: complete absence of VWF, severe"},correct:"B",explanation:"VWF biology and VWD: VWF gene (chromosome 12p13.3): 52 exons; pseudogene on chromosome 22. Synthesis: endothelial cells (Weibel-Palade bodies — elongated, rod-shaped secretory organelles; store VWF, P-selectin, angiopoietin-2) and megakaryocytes (alpha-granules of platelets). VWF is synthesized as pre-pro-VWF → glycosylation and dimerization in the ER (C-terminal disulfide bonds) → propeptide (VWF D1D2 domains) aids multimerization in the Golgi (N-terminal disulfide bonds of multiple dimers) → stored as ultra-large VWF (UL-VWF) multimers in Weibel-Palade bodies; cleaved extracellularly by ADAMTS13 (a disintegrin and metalloprotease with thrombospondin type 1 motifs) → normal circulating multimers. VWF functions: Platelet adhesion: high shear stress causes VWF to unfurl from globular to extended 'fishing line' conformation → exposes A1 domain → binds GPIb-alpha. This is particularly important in arteries and arterioles (high shear). FVIII carrier: VWF binds non-covalently to FVIII in plasma (D' domain of VWF + A2 domain of FVIII) → protects from FXa, activated protein C, and TFPI proteolysis; VWF-FVIII complex half-life: ~12h vs ~1h for free FVIII. VWD types: Type 1 (~70-80%): partial quantitative deficiency; AD; VWF <50 IU/dL; ristocetin cofactor assay (VWF:RCo) reduced; FVIII mildly reduced; treated with DDAVP (desmopressin → releases VWF from Weibel-Palade bodies) or VWF concentrate. Type 2A: absent large/intermediate multimers (gain-of-function mutations in A2 domain → increased ADAMTS13 cleavage; or loss-of-function in A2 domain preventing multimer assembly). Type 2B: gain-of-function A1 domain → spontaneously binds GPIb → platelet aggregation → thrombocytopenia + loss of large multimers (AVOID DDAVP — worsens thrombocytopenia). Type 2M: reduced platelet binding without multimer loss. Type 2N: FVIII binding defect (mimics hemophilia A, but AR). Type 3: severe complete absence of VWF → very low FVIII → severe bleeding. Lab: BT (bleeding time) or PFA-100 (platelet function analyzer) prolonged; aPTT prolonged (due to FVIII↓); VWF:Ag, VWF:RCo reduced; FVIII:C reduced. ADAMTS13 deficiency → TTP (UL-VWF accumulates → platelet thrombi in microvessels).",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"VWF"},
    {question:"The spleen is the largest secondary lymphoid organ. What is the functional significance of the red and white pulp, and how does autosplenectomy occur in sickle cell disease?",options:{A:"The red pulp is responsible for T cell responses; the white pulp contains red blood cell sinusoids for filtering",B:"White pulp: lymphoid tissue organized around the central arteriole (periarteriolar lymphoid sheath, PALS — predominantly CD4+ T cells; surrounded by lymphoid follicles — B cell zones with primary and secondary follicles; marginal zone — B cells that respond to T-independent polysaccharide antigens). Red pulp: venous sinusoids and pulp cords (of Billroth); old/damaged RBCs must pass through the narrow (1-2 micron) slits between the sinus lining cells and the fibrous trabeculae → rigid, damaged, or spherocytic RBCs cannot deform → trapped and phagocytosed by macrophages → 'culling.' Autosplenectomy in SCD: repeated vaso-occlusive crises in the spleen → splenic infarction → fibrosis → progressive loss of splenic function → functional asplenia by age 5 → susceptibility to encapsulated bacteria requiring opsonization (complement, IgG) + splenic macrophage phagocytosis"},correct:"B",explanation:"Splenic anatomy and function: Gross structure: capsule → trabeculae (structural support) → splenic parenchyma. White pulp (~25% of splenic mass): organized lymphoid tissue; PALS (periarteriolar lymphoid sheath): surrounds central arteriole; predominantly T cells (CD4+ > CD8+). Follicles (adjacent to PALS): primary (resting, small naive B cells) or secondary (with GC). Marginal zone: at the border of white and red pulp; marginal zone B cells (CD21+, CD35+, CD23-) respond to T-independent antigens (polysaccharides, LPS) → produce IgM quickly without GC reaction → important for early response to encapsulated bacteria. Marginal zone macrophages and dendritic cells sample the blood for antigens. Red pulp (~75% of splenic mass): sinusoids (vascular channels lined by specialized flattened 'stave cells' with fenestrations between them) and pulp cords (of Billroth) — reticular meshwork containing macrophages. RBC filtration: RBCs must squeeze through 1-2 micron slits between sinus-lining cells → requires high RBC deformability (maintained by spectrin-actin cytoskeleton integrity). Damaged, aged (reduced deformability from oxidized band 3), spherocytic, sickled, Heinz body-containing, or IgG/complement-coated RBCs cannot deform → trapped in cords → phagocytosed by cord macrophages ('culling'). Also 'pitting' function: removes intracellular inclusions (Howell-Jolly bodies — nuclear remnants; Heinz bodies — denatured Hb; Pappenheimer bodies — iron granules; malaria parasites) without destroying the RBC. SCD autosplenectomy: repeated sickle-related vaso-occlusion in the spleen → progressive splenic infarction (spleen converts from large in infancy due to sequestration crises to small, fibrotic, non-functional by age 5-8 in homozygous SCD) → Howell-Jolly bodies visible on PBS (nuclear remnants no longer pitted) → functional asplenia → bacteremia from S. pneumoniae, H. influenzae type b, N. meningitidis → sepsis. Prophylaxis: penicillin prophylaxis (until age 5 minimum, many centers continue lifelong) + vaccinations (PCV, PPV23, Hib, MenACWY, MenB).",topic:"Blood & Hematopoiesis",subtopic:"Spleen"}
  ];

