    explanation: "Primary neurulation is initiated by the notochord (derived from axial mesoderm) signaling to the overlying ectoderm. The two key notochordal signals are: (1) Sonic hedgehog (Shh) — secreted by the notochord to induce ventral neural tube structures (floor plate, motor neurons), and (2) BMP antagonists (Noggin, Chordin, Follistatin) — these diffusible proteins bind and block BMP4/BMP2 in the overlying ectoderm. BMP signaling normally drives ectoderm toward epidermal fate; when BMPs are blocked by Noggin/Chordin from the notochord (and later from the floor plate), the ectoderm defaults to neural plate fate (neuroectoderm). This neural induction model is the 'default model' of neural induction. The neural plate folds at the neural folds and fuses at the dorsal midline to form the neural tube (~day 18-28, cranial neuropore closes at ~day 25, caudal at ~day 28). Neural tube defects (NTDs) result from failure of this closure — failure of cranial neuropore: anencephaly; failure of caudal neuropore: spina bifida. Folic acid supplementation reduces NTD risk by supplying methyl groups for one-carbon metabolism needed for neural tube closure. Wnt3a (C) provides posterior neural tube identity (caudalizing gradient) but is not the primary neural inducer. BMP4 (A) promotes epidermal fate, not neural.",
