    explanation: "The sliding filament theory (Huxley and Hanson, 1954) proposes that muscle contraction results from thick and thin filaments sliding past each other without changing their individual lengths. This explains the ultrastructural changes during contraction: (1) A-band: corresponds to the length of thick (myosin) filaments (~1.6 micrometers) — this remains CONSTANT during contraction because myosin filament length does not change. (2) I-band: the region containing only thin (actin) filaments bisected by the Z-disc — this SHORTENS and disappears at maximal contraction, as thin filaments slide fully into the A-band. (3) H-zone: the central region of the A-band containing only thick filaments (no overlap) — this SHORTENS as thin filaments slide inward from both Z-discs and eventually disappear when thin filaments from opposite halves meet at the M-line; at maximal contraction the H-zone is absent. (4) Sarcomere (Z-to-Z) length decreases. (5) Z-discs move closer together. Key evidence for this model: (1) A-band length is constant in contracting vs. relaxed muscle (EM measurement); (2) I-band and H-zone change with contraction state; (3) stiffness of muscle increases with activation (cross-bridges form), supporting mechanical coupling. The cross-bridge cycle: myosin S1 head (in rigor state, bound to actin) releases when ATP binds; ATP is hydrolyzed (forming ADP+Pi, putting S1 in 'cocked' position); S1 rebinds actin (weak binding) and Pi release causes the power stroke (force-generating conformational change); ADP is released; rigor state restored.",
